<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Currency movements hit S&amp;N in opening
quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SMITH &amp; NEPHEW, the healthcare and medical products group, reported pre-tax
profits down 8 per cent, from Pounds 29.5m to Pounds 27.2m, for the first
quarter of 1991.
Adverse currency movements reduced the outcome by about Pounds 2.5m.
But Mr Eric Kinder, chairman, issued a confident statement with the results.
'Overall our trading in the first quarter was on plan and sales showed
continuing underlying growth,' he said. 'Despite weaknesses in many of the
world's economies our core businesses continue to perform well.'
Turnover for the three months was almost unchanged at Pounds 171.5m.
Excluding the effect of exchange rates and the disposal of the Watson Marlow
infusion pump business, underlying growth was 10 per cent.
Sales and profits of medical products such as wound dressings and bandages
'continued their excellent growth in continental Europe and the US.' Sales
to UK hospitals were still constrained by the shortage of cash in the
National Health Service. Profits from manufacturing specialised gloves began
to recover, following last year's decision to withdraw from the loss-making
examination gloves business.
The UK consumer business - including brands such as Nivea, Elastoplast,
Lillets and Dr White's - suffered from the recession, with sales and profits
lower than a year ago.
</TEXT>
