<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Maxwell's Pounds 142.5m offer for sale
closes oversubscribed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLARE PEARSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Pounds 142.5m offer for sale of Mr Robert Maxwell's Mirror Group
Newspapers was oversubscribed when it closed yesterday morning.
Members of the public accounted for at least 100,000 of the applications for
shares in the company, which owns the Daily and Sunday Mirror and other
newspaper titles.
Advisers to the offer yesterday estimated that the overall UK subscription
was not likely to have been higher than 1.5 times the 114m shares on offer.
But receiving bankers had not yet arrived at an exact level.
It was thought that the public had asked to buy up to two thirds of the
shares available, with institutions accounting for the balance of the
applications.
Through the UK offer and a separate overseas placing, Mr Maxwell is selling
49 per cent of the company to raise Pounds 245.5m.
There was speculation yesterday that part of the demand for the UK offer may
have come from overseas institutions which had been unable to obtain as many
shares as they wanted via the international placings.
This followed reports by Salomon Brothers, lead manager for the sale outside
the UK, of strong demand especially from the US.
Basis of allocation would be announced once counting of applications had
been completed, said Samuel Montagu, financial adviser to the flotation.
</TEXT>
