<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Pretoria and ANC move to end township violence: Mandela and
de Klerk reach a 'broad consensus' on measures aimed at halting the
bloodshed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE SOUTH African govern-ment and the African National Congress have reached
outline agreement on measures to end violence in black townships, only hours
before the ANC had threatened to pull out of talks on the country's
political future.
The agreement, which has still to be finalised, represents the best hope yet
of halting violence which has left nearly 10,000 people dead in black
townships since 1984.
According to a statement released last night by the government, 'broad
consensus' was reached on most issues after six hours of talks on Wednesday
night between President FW de Klerk and Mr Nelson Mandela, deputy president
of the ANC.
Officials from the two sides met yesterday to finalise details of the
agreement, which involves a ban on the carrying of almost all so-called
'traditional weapons' in public.
The statement said some remaining issues required further discussion, with
talks to take place urgently. Those close to the talks said disputes over
details - such as the convening of a planned conference on violence - could
still sabotage a formal agreement.
But there was no sign last night that the ANC intended to carry out its
threat to boycott talks on a post-apartheid constitution, at least while
negotiations continue.
In an ultimatum issued last month, it had set a May 9 deadline for agreement
on measures to end violence.
Flexibility from Pretoria on the issue of 'traditional weapons' appears to
have made it possible to avert deadlock.
The Inkatha Freedom Party claims that Zulu culture requires the carrying of
weapons such as knobkerries (clubs), assegais (spears) and pangas (machetes)
at certain gatherings. But the sight of Zulus marching through black
townships armed with such weapons has provoked confrontation, leading to
hundreds of deaths.
In a meeting on Tuesday, Mr de Klerk appears to have forced the Zulu leader,
Chief Mangosuthu Buthelezi, to agree that all such weapons apart from spears
should be banned. Carrying such weapons in designated 'unrest areas' will
now be prohibited while legislation covering the country as a whole will be
reviewed.
The statement made clear that agreement had yet to be reached on what
constituted a cultural occasion at which spears could be carried and whether
party political meetings qualified. It also indicated the two sides had
failed to finalise arrangements to convene a multi-party conference on
violence.
Pretoria had said it would convene such a conference on May 24 and 25, but
this was rejected by the ANC; the meeting now looks likely to be hosted
jointly by the ANC, Inkatha and the government, under the auspices of a
multi-denominational group of church leaders.
Compromise has been reached, either before or during the talks, on six of
seven demands contained in the ANC's ultimatum. So far, Pretoria has refused
to act on the last one, the sacking of two ministers - General Magnus Malan
at defence and Mr Adriaan Vlok at law and order.
The statement said Mr de Klerk reiterated 'the standing policy of government
requiring professionalism and the absolute impartiality of the police in
maintaining law and order, in protecting lives and property and in crowd
control'.
The latest agreement itself may do little to achieve peace, however, until
bilateral contact is resumed between the ANC and Inkatha, which severed
relations last month. Although an obstacle to constitutional talks appears
to have been removed, there is also likely to be little progress on this
until the ANC has elected a new leadership at its planned national
conference in July.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
