<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Letter: Competition in telecommunications
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr KENNETH P ARMITAGE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Hugo Dixon's 'A Failed Connection' (May 8) is an excellent resume of the
apparent stalemate, vis-a-vis the government's white paper on
telecommunications deregulation in the UK, and the subsequent 'flurry of
inactivity' since its publication.
Perhaps, despite its stated policy of introducing competition, the
government is dragging its feet to safeguard the value of its shareholding
in BT.
The point is that if any real competition is to be encouraged to provide
alternate telecommunication networks, and thereby provide choice to the
customers, then problems associated with access connection charges must be
resolved at the earliest opportunity and not by any interim solution until
1993.
The local networks around towns and cities were already in place before BT
was privatised and, while some may be in need of replacement now and in the
future, the cost of new network cabling should not have to be borne entirely
by the alternative service network operators as currently appears to be
suggested. Therefore, any charge for connection to BT local networks should
be restricted to a conveyance fee only.
One must question whether government really is committed to providing
telecommunication network customers with choice.
Kenneth P Armitage,
29 Stoneham Close,
Petersfield,
Hants.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
