<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Letter: Not amused
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr PETER MORGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I sympathised with your leader ('No FT, no comrades', May 3). The
Institute of Directors also featured in that Wednesday night party political
broadcast by the Labour party, with the implication that any criticism of
government policy means support for the Labour party.
It is perhaps no coincidence that in the speech of mine to which Labour
referred in the broadcast, I too had quoted, with approval, Mr Samuel
Brittan's remark: 'Unfortunately, it is still not possible for market
economists to support Labour with a straight face.'
The IoD can certainly see nothing to laugh at in socialist policies. Under
socialism we are promised higher taxation, not lower taxation; public
intervention, not private initiative, public capital, not private capital;
renationalisation, not privatisation and regulation rather than
deregulation.
No one should think that the IoD supports socialism.
Peter Morgan,
director-general,
Institute of Directors,
110 Pall Mall, SW1
</TEXT>
