<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Letter: Support for the TUC's national economic assessment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr DAVID LEA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, John Gapper's report on the Usdaw conference ('Usdaw votes for and
against pay restraint policy', May 1) stated, with reference to the national
economic assessment, that 'opposition to the idea in the TUC has been led by
the AEU engineering union'.
Your readers should be aware that, while the AEU sought changes to the first
draft of the document, in the course of a debate at the TUC general council
on April 26 unanimity was reached on the content of a TUC statement on
collective bargaining, including a section clearly setting out the role of
the national economic assessment.
The only amendment to the draft being considered by the general council was
moved by Bill Jordan, president of the AEU, and seconded by Rodney
Bickerstaffe, chairman of the economic committee and general secretary of
the National Union of Public Employees.
This was incorporated in the text and the statement was then adopted
unanimously.
David Lea,
assistant general secretary,
Trades Union Congress,
Congress House,
Great Russell Street WC1B 3LS
</TEXT>
