<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Letter: Partnership can deliver vocational education
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr JOHN SELLARS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Regarding your report 'Agency attacks funding of courses' (May 2), your
readers will be interested to hear of further developments in our
relationship with the Training and Enterprise Councils (Tecs) and the
progress of the government's programme to develop vocational education.
I reported to the select committee on employment that a successful working
partnership has been established with the National Council for Vocational
Qualifications (NCVQ), leading to recent accreditation for some of our
courses. The first diploma in business and finance - to introduce vocational
education into schools - was accredited last month.
NCVQ accreditation is the key to recognition by the Tecs for funding
purposes. Our courses need NCVQ accreditation to gain listing by the
Training, Enterprise and Education Division (TEED). This listing in turn
frees Tecs to fund students on BTEC-validated vocational courses.
My comments about the need for a national strategy for vocational education
were made in support of the present government's, and indeed the
opposition's, declared intention to put in place a system of vocational
education which is linked to vocational training in the workplace.
We welcome the prospect of a white paper from the Department of Education
and Science on education for 16-19-year-olds. We anticipate that it is
likely to create the second pillar of a national strategy which will link
schools and colleges with the activities of the 82 Tecs.
An especially welcome development from BTEC's point of view is the growing
consensus across the political spectrum in favour of vocationally-based
education. We believe that the successful delivery of a national vocational
education system can only be achieved if there is a positive partnership
between education and employers, with government giving the lead.
John Sellars,
chief executive,
Business and Technician
Education Council,
Central House,
Upper Woburn Place, WC1
</TEXT>
