<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Leading Article: How to control pay at the top
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
AS SO often over the past few years, the late spring spate of annual reports
is proving open season for people to snipe at the large sums of money which
many top managers are paid these days, on both sides of the Atlantic. This
year, unusually, some good may come of all the criticism.
There are several reasons why this year's brouhaha is different in
character. First and foremost, for the first time since the early 1980s,
revelation of some sharply rising mega-salaries comes against an almost
universal backdrop of falling profits.
Second, many of the same companies are also expecting lesser managers and
employees to moderate their salary and wage claims sharply in the face of
the recession. Third, some of the companies have suffered especially
embarrassing business failures.
Fourth, some of this year's toughest sniping is coming from insiders: late
last month the head of the British Institute of Management laid into UK
directors for increasing their pay but reducing that of their managers for
the first time since 1984. He warned that this might 'damage the
relationship on which good leadership is based'.
A further reason for the pitch of this year's debate is the salutary example
of so many of yesterday's highest paid (and supposedly best performing)
executive stars biting the dust.
Finally, it is becoming crystal clear that the issue is not just one of
basic salary and bonuses, but also of a bevy of other benefits: extra
pay-offs to departing directors, big adjustments to pension benefits and
housing subsidies.
Performance incentives
Some of the criticism contains a degree of both exaggeration and delusion.
The idea that top directors of large UK companies are always paid at
astronomic rates is by no means borne out by all the available surveys. Some
have also taken big pay cuts in the latest 12 months.
Nor is the concurrence of slumping corporate profits with sharp pay rises
for directors always as illogical as it seems: a growing proportion of top
executive pay, especially in the US, is rightly based on medium or long-term
performance incentives, which at present relate back to better years: in
1991, they reach back to 1989 or even earlier.
US counterparts
Then there is the much-touted global (or at least transatlantic) market for
top executives which, it is often argued, means that British bosses'
earnings should grow even closer to those of their US counterparts. In
direct terms, this factor applies only to certain international industries;
it can hardly be claimed, even indirectly, to be a justifiable factor behind
remuneration levels at UK insurance companies and building societies, for
instance.
In recent years, the most popular prescription for improving the control of
top executive pay has been to give more power to non-executive directors and
corporate audit committees; that view was expressed again last month by
Britain's Institutional Shareholders Committee.
Such an approach is inadequate. Audit committees run by 'independent'
non-executive directors (a questionable concept in itself) certainly have an
important role to play. But, in the US, company boards with a majority of
non-executive directors, plus the high prevalence of audit committees, have
not solved the problem.
The most effective solution would be to force public companies to create
much greater transparency in the service contracts which they give their
main board directors. Current legislation allowing shareholders to search
out such information at short notice should be strengthened by requiring
companies to send details of every such package (existing and proposed) to
all shareholders, and thereby to the public, well in advance of the annual
general meeting, at which all packages should be voted upon.
Few shareholders take much interest in these issues at present, but a
requirement for full disclosure and approval, plus all the attendant
publicity, would create much more effective pressure on companies.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 14
</PAGE>
