<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Arts: Tokyo &amp; Endellion Quartets - Queen Elizabeth and
Wigmore Halls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The qualities of the Tokyo Quartet are rare and precious: tone as supple as
fine leather, each note precisely directed, each line drawn taut with an
athlete's muscular control, the ensemble faultless in blend and balance. In
a Tokyo concert one soon learns to take for granted standards of execution
out of the reach of all but a few quartets; but the quest for technical
exactitude no longer inhibits the artistic freedom of the performances as in
the early days of the group's existence it sometimes seemed to.
The conversational side of Tokyo quartet-readings has blossomed; the four
players achieve both unanimity of purpose and individuality of character. In
Monday's South Bank recital their Beethoven (Op. 18 no. 1, in F) and Mozart
(K575, in D) made for a gripping first half. Neither performance could be
described as 'European', or steeped in the manners of the 18th century:
there was little intimation of the Haydn-like sleights-of-hand that
Beethoven was setting out to equal (or even outdo), and, in the Mozart,
little attempt to search out nuances of gentle wit or smiling suggestiveness
beneath the courtly facade.
In the performances of less remarkable quartet-groups these limitations
might be regretted. Because the Tokyo playing was so strong and so masterly,
one accepted the style on its own terms - without qualification, with
pleasure and admiration. A similar experience was offered by the Brahms
Piano Quintet after the interval, with Barry Douglas a virtuoso pianist
unfailingly sensitive to his string-playing partners. It was not subtly hued
Brahms, shaded with nostalgia, hesitation, and regret; but it was definite,
superbly disciplined, and ringingly powerful.
The Endellion Quartet is this month embarked on a Wigmore Hall Beethoven
cycle. The first instalment, on Wednesday, was very much a mixed bag: even
after one had succeeded in drumming the long-lined beauty of the Tokyo sound
out of mind and memory, it did seem that the players were falling prey to an
unusual amount of technical flaws (the intonation of the leader, Andrew
Watkinson, can prove alarmingly insecure under pressure).
What's more, and in contradiction of the Endellion's current high standing
among English quartets, it was hard to gain any impression of real purchase
upon Beethovenian musical argument. The C minor (Op. 18 no. 4) was
unremittingly bland, the 'Harp' (Op. 74) uncomfortably out of focus; and
even though in the big B flat, Op. 130 (given with Beethoven's revised
finale), there was greater evidence of technical control and tonal
consistency, no 'long view' was presented to the listener. One hopes later
concerts in this cycle will more convincingly explain why the Endellion
decided to embark on one.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 13
</PAGE>
