<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Do you believe black entertainers are so hopelessly inferior that, without
the help of special separatist enclaves which bar white participants, they
will never make it onto television? If so, how do you explain the success of
Shirley Bassey and Lenny Henry, Tina Turner and MC Hammer, Derek Griffiths
and Floella Benjamin, Rusty Lee and Gary Wilmot, Willard White and Jessye
Norman, and dozens of other black comedians, actors and musicians who seem
to have triumphed without any such system? The mystery is why broadcasting
bosses keep on setting up these insultingly condescending series and why
self respecting black people don't boycott them. Latest in the deeply
patronising tradition is The Real McCoy (9.00 BBC2). If this had been
invented in South Africa Britain's broadcasters would have risen as one man
and reviled it.
BBC1 mounts a campaign with a difference: instead of appealing for money
Light The Darkness (10.20) appeals for people and governments to observe the
provisions of the Geneva Convention.
</TEXT>
