<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Arts: Pal Joey - Bristol Old Vic
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ST GEORGE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rodgers and Hart's Pal Joey (1940) was thought obscene when it transferred
to London from New York in 1954. It was doctored for the English censor, and
then further diluted into the anodyne film version: Columbia excised the
social and sexual comment by turning it into the story of a heel (Sinatra)
and two women (Hayworth and Novack). The original is a dark tale of
exploitation and ideals, and it has been delivered accurately and
energetically in a fine production at the Old Vic.
The English have never evolved an equivalent of the American musical. The
genre combines felt realities with hoped-for dreams, staples from Showboat
to West Side Story. But this strain in American music has been developed
away from the stage by Paul Simon ('American Tune') and Randy Newman ('Land
of Dreams'). The English revival of a Rodgers-Hart musical now tells us
about our own times. This production of Pal Joey puts Joey the young
opportunist, Vera the sexually assertive older woman and Linda the
idealistic girl, in the original Chicago dive. Joey is the quintessential
toy-boy and wide-boy who thinks with his loins andcalls lust ambition.
But the 'dames' are always in control. Here, the key to the evening is not
the overworked but enduring 'Bewitched, Bothered and Bewildered', but 'Take
Him . . . he's free' sung by the two women in Joey's life as they decide who
will claim ownership. The sexual energies are kept hidden, but emerge in the
intimate ballads, 'What is a Man?' ('is he an ornament, useless by day,
handy by night?') and 'Den of Iniquity', a fouled version of the ideal
love-nest.
The show is sharply and wittily choreographed, with fine dancing throughout,
particularly from Sara Weymouth (Gladys) and the night-club troupe. Jill
Gascoine (Vera) acts the rich vamp superbly; at fiftysomething bored enough
to make revisiting teenage lust a delight, and attractive enough to make it
look possible. Carol Starks' Linda is her innocent counterpart who learns
fast. Cissy Collins' journalist sings 'Zip' with panache: Hart's lyric
brilliantly gathers Dali, Lippmann, Saroyan and Toscanini into one song. And
if Anthony Bowles' musical arrangement sometimes sounds thin, the show is
driven on by Ben Ormerod's substantial lighting changes which keep the
action moving.
Financial difficulties have put The Old Vic under sentence of closure. If it
continues to deliver high quality productions like Pal Joey, it deserves to
remain open.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 13
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-744</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAB3FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Arts: Martini's talent revealed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SUSAN MOORE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Italian Art in the 20th Century at the Royal Academy in 1989 brought to
London four sculptures by Arturo Martini; 'On Classic Ground' at the Tate
last year, a further seven. The Accademia Italiana brings us 49 in an
impressive exhibition, shown previously at the Hotel de Ville, Paris. It is
nothing short of a revelation to non-Italians.
The Italians, too, have been slow in their reappraisal of one of the most
influential and innovative sculptors of the first half of the century: many
of the works here had not been exhibited since the 1920s before the major
retrospective at the Palazzo Reale in Milan in 1985 or the centenary
celebrations at Aosta two years ago. Only in the last decade has the early
20th century Classicism of the renegades of the avant-garde seen serious
critical re-evaluation.
Martini takes his bow here in 1920, the date of his first one-man show -
organised by Carra - and the beginning of his association with the Roman
journal Valori Plastici which championed the return to Classical order. His
interpretation of that order was idiosyncratic and intuitive. He sought a
primitive clarity and purity from his native past, drawing on the forms of
the 14th and 15th century Italian Primitives and the 2nd century Etruscans,
and on the timelessness of peasant life and popular myth. 'The Etruscans
made their statues the way our women make ravioli,' Martini declared. The
same could be said of him.
Massive, simplified forms, even when in low relief, suggest the volume and
rotundity of figures by Giotto and Masaccio. Bronzes have the delicacy and
the sharply outlined features of Quattrocento busts An 'Etruscan' terracotta
chimaera turns to bear its teeth. Simple peasants in archaic dress are
rooted into Mother Earth and gaze towards the heavens, in 'The Stars'. The
compact bulk of 'Fertility' recalls Picasso's nudes of 1906 that similarly
derive their forms from the ancient sculpture of the Iberian peninsula.
Allusion is favoured above narrative, but his sculpture is not without
sentiment. Lovers are melded into single figures, or sit numbed and
separated by untimely death. The Prodigal Son is reconciled with his father
in an overtly Hellenistic bronze of 1926 which Martini considered among his
finest achievements. He has emphasised the tension and the pathos: 'a Greek
could not have done it,' he said.
Eroticism frequently rears not so much its head as its bottom. It is
tempting to relate his predilection for the female posterior to a childhood
memory of watching a prostitute lift up her skirt and squat in a canal: 'A
vision of her large behind exploded in front of me, white, on her two
trunk-like thighs. It was a temple, an ecstasy.'
His terracotta sunbather - which again brings to mind Picasso and his
monumental bathers - is Woman luxuriating in the sun and opening up her body
to embrace it. She is as voluptuous as anything by Maillol. Eroticism is
rampant in 'She-Wolf'. Title and posture allude to the symbol of Rome who
suckled the twins, and to the creature of Sicilian myth of devouring
sensuality. She is also Woman depraved, at once deeply and fatally desirable
and repulsive.
Martini described himself as the greatest seismograph of his age who let
himself be influenced by the natural oscillations of his time. Undoubtedly
he was eclectic in his choice of subject matter, technique and material.
Here he shows himself sensitive to a variety of media, from varnished
plaster to polychrome terracotta and wood, bronze, stone, and marble.
The varnished plaster bas-relief 'The Lovers' makes effective but subtle use
of cast shadow. A silky fluidity of line is found for the 'Dead Lover', and
that sensual, gleaming surface reappears again in the glorious - at times
almost Mannerist - series of small mythological bronzes of the 1930s. But it
is his experimentation and feeling for stone that often produce the most
exciting results.
In 'The Convalescent', the frail figure of the young girl is an essential
part of the massive boulder of grey, pitted Vicenza stone that is her
wheelchair. The porous Finale stone of 'Thirst' is rougher and more
expressive still. Its rough-hewn quality is reminiscent of Michelangelo's
'Slave', but Martini also saw the lava bodies excavated at Pompeii in the
1930s. This sculpture could almost be a wind-eroded outcrop of rock.
Cool marble is used for the chilly 'Narcissus' who peers into the water
beneath the crook of his arm to admire his own reflection. His figure is
streamlined, taut and inviolate. Vicenza stone is selected again for what is
the climax of this exhibition: 'The Dead at Bligny of 1935', which alludes
to the involvement of Italian soldiers at the 1918 battle. The pose of the
soldier is that of the small bronze 'The Hundred Metre Sprinter' made
earlier that year. It has simply been turned upside down to serve a new end.
The exhibition, sponsored by the Commune di Milano, continues at the
Accademia Italiana, 24 Rutland Gate, SW7, until June 23.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 13 Photograph Sunbathing Woman, a 1931 terracotta by Arturo
Martini (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
