<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Technology (Worth Watching): Waste recycling on the boards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DELLA BRADSHAW
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIAN wheat chaff and Georgian cotton stalks could form the basis of a
thriving industry in the Soviet Union to turn waste agricultural matter into
composite boards.
Compak Systems of Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, is to supply five process
plants to the Soviet Union which can produce the panels from fibrous waste
which are produced as a by-product of a variety of crops, including rice,
wheat, oil rape seed or sugar cane. The waste material is chopped and mixed
with a specially formulated resin binder, and the cocktail then formed and
heated.
The boards, which are between 4mm-20mm thick, can be used to replace
particle board or plywood.
Compak Systems: UK, 0482 28650.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 11
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-748</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXABZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Technology (Worth Watching): Box contains a sanguine idea
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DELLA BRADSHAW
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
High-tech weaponry stole the limelight in the recent Gulf war, but a
glorified cardboard box also played its part.
It was used to transport frozen blood for the US Air Force without the need
for mechanical refrigeration or the need for dry ice (which gives off carbon
dioxide as it evaporates).
The re-usable container stored the blood at below -40 deg C for 48 hours -
important because blood has to be thawed according to specific guidelines,
and if allowed to warm to above -40 deg C can easily spoil.
The cardboard box is lined with polyurethane foam and the packs of blood -
chilled to -80 deg C - are wedged between canisters containing a mixture of
frozen ethylene glycol and water.
Developers of the containers, Battelle, of Columbus, Ohio, and Insulated
Shipping Containers, of Phoenix, believe they could be used in future to
transport organs, medicine, or even food.
Battelle: US, 614 424 3889; UK, 071 493 0184.
</TEXT>
