FT  10 MAY 91 / Technology (Worth Watching): Acquiring a new taste in
coatings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DELLA BRADSHAW
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MACHINERY used in the production of food is likely to come under strict
scrutiny in the next few months with government restrictions on the use of
mineral hydrocarbons for direct and indirect inclusion in foodstuffs.
More widely known as white oil and liquid paraffin, these hydrocarbons are
used as a wax covering for cheese rinds and a coating on dried fruits as
wells a lubricant in machines - such as for oiling the chutes down which
food tumbles.
As an alternative Rocol, of Leeds, has developed a range of machinery
lubricants based on the glyceride and ester families. (Esters are organic
compounds produce when acids react with alcohol.) The lubricants will be
available from July.
Rocol: UK, 0532 866511.
