<DOCNO>FT911-754</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXABTFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Technology (Eagle Eye): The lines stay 'open' - How AT&amp;T and
NCR will fuse their products after this week's merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NCR's marketing slogan 'Open, Co-operative Computing' rings with irony as
its executives begin the painful task of combining the proud old company's
operations with those of AT&amp;T.
Since AT&amp;T launched its hostile bid to acquire NCR last December, the
computer company has been anything but co-operative. NCR's support for 'open
systems' proved to be the fatal attraction.
The AT&amp;T takeover 'is a fact of life', Charles Exley, NCR chief executive,
conceded earlier this week. His lack of enthusiasm was hardly surprising
after months of battling AT&amp;T to maintain NCR's independence.
Exley had been masterminding a transformation of NCR. Last year the company
launched a bold move into open systems based upon industry standards
including Unix, the AT&amp;T computer operating system, and Intel's
microprocessors. It was supposed to breathe new life into what many had come
to regard as a tired old-line computer company.
NCR launched high-end personal computers and servers. A notebook computer is
due next month. The company is also developing mainframe-performance
computers in a joint venture with Teradata, a California maker of 'massively
parallel' computers.
The strategy began to pay off. But just as NCR was beginning to capture the
attention of new customers it also caught the eye of AT&amp;T. After years of
failing to fulfil its dream of combining telecommunications and computer
technology to become a dominant player in the market for networked
computers, AT&amp;T was ready to try a new tack.
AT&amp;T's strength is that it owns the world's largest long-distance telephone
network. The company has long believed that its growth lies in exploiting
that network to carry computer data.
'Networked computing is growing more than three times faster than the
computer industry as a whole,' Robert Allen, AT&amp;T chairman, said recently.
'Today the world does 50bn electronic transactions a year. By 1995 that's
expected to quadruple to 200bn. Leadership in telecommunications alone will
no longer be enough.'
Allen's logic is faultless. NCR's product strategy has been widely
applauded. Drawing the two together will, however, be a challenge. The
majority of technology mergers have failed to live up to expectations. The
current struggles of Unisys, formed by the merger of Sperry and Burroughs,
are testimony to the fact that computer industry visionaries frequently have
blind spots.
Combining the product lines of AT&amp;T's computer operations and NCR will be
made simpler by the fact that both were pursuing 'open sys-tems' strategies.
There is plenty of sorting out to be done, however. AT&amp;T, for example,
currently sells personal computers built by Intel and high-end
multiprocessor systems supplied by Pyramid Technology in addition to its own
computers.
Pyramid expects to maintain or even expand its business with AT&amp;T in the
wake of the NCR acquisition. Industry analysts agree that the Pyramid
products will provide the combined companies with a high-performance product
that NCR currently lacks.
Intel is in a more precarious position. Its personal computer sales to AT&amp;T
could be jeopardised by the merger because NCR makes its own PCs. Overall,
however, Intel stands to gain since NCR's entire product line is based upon
Intel microprocessors.
Within the computer industry many question whether AT&amp;T can smoothly execute
the merger with NCR. The months of bitterness surrounding the takeover bid
will not make the process any easier. Although Exley this week claimed to
have a hard time remembering the 'combative stage' of the takeover process,
many of NCR's employees who entered into the spirit of the fight have not
forgotten.
Who you gonna call when your personal computer network goes down? Is it a
hardware or a software problem? Whose software? Whose hardware?
Open systems standards that enable different manufacturers' computer
equipment to work together have many advantages. One drawback is that it has
become more difficult for users to get support services from a group of
vendors who point fingers at each other when something goes wrong.
To address the issue, a group of leading US computer and software companies
have formed a combined technical support alliance (TSA) to co-ordinate
support for multivendor computing environments.
The TSA members include Apple, Borland, Compaq, Hewlett-Packard, IBM, Intel,
Microsoft, NetFRAME, Novell, Oracle, Ungermann-Bass and 3Com. These
companies will co-operate to ensure that their service staffs are trained to
understand other member's products so that they can offer users a
comprehensive solution to problems.
'Our customers want the flexibility to choose products from many different
vendors, along with the assurance that we vendors are co-operating to
support them. Although most of us have been working together already, TSA
formally offers our customers the assurance that we will all co-operate on
support issues,' said Darrell Miller, Novell executive vice president.
In theory it should be easy to send data from one personal computer to
another via a phone line. Theory and practice collide when we 'road
warriors' check into a hotel and try to hook up our laptop or notebook PCs
to the phone.
Recognising this problem, the Association for Computer Training and Support
(Acts), an international mix of corporate computer trainers and computer
managers, has challenged hotels in the US to make their phone systems
'computer friendly' by the end of 1992.
'More than 1.3m laptop computers were purchased in 1990,' said Elliott
Masie, director of Acts. A large percentage of these are used by business
travellers, yet fewer than 40 per cent of hotel rooms in the US are 'modem
ready' says the group. In Europe the percentage is much lower.
Computer Products Plus, of Huntington Beach, California, offers a 'road
warrior's toolkit' - a bag of tricks including crocodile clips, screwdriver,
a magnifying glass and a device designed to circumvent hotel switchboards.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 11 Illustration (Omitted). Illustration (Omitted).
</PAGE>
