<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / BAA seeks review of airport fees to offset revenue losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BAA, the airports operator, is seeking a new five-year pricing formula for
aircraft landing and parking fees. It wants a formula that will enable it to
recoup revenue losses from the abolition of European Community duty-free
sales in 1992 and from additional airport security costs.
The Monopolies and Mergers Commission is conducting its first five-yearly
review since BAA's privatisation of the company's three airports in the
south-east of England
Like other privatised industries regulated by government bodies, BAA is
worried that the recent Ofgas decision to impose a tough five-year pricing
formula on British Gas could set a precedent. Ofgas has limited annual
British Gas price increases to 5 percentage points below the rate of
inflation.
It is expected that the MMC review, which will recommend a new five-year
pricing formula for BAA starting next April, will be completed at the end of
June and the report published in August.
The Civil Aviation Authority, which regulates BAA's airport activities, is
expected to make a final decision on the new pricing formula in October.
Under the current formula, BAA can increase its annual landing and parking
fees by up to 1 percentage point below the rate of inflation. These fees
make up about 40 per cent of the annual income of BAA's three south-east
England airports.
BAA can also recoup 75 per cent of additional security costs incurred
because of government regulations introduced in 1989/90. The company says it
takes two years to recover these additional costs which amount to Pounds 14m
a year. BAA's overall security and safety costs are approaching Pounds 100m
a year.
BAA is particularly worried by the EC's proposal to abolish duty-free sales
in the single European market, which the company believes would result in an
annual revenue loss of Pounds 50m. Duty-free sales have traditionally
cross-subsidised other airport charges.
The company is also concerned by the implications of the EC's plans to
abolish frontier barriers within the community after 1992.
It says this would lead to heavy costs to adapt airport immigration and
customs areas.
BAA argues that any new pricing formula must also take into account the
company's 15-year investment programme to increase and improve airport
capacity in the south-east. The company envisages a Pounds 1bn new terminal
at Heathrow; expanding Stansted's capacity from 8m passengers a year to 15m
and eventually building a second terminal there; and modernising facilities
at Gatwick and Heathrow.
BAA is also funding about 80 per cent of the Pounds 230m express rail link
between London Paddington and Heathrow, which is due to come into service in
1995.
The MMC review of BAA's south-east airport operations will be one of the
first important tasks facing Mr Christopher Chataway, the former
telecommunications minister, who will take over from Sir Christopher
Tugendhat as chairman of the CAA at the end of this month.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9
</PAGE>
