<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Lloyd's controls were inadequate, court told
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN American Name yesterday claimed that the Lloyd's authorities should have
taken action to avert mismanagement at Oakeley Vaughan Underwriting, and
that its regulation of the insurance market had been inadequate.
Mr James Stone, a Name, or member, at Lloyd's since 1978, was presenting
evidence on the eighth day of the case in which 33 Names are claiming that
the failure of the Lloyd's authorities to regulate the market adequately was
responsible for their losses of more than Pounds 5m. He said: 'I thought
that if something was done that was wrong somebody would ring a bell. They
didn't'
Mr Stone was particularly heavily committed to the Oakeley Vaughan agency,
eventually staking more than Pounds 100,000 of the Pounds 450,000 he wrote
at Lloyd's to OV syndicates.
Oakeley Vaughan also managed his investments in other Lloyd's syndicates,
and Mr Stone developed a close friendship with Mr Charles St George, the
chairman of Oakeley Vaughan.
Under cross-examination by Mr David Johnson QC, representing Lloyd's, Mr
Stone accepted that he had been naive in the way he had organised his
affairs at Lloyd's. 'When I joined I didn't go into it in the detail with
which I should have. I guess I was unknowledgeable about what I was doing.'
Mr Stone was 'under the influence of Mr St George', Mr Johnson said. 'The
fact is that you had no knowledge of what powers Lloyd's have over
underwriting agents.'
Mr Stone had repeatedly ignored warnings from Mr John Hayter, the agent who
initially managed his affairs at Lloyd's, about the wisdom of committing
money to the Oakeley Vaughan agencies, Mr Johnson said.
Mr Stone accepted that when he joined Lloyd's he was putting his affairs in
the hands of an underwriting agent, but said he thought 'if there had been
something wrong I would have expected to have been told about it. In our
country we rely on the integrity of the system, not the broker calling in
the stock. I've said this so many times it sounds like a broken record.'
</TEXT>
