<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / World Trade News: Albania starts to lift barriers in
investment drive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY, East European Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALBANIA will introduce foreign investment and joint-venture legislation, as
well as measures to privatise sectors of the economy, as part of the
government's plan to boost foreign trade and modernise the economy, Mr Ligor
Dhamo, president of the Albanian Chamber of Commerce, said yesterday in
London.
Mr Dhamo, who with Mr Spartak Mersini, a senior official at the Albanian
ministry of foreign trade, was on a three-day visit to the UK, said Albania
was in desperate need of foreign investment to revamp food processing, light
industry and other sectors of the economy.
Last year, Albania had a trade deficit of Dollars 200m (Pounds 118m), a per
capita annual income of Dollars 850, and over-employment of 30 per cent in
the industrial sector, or about 93,000 people.
Mr Dhamo said the prospect for a resumption of full diplomatic relations
between Tirana and London 'in the near future', and Albania's determination
to modernise its economy, would increase trade between both countries. Total
trade turnover last year was less than Dollars 3m.
Diplomatic relations were severed in 1939. Attempts to restore them failed
in 1946 after the Corfu Channel incident in which two British destroyers
were mined off the coast of Albania.
Western investors had few incentives to trade with Albania because policies
undertaken by Mr Enver Hoxha, the former communist president who died in
1985, banned foreign credits as part of his ideological policy of
self-reliance and independ ence.
But yesterday, Mr Dhamo said policies now pursued by the recently-elected
parliament, which is dominated by the Albanian (communist) Party of Labour,
would open up the country to foreign investment.
In particular, he said new draft laws would:
allow foreign enterprises, banks and foreign nationals to set up companies
in Albania;
safeguard those investments against expropriation or nationalisation;
guarantee the right for full repatriation of profits - in hard currency.
In a speech to British companies, however, Mr Dhamo said the authorities
would establish a 'system of custom duties of a protectionist character for
significant final products and sectors of the economy.
'Gradually, this system will be adjusted to the structures and levels of the
tariff of international trade organisations of Gatt, the European Community,
which we want to join.'
The parliament were drafting a tax system which envisaged tax holidays of up
to three years for foreign investors, and thereafter, rates of taxes of
between 15 and 40 per cent. 'But I think the average tax will be around 20
per cent,' he said.
Foreign companies, however, would not be allowed to own or buy property in
Albania. 'They will be allowed to rent property,' he explained.
A draft law on privatisation, expected to be unveiled later this year, will
seek to clarify ownership and property rights.
The British Foreign and Commonwealth Office yesterday extended the Know-How
Fund to Romania in recognition of the country's committment to reform.
The amount of financial assistance was not specified, however. The fund
provides banking, accountancy and finance advice and expertise to help the
countries of eastern Europe in their moves towards democracy and a free
market.
</TEXT>
