<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / South Koreans turn their backs on ageing party politicians:
Street protests and the fall in government popularity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTH KOREA'S ruling Democratic Liberal Party yesterday marked the first
anniversary of its official formation. But there was a distinct lack of
celebration in the corridors of power, still less on the streets of Seoul.
Instead, 250,000 demonstrators - mostly students and workers - spilled into
the streets, demanding that the government resign, and clashing with riot
police in downtown Seoul and several other South Korean cities. The
protests, some of the worst in recent years, have been fuelled by the death
of a university student last month at the hands of riot police.
While dramatic, this spring's demonstrations are unlikely to pose a threat
to the government. But they will further add to the problems of President
Roh Tae Woo's administration which has seen its popularity fall steadily as
a result of a string of scandals, intra-factional fighting and economic
concerns.
In the latest poll conducted by Korea Gallup, the DLP received only 18 per
cent support. This is lower than that enjoyed by the Democratic Justice
Party, the former ruling party, just before it joined together with two
opposition groups to form the DLP early last year: the new party has proven
to be less than the sum of even one of its parts.
Demonstrations by students, traditionally regarded as the conscience of the
nation, should never be taken lightly by Korean governments. But dramatic as
it seems, the current round of unrest lacks the broader social support
needed to achieve the students' demands.
There is also much ritual about the protests. It would be a strange spring
in Seoul if tear gas did not fill the air and if riot police buses were not
lined up in front of the city hall awaiting the inevitable demonstrations.
'May is always the cruellest month,' notes Mr Nam Jae Hee, one of the DLP's
most influential national assembly members.
This year's protests should also be put in perspective. They have generally
been less violent than those of last year, when radical students gained
control of parts of the downtown area, setting fire to the US cultural
centre. Moreover, the spate of self immolations by students which have so
far brought three deaths reflect an extremism borne of falling support among
the population as a whole.
The demonstrations can be expected to continue at least until May 18, the
eleventh anniversary of the Kwangju massacre in which more than 200
protesters were killed by troops in the south-western city. 'But we expect
them to die down quite quickly after that' said one western diplomat.
Of greater concern, perhaps, are the problems which will remain once the
wave of protests passes. The unpopularity of the government, which has
resulted from a series of scandals, intra-party factional feuding, inflation
and rising housing costs, has caused a disillusionment with politics and
politicians in Korea's four year democracy.
The response from the government has often served to exacerbate the problem.
Since the end of last month, two cabinet ministers have been dismissed - one
to take responsibility for a pollution scandal in the south-eastern city of
Taegu, and one to take responsibility for the death of the student. But the
rapid turnover of ministers only adds to the sense of instability and the
feeling that the government lacks direction in its policies.
'There is a crisis of confidence' says Professor Han Seung Joo of Korea
University. 'But it is not the same as the crisis in 1986 and 1987 in the
sense that it doesn't really translate into opposition to the system
itself.'
The reason, argues Dr Kim Hak Joon, chief assistant to the president for
policy research, is the creation of a solid middle-class. 'They may
complain, but they are strongly committed to the system and law and order.'
'Our political parties are strongly related to the past,' argues Dr Kim.
'That is why political parties and leaders have disappointed the masses and
that is why nowadays there is much talk about the need for generational
change.'
Professor Han agrees. 'The only change is that the two Kims have got older'
he says, referring to Mr Kim Young Sam, the number two in the ruling party
and Mr Kim Dae Jung, leader of the largest opposition party and the other
Kim's perennial rival.
The opposition has failed to capitalise on the government's weakness and Mr
Kim Dae Jung has been unable to extend his support beyond inhabitants of and
migrants from the south-western province of Cholla. A poll last month by one
of Korea's leading daily newspapers found that a full 60 per cent of those
asked did not support any party.
So for South Koreans, who turned out in their millions to force the
introduction of democracy in 1987, there is disillusion. 'In the medium and
long term this means an increasing alienation of people from politics' says
Professor Han. 'This is perhaps the most serious problem.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
