<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Quebec separatist passions cooling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HOPES are growing in Canada that Quebec can settle its differences with the
rest of the country without breaking away.
None of the emotive issues which led to the collapse of the Meech Lake
accord, which would have enshrined in the constitution Quebec's claim to be
'a distinct society', has yet been resolved. But recent events point towards
a greater willingness to compromise - in both French- and English-speaking
Canada - than has been evident for the past year.
The improved climate was reflected this week in conciliatory remarks by
Quebec's premier, Mr Robert Bourassa, who said he might delay a referendum
on sovereignty, scheduled to take place by October 1992, if the rest of the
country appeared close to making a binding offer on restructuring the
present federal system.
His remarks come amid evidence that the drive for a sovereign Quebec is
losing some of its steam. One recent poll showed that 48 per cent of Quebec
voters support sovereignty, down from 64 per cent last November.
Organisers of next month's St-Jean-Baptiste Day parade, marking Quebec's
national holiday, have complained that they have raised only CDollars 2,010
(Pounds 1,015) in donations this year, against a target of CDollars 500,000.
The dampened enthusiasm for independence appears to result partly from the
recession and warnings from business leaders about the economic cost of a
fragmented country.
The federal government will outline further details of its strategy for the
forthcoming constitutional negotiations at the opening of a new session of
parliament next Monday.
Meanwhile, the 'national unity' initiatives launched by Ottawa since last
autumn appear to be bearing some fruit.
English-speaking Canadians, especially in the west, still oppose a special
deal for Quebec along the lines of the defunct Meech Lake accord. But they
are being reassured that the next round of negotiations will also deal with
at least some of their concerns, including the composition of the
non-elected Senate, the much-maligned policy of official bilingualism, and
aboriginal Canadians' political and economic demands.
And despite his party's dismal showing in public opinion polls, Prime
Minister Brian Mulroney is being widely applauded for his choice of former
external affairs minister Joe Clark to take charge of the constitutional
affairs portfolio.
Mr Clark, who has the advantage of being a bilingual Albertan untarred by
the Meech Lake episode, has said bluntly that it will be impossible to meet
Quebec's October 1992 deadline. Ultimately, though, he may be unable to
satisfy everyone. Despite the government's determination to avoid a national
referendum on the issue, that may be the only way forward.
</TEXT>
