<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Gun lobby suffers rare defeat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER RIDDELL, US Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SUPPORTERS of tighter gun control in the US have won a rare victory over the
well-financed gun lobby, with the approval by the House of Representatives
of legislation imposing a seven-day waiting period for purchases of handguns
to allow time for background checks.
The margin, 239 votes to 186, was larger than expected after intense
lobbying and advertising. But a much closer vote is expected in the Senate,
where rural states in which the pro-gun National Rifle Association (NRA) is
influential have an equal say with more highly populated, and crime-ridden,
urban states.
Moreover, President George Bush, a longstanding opponent of gun control and
an NRA member, has threatened to veto the measure unless it forms part of a
much broader anti-crime package that includes an expanded federal death
penalty.
The debate over the measure has touched deep-seated American traditions.
Even if it is enacted, no one expects the bill to make much practical
difference in a country where there may be 100m guns in circulation.
</TEXT>
