<DATELINE>
   BUENOS AIRES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Raul Granillo Ocampo, former Argentine cabinet secretary, has rejected as
irrelevant a government investigation into a case of alleged corruption
involving Swift-Armour SA, an American-owned meatpacking company.
In January, the case made corruption a political issue after a newspaper
published a confidential letter from the American embassy complaining that
an official had demanded bribes from Swift-Armour. The scandal touched off a
cabinet crisis in which four ministers were dismissed.
A federal judge investigated the case but last week shelved it for lack of
evidence.
Mr Ocampo, who resigned after being accused of leaking the letter, said on
Wednesday that the investigations 'were nothing more than an official
formality to confirm a conclusion written and determined before its
initiation.'
He said his enemies used the investigation to further their own political
agenda, rather than investigating the claim.
