<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / From conflict to consensus: The differing styles of Brazil's
old and new economy ministers, Zelia Cardoso and Marcilio Marques Moreira
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CREDIBILITY was the word on many lips throughout Brazil yesterday on hearing
that Mr Marcilio Marques Moreira, the Brazilian ambassador in Washington, is
to replace Ms Zelia Cardoso de Mello as economy minister.
A career diplomat and former banker, Mr Moreira, 59, commands respect
internationally and from Brazil's private sector. His first task will be to
escape from the current price freeze without an explosion of inflation.
Inflation last month was 7 per cent but most industries claim their prices
are now 40 per cent behind what they should be.
'He's a first world citizen with all the tools to build a good team and make
a revolution in this country,' said Mr Igor Cornelson, Director of Chartered
West LB in Brazil.
Mr Moreira's appointment signifies a shift in style of government to a more
consensual approach. Until now the government of President Fernando Collor
has failed dismally in attempts to secure an essential social pact to
support its radical anti-inflationary policies, mainly because of the
aggressive style of Ms Cardoso.
Ms Cardoso, 37, was one of the main architects of the Collor Plan, the
package of radical stabilisation measures announced 14 months ago. The tight
monetary policy, which included the freezing of 80 per cent of national
assets and savings, was initially successful in bringing inflation down from
80 per cent a month to single figures. But by the start of this year it was
back over 20 per cent a month.
The announcement at the end of January of Collor Plan 2, which included a
wage and price freeze, was widely seen as recognition that Latin America's
most radical economic experiment had failed, and credibility dropped to rock
bottom.
Many in Brazil agreed with the direction of economic policy towards
deregulation and liberalisation. The problem was always with management. Ms
Cardoso and her team (known as the Campinas boys for their university
backgrounds and youth) were academics without political or administrative
experience. They tended to lecture people on economic theory rather than
attempt to negotiate.
Asked about the government's bitter rift with the powerful Sao Paulo
business community in an interview with the FT last year, Ms Cardoso simply
said: 'We're right. They're wrong. You'll see.'
This attitude won her enemies at home and abroad. However no-one faced with
the Herculean task of stabilising Brazil's inflation-ridden economy and
ending years of protectionism was likely to win friends. One diplomat said:
'Zelia has been under tremendous attack precisely because she's been trying
to do some of the things that needed to be done and that meant sacrifices
all round.'
But Ms Cardoso was unable to convince the population of the need for
sacrifice, and her polices have produced poor results. Last year the economy
contracted 4.6 per cent, industrial production fell 12 per cent and
unemployment in Sao Paulo rose to more than 1m.
President Collor was reluctant to lose his most loyal cabinet colleague. Ms
Cardoso survived a scandal last September in which an indiscreet bolero,
danced with the then justice minister at her birthday party, led to the
revelation that the two were having an affair.
She survived and even had her powers enhanced. In recent months she secured
jobs for friends such as the infrastructure minister, which led people to
dub her Brazil's prime minister.
Her increased influence seemed to go to her head and conflicts with other
government members became increasingly open in recent weeks. Mr Collor's
brother, among others, began pressing him to dismiss her. A poll last week
showing that a clear majority of the population was against the Collor
government seems to have been the catalyst for her removal.
Mr Moreira's appointment and his own reputation gives the government a new
lease of life in terms of credibility, though this could be quickly lost if
inflation is not soon brought under control. Mr Moreira is expected to
accelerate the liberalisation process to force down prices, maintain tight
monetary control to prevent consumption and devalue the cruzeiro to increase
the competitiveness of Brazilian goods abroad.
Mr Carlos Langoni, an economist and former head of the Central Bank, said:
'Externally he will speed up debt negotiations and is very aware of the need
for Brazil to become competitive again but his great contribution
domestically will be to come back to fundamentals.
'There will be no short cuts such as freezes or radical ideas. He is a
negotiator.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
