<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / EC takes a considered view of pig manure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Commission has been unfairly criticised for being naively
visionary and interferingly nit-picking at the same time.
On the one hand, the Berlaymont bureaucrats are trying to subsume our
nations into a 'federastical' super-state, while pretending that the
Community can swan around and resolve crises like the Middle East where real
superpowers have failed.
On the other, they carry out dastardly ambushes on icons of our cultures,
such as the smoky bacon crisp and the defenceless tilde, the 'N' with a
diacritical mark - thus n - which they want taken off Spanish keyboards.
Happily, it can be revealed that such allegations are unfounded and that
senior officials engage daily with the most intractable of our secular
problems.
Manure dominated no fewer than three lunch tables patronised by the most
senior of officials in a Berlaymont watering-hole this week. Exquisite
asparagus and mouth-watering monk-fish could not deflect them from their
grapple with pig-droppings (state aids for the processing of).
Here in a poop-scoop was the classic dilemma of the Great Market which the
EC is building: how to reconcile fair competition with the environmental
imperative of keeping the citizenry dropping-free.
It is the Dutch who have brought this burning issue to a head. The
Netherlands is a small country with a lot of people and even more pigs.
The problem is that reprocessing manure is not a going business without
state subsidies which are illegal and competition-distorting under EC laws
framed for people rather than pigs.
Dung recyclers are honoured citizens in the Netherlands. Brussels officials
were left in no doubt of this on a recent visit to a reprocessing plant,
dominated by a picture of Queen Juliana raising a toast with a glass of
water by-produced from pig manure.
Any lingering scepticism has now been dispelled by a no-nonsense letter to
the Commission, re the absolute necessity of state aid for manure
reprocessing, from Mr Ruud Lubbers, the Dutch prime minister himself.
While the controversy rages, it may be just as well that that Mr Lubbers is
tipped as a possible replacement for head of the Commission after its
currently presiding visionary, Mr Jacques Delors. Mr Delors is an urban
Frenchman, with a rather romantic view of the countryside (he is said to
have a cousin with just six cows). Mr Lubbers, it is patently obvious, is
very sound, and prepared to get to grips with real grass-roots stuff.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2 Photograph The culprits (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-777</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAA6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
