<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Privatisation pioneers find it tough at the bottom: Local
experience cries out for co-ordinated reform throughout the Soviet Union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN Sub-Lieutenant Vladislav Gerasimov left the navy and returned to his
native Leningrad, he decided he had nothing to lose by trying his hand at
business.
One year on, aged 29, he is the proud proprietor of one of the first shops
'privatised' as part of Leningrad city council's market reforms.
Mr Dmitri Vasiliev, in charge of Leningrad's city council privatisation
programme, says he aims to sell 80 per cent of the city's 4,000 shops, as
well as most of its restaurants and housing.
He has sold 40 shops so far but he cannot say how long the whole process
will take as this depends on what he calls the 'political situation'. One
problem is that he still faces resistance from Communist-controlled
districts and the state organisations which run most of the retail network.
But the pioneering initiative of radical city councils and of entrepreneurs
such as Mr Gerasimov also reveals the limitations of economic reform in
isolation. Their experience cries out for a co-ordinated reform programme at
all levels of government and the economy.
After giving up attempts to repair the ailing socialist system, the Soviet
leadership has come round to the view that privatisation and other
capitalist evils are essential to economic recovery.
Although the union government has not yet begun privatisatsia of factories
on any significant scale, republican and local authorities have made a start
in taking small businesses and agricultural land out of state hands.
The government's latest anti-crisis programme seeks to privatise two-thirds
of small business by the end of 1992. One of the programme's contradictions
however is that it sets no precise targets for its proclaimed goal of
breaking up monopolies and privatising state industry.
Mr Valentin Pavlov, the Soviet prime minister, said in an interview this
week that one of his government's most important tasks was to de-monopolise
and privatise industry. He said the government was drawing up detailed plans
to achieve this together with the privatisation of the wholesale trade
network.
If this is so, then the government will be helping those at the grassroots
level who have taken the initiative on this difficult route.
For the time being, what Leningrad's Mr Vasiliev is doing falls short of
privatisation in the traditional sense - in so far as the businesses are
long-leased, rather than sold outright.
He says that the main reason for this is because the council is afraid of
being short-changed by selling in a market where prices are still
artificially low in the absence of market mechanisms.
Politically, he adds, there is a danger of a backlash if he goes too far too
fast. This is why for instance the council reserves the right to require
that new owners continue to sell basic commodities they sold under state
ownership.
'If a bread shop starts selling jeans (and stops selling bread), this could
be the end for us,' says Mr Vasiliev, referring to the already fragile
supplies of basic commodities. 'But nothing stops a shop from expanding its
selection.'
However, Mr Vasiliev, whose great-grandmother owned a chain of hairdressers
before the Bolsheviks abolished private property, has no time for socialist
ideals of worker-management.
Although employees are given a first option on leasing businesses, he says
'they make bad managers'.
From the outside, Mr Gerasimov's shop, in an industrial suburb with an
impersonal sign saying 'Haberdashery', looks like any other grubby state
institution in the Soviet Union. Inside however, it sells a far wider range
of goods than you would expect in a haberdashery shop, including items such
as wall-paper and swim-suits. Mr Gerasimov claims turnover has quadrupled
since he took over in March.
For Mr Gerasimov, minimum requirements for what he should sell and not
having outright ownership are the least of his worries. He paid Rbs15,000
for the shop's contents, and signed a 15-year lease giving him first option
for outright purchase. The lease has been set at Rbs30,000 a year. He was
chosen to take over the shop after a laborious selection process by the city
council. This has since been replaced by an auction system.
Nor does this Communist party member have any problems with his staff. He
told the three women who worked in the shop that they were welcome to stay
on, providing they shed the bad habits of state employees: 'I told them they
were not allowed to shout at the customers any more.' He also doubled their
pay.
His main headache is more fundamental - finding goods to sell in a shortage
economy where supplies are largely controlled by the state.
He says some enterprises want to do business with him but are already
committed to selling their output to the state through the system of state
orders. Others will only dispose of their surplus production in return for
other goods or in hard currency.
'We spend a lot of time looking for goods to sell because even though there
are private shops, there are no private factories,' he said.
'All the letters we write have to start with the words 'I ask you', but I am
fed up with asking.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
