<DOCNO>FT911-778</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAA5FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Estonia moves cautiously through collectivist web
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ENRIQUE TESSIERI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TALLINN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR RIHO OLBERG, a 40-year-old Estonian farmer, has never known what it feels
like to own the land he farms. Although he lives on the property his great
grandfather bought from the German Baron Arthur Konstantin Sternberg in
1897, his only proof of ownership is a deed to roughly 44 hectares dating
from the days of the Russian empire.
Mr Olberg hopes to be one of the first Estonians to benefit from
privatisation. He knows it will be an uphill struggle. 'People are afraid to
show too much enthusiasm over private property because they fear a backlash
 -that their land will be once again confiscated, collectivised and they
will end up in Siberia,' he said.
Estonia, one of the three Baltic republics set on independence, is striving
to free itself from the bonds of a centrally-planned economy.
Privatisation is widely seen as the only path by which the Soviet Union can
launch itself into a market economy. For republics such as Estonia, it is
also a barometer of the pace of economic reform for foreign investors.
Estonia launched its first modest step towards privatisation last year,
permitting the sale of state-owned service, trade and catering companies
worth up to Rbs500,000 (Pounds 164,000). The results have been modest: a
beauty parlour, barber and a florist shop were auctioned in March in the
western coastal town of Haapsalu.
The republic is planning to take another step soon by selling 17 large
enterprises. It intends to put up for sale a 10 per cent stake of all medium
and large companies under the control of the Estonian state: these would
include seven companies during the first half of this year and a further 10
later this year.
However, Mr Ardo Kamratov, head of the Estonian department of state
property, believes there are pitfalls. For example, companies' shares are to
be offered first to their workers, then to local inhabitants and only then
to outsiders, including foreigners.
The seven large companies up for total privatisation include Baltika and two
other textile companies, Talleks, which builds excavators, and TLN
Taksopark, Tallinn's taxi company.
In early April, Estonia passed legislation which attempted to set the
framework for returning land confiscated after 1940 to its rightful owners.
Those who are eligible and want to reclaim land owned up to June 1940, when
Estonia was illegally annexed by Moscow, must apply to the Estonian
authorities before next January.
As a measure against speculation, land will only be returned to those who
will make it produce, according to Mr Pajo. If the owners cannot work the
land, they will be compensated, possibly with Estonian bonds or cash.
Difficult questions such as assessing the price of land and determining
compensation have not yet been addressed. And there are fears that Estonia
cannot guarantee private property will never again be confiscated.
Mr Maido Pajo, the Estonian deputy minister of agriculture, admitted that
the privatisation process in the countryside had been hindered by the
collective and state farms, which are important social units providing
education, housing and an economic livelihood for their workers.
Fifty years ago, when 60 per cent of Estonians lived in the countryside
(only 30 per cent do so today), there were about 140,000 farms of 25-50
hectares, with a few of 1,000 hectares. Today's collective and state farms
are between 3,000 and 15,000 hectares and are home to anywhere from 200 to
1,000 people.
Most of the rural land in Estonia is controlled by collective and state
farms. As a first step towards privatisation, some of these farms have
already been made into co-operatives.
Mr Olberg has been chastised by many of his fellow farmers for believing too
passionately in private property. But he has not lost his sense of humour.
'I have been normal all my life,' he says. 'The truth is that most of the
people who live around these parts have been abnormal because they don't
believe that a human can own land.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-779</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAA4FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Brandt presses Europe to set up intervention force
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A EUROPEAN intervention force should be established to help secure peace in
areas threatened by civil war such as Yugoslavia, or to tackle ecological
disasters like the recent Italian oil spillage, according to Mr Willy
Brandt, the former West German chancellor.
In an interview before visiting New York today to spell out proposals to
reform the United Nations and improve its world development role, Mr Brandt
strongly favoured greater security co-operation among European countries as
part of moves towards European political union.
He also favoured extending the European Community eastwards, saying it was
in Germany's own interest to support the eventual adhesion of Poland,
Czechoslovakia and Hungary to ward off the risks of disruptive migration
towards the west.
Mr Brandt noted that the German-Polish co-operation treaty being signed next
month commits Bonn to backing Polish membership of the EC. It was vital to
give these countries the prospect of joining, even if full membership were
10 years away, he said.
Underlining a turnaround in the thinking of the opposition Social Democratic
Party, of which Mr Brandt is still honorary chairman, he said he was in
favour of military intervention in another country's affairs in cases of
gross abuses of human rights.
On the question of allowing the German army to operate outside Nato, Mr
Brandt said he supported changing the constitution to allow the Bundeswehr
to be used outside Nato in all military operations which have UN backing.
But he left open whether the SPD party congress next month would back a
limit on Bundeswehr deployment simply to UN peace-keeping.
Mr Brandt said he was against asking for a permanent seat for Germany on the
Security Council. Any attempt by Germany to promote the idea - first floated
by the Soviet Union last year - would create so much controversy that it
could easily block reforms aimed at making the UN more effective, he said.
Rather, France and Britain, the two European permanent members of the
council, should be encouraged to use their voices to represent European
Community opinion. This could be a prelude to giving the EC formal
representation on the council.
Mr Brandt returned to the headlines for his concern about world development
with the Brandt Commission report carried out at the end of the 1970s.
Looking back, he denied feeling depressed about events during the last
decade. But he conceded that, largely as a result of a lack of new lending,
international resources were now flowing from the developing to the
developed world, rather than the other way around. 'Not everything has
become worse. But everything is much more complicated.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-780</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAA3FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Havel plea for west to be generous: Former Communist states
need help to return to European fold, says president
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CZECHOSLOVAKIA'S president, Mr Vaclav Havel, yesterday called on richer
countries for 'generous help' to enable the former Communist states of
eastern Europe to rejoin the path of western 'civilisation, culture and
values'.
Speaking in Aachen, where he received the city's annual Charlemagne prize
for international relations, he said Europe was nearer than ever to
realising 'the age-old hope of becoming an area of friendship and
co-operation for all its inhabitants.'
Now, despite the tearing down of the Iron Curtain, Europe needed to find
'the courage for speedy, unconventional and sometimes risky steps' to
overcome remaining divisions.
Backing the idea of a European Confederation first suggested by President
Francois Mitterrand, Mr Havel said European integration had to take place
through an overlapping network of institutional links across the continent.
He said western aid for the post-Communist countries, comparable with that
provided for western Europe under the post-war Marshall Plan, was necessary,
and was also in the 'existential interest' of the west itself.
The one-time dissident playwright reminded his audience in the historic
coronation chamber of the Aachen city hall of the basic reasons why the
former Communist states were seeking rapprochement with the west. 'This is
not because, as countries which today stand poor and destroyed, they believe
that their rich and prospering western friends can solve all their problems
for them.'
Rather, he said, countries such as Czechoslovakia identified with and were
seeking a return to 'a certain civilisation, a certain political culture'
which they themselves in previous centuries had helped to form.
'This is not a question of (eastern Europe) being fascinated by another
world. It is just the opposite. After decades of unnaturally following the
wrong track, we are yearning to rejoin the road which was once ours too.'
Mr Havel said that the goal of European integration could not be fulfilled
without maintaining the 'Atlantic dimension' of association with the US and
Canada. Additionally, 'no future European order is conceivable without the
European peoples of the Soviet Union, who are an indivisible component of
Europe, and without the great community of peoples, into which the
present-day Soviet Union is being transformed.'
</TEXT>
