<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Private radio and TV to return in Malta
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GODFREY GRIMA
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VALLETTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MALTA is to have private radio and television broadcasting after a gap of 16
years under legislation approved by parliament this week.
The legislation sanctions the creation of 10 radio stations, a television
cable operation and several non-profit-making community radios.
Radio and television stations were nationalised by the former socialist
premier, Mr Dom Mintoff, in 1975.
Radio and tv broadcasting has become increasingly politicised, with
ministers using flimsy excuses to appear nightly on television news
bulletins.
The spawning of privately owned radio stations may, however, do little to
defuse the Maltese passion for politics. Barely had the broadcasting act
made its way through parliament and Mr Eddie Fenech Adami, the prime
minister, had licensed his own ruling Nationalist party, the opposition
Labour party and the island's conservative Roman Catholic church to set up
their own radio stations.
There are suspicions that the liberalisation of broadcasting is in fact
designed to give political parties new weapons with which to wage battle as
the 1993 general election approaches.
These suspicions are fuelled by the government's decision to grant the
church a radio licence. The church in Malta is largely viewed as a
traditional foe of the Labour party whose influence, now on the rise again,
may have a telling effect on the forthcoming general election result.
</TEXT>
