<DOCNO>FT911-789</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAAUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Survey of Hong Kong (14): Big shift in population planned -
More skyscrapers to be built in the New Territories
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LAST YEAR it was fishponds, gently worked by rural families still farming
this area of Hong Kong's New Territories. Today, the calm has been shattered
by convoys of trucks bringing yellow rock, freshly hewn from nearby hills
for foundations for skyscrapers.
Soon the first few families will move in and, by 1997, this will be home for
150,000 Hong Kong people.
The dramatic transformation of Tin Shui Wai in the New Territories' far
north-west into Hong Kong's latest new town, complete with shopping arcades,
bowling alleys and Japanese restaurants, marks the latest step in a
remarkable population shift.
Faced with a population explosion from immigration and a baby boom in the
1960s, government planners earmarked the New Territories as the only place
left to house the overflow from the cramped areas of Hong Kong Island and
Kowloon.
Eight new towns have been built so far. The sleepy Cantonese clan villages
of the 1960s have been overrun by 30-storey apartment blocks, ring roads and
industrial estates. The population has quadrupled since 1961.
By 1997 it will have almost doubled again to 3.27m, more than half Hong
Kong's total.
In the villages around the new town of Yuen Long the effects of such rapid
urbanisation are still being felt.
Mr Tso, now in his 70s, fled here from China with his wife and cousins.
Their tiny cottage, with one living room and sleeping area above, stands
opposite the village temple.
Until last year it was inaccessible to cars. Now a major road is being built
through the village, flattening the Tsos' cottage and forcing them out into
a modern government housing estate.
Mr Tso does not want to leave and enter the 'modern' world. For a start, he
has never been in a lift.
The New Territories have rarely captured the imagination of the expatriates
and businessmen who pass through Hong Kong. It cannot offer the icons of the
future, the skyscrapers and neon on Hong Kong's harbour, nor the icons of
the past available just a few miles north in China.
But in places the tangled hills, turned an even deeper shade of green by
passing clouds, the long hiking trails popular with Hong Kong Chinese
enjoying the clean, or cleanish, air and the lolling atmosphere of life all
combine to laugh in the face of the madness that is the better-known Hong
Kong.
The area is roughly 15 miles deep by 25 wide. It was leased by Britain in
1898 when the European powers scrambled for concessions in China.
Britain wanted the land as a buffer zone to protect Hong Kong and its
valuable harbour, acquired 57 years earlier. It is the lease on the New
Territories, expiring in 1997, which forced Britain to agree to return Hong
Kong to China.
Colonial administrators largely ignored the farmers, pearl fishermen and
local traders of the New Territories, prefering to maintain order through
alliance with the Heung Yee Kuk, a powerful group of land owners.
Even in the 1960s, when the Kuk were armed against communist uprisings,
Britain assessed the political climate in the New Territories
unscientifically, by counting Chinese and Taiwanese flags flying in the
villages.
As the area has become an overflow for Hong Kong people, so valleys and farm
land have become dumping grounds for the less edifying aspects of Hong Kong
life. Remote areas like High Island in Sai Kung are home to Vietnamese Boat
People, tucked out of sight of Hong Kong taxpayers, who pay for the
accommodation, as well as hiking tourists.
In return for its support, the Heung Yee Kuk was absolved from colonial
interference. Rules governing land use were never introduced. In the 1980s
local farmers found it hard to compete against cheap vegetable imports from
China.
So instead of farming, they have hired out their land as storage areas for
shipping containers, construction materials and scrap heaps. The farmers now
watch television or gamble all day on the stock market with their profits.
Beside the tiny roads around Lau Fau Shan, once reknowned for its natural
beauty, fields full of rusting containers piled six or seven high provide a
powerful but unpleasant reminder of Hong Kong's trading status.
The government, claiming to be sensitive to environmental lobbying, has
clamped down on this new kind of absentee landlordism. Even though the
measures are half hearted, they have provoked the wrath of the Kuk, which
believes it has been betrayed.
Mr Lau Wong-fat, chairman, says his members are being deprived of their
right to use their land as they wish. The Kuk's custom of only recognising
male succession is also under attack because Hong Kong is introducing a Bill
of Rights which guarantees equality before the law. Mr Lau says these rights
and customs were guaranteed in the 1898 Peking Convention and in more recent
treaties like the Basic Law, Hong Kong's mini constitution after 1997.
He says the traditionally pro-British Kuk, a force for stability in the New
Territories, will become more confrontational is its grievances are not
addressed.
Near the small town of Kam Tin, two walled villages owned by the Tang clan
still draw tourists and curious locals. The present clan matriachs, quick to
spot an earner, greet visitors with a demand for money - 'one photo, two
dollar - one photo, two dollar]'
It would be no surprise if their traditional silk gowns are donned only for
the photo call or, perhaps, are designed to conceal portable phones.
Away from the ever widening main roads there are still reminders of the
past. Near the Chinese border in the east, around Ta Kwu Ling, farming
hamlets are linked by thin concrete paths which wind through patchwork
fields of vegetables and rice paddy.
One field is lined with pot plants, soon to be packed off south to the
boardrooms of Hong Kong's businessmen. Clumps of bamboo offer shade for the
village's dogs. The same bamboo will one day support Hong Kong's
construction workers atop the colony's building sites.
On one recent Sunday afternoon, the only sounds come from an old Hakka woman
carting firewood back home and families watching the horse racing at Sha Tin
on television. Occasionally there is the clatter of a game of mahjong, a
Cantonese favourite which combines the opportunity to make lots of noise
with, hopefully, lots of money.
Near Fanling, another new town in the north east, the bus passes army camps
which act as home to the Gurkhas, defenders of Hong Kong until 1997. China's
People's Liberation Army came to visit recently and assess their future
barracks. They returned to China amazed at the number of tennis courts.
On the other side of the town is Wo Hop Shek cemetery, Hong Kong's largest,
which snakes away into the hills. Each year families return to share some
food and clean the graves of their ancestors. But as more and more Hong Kong
people head overseas for a foreign passport, ancestors are being neglected.
The tombs lie silent, cluttered with the debris of past seasons. As the
light quickly fades, photographs of the deceased on the headstones gaze
northwards across the hills towards China, awaiting the return of their
former masters.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI Photograph Apartment blocks are transforming the New
Territories where the population could reach 3.2 m by 1997, more than half
of Hong Kong's total (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-790</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAATFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Survey of Hong Kong (12): Confidence has been enhanced -
Investment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HONG KONG may have little control over its political destiny. But the job of
making itself attractive to the international financial community has become
even more important of late. Although the colony can rightfully claim to be
East Asia's leading financial centre south of Japan, the uncertainties of
1997 and growing competition from other centres like Singapore have forced
it to redouble its efforts.
Much of the work has centred on the stock exchange whose flaws were exposed
by the 1987 market crash and the ensuing bribery scandals. The creation of a
new Securities and Futures Commission has paved the way to a new regulatory
structure for the investment industry. The exchange itself has been
strengthened by a number of measures including a more independent-minded
council to run it.
The main steps have been to make the securities markets more transparent and
less prone to abuse. There are new disclosure rules, and the procedures for
listing companies - which was where most of the abuse occurred - have been
cleaned up.
More reforms will come later this year to bring the exchange in line with
major exchanges elsewhere. A new law against insider trading (though not
criminalising it) will come into force. Changes are also being planned to
permit listed companies to buy back their own shares, and to enable dealers
to engage in short selling. A new take-over code and set of conduct of
business rules are in the pipeline.
None of this has been particularly popular with the broking community which
complains of over-regulation. But Mr Robert Owen, the SFC chairman, says:
'If you look at the international spectrum of levels of regulation, Hong
Kong is still quite firmly at the light end.'
Mr Francis Yuen, the chief executive of the exchange, says that the
regulation phase is now virtually complete, and the next phase will be the
development of new products, such as warrants, options, and securities from
the newly privatised sector in China - 'we could have a big role to play
there,' he says.
Innovations should be helped by new electronic trading and settlement
systems which the exchange hopes to introduce by the end of this year. The
systems have been subjected to lengthy delays, largely because of their high
cost. Although they are not vital to the numerically large number of small
local brokers, they are considered to be essential if Hong Kong is to hold
its place in the international investment community. Issues such as this
have aggravated members of the international broking community who feel they
do not have a big enough voice in the exchange's affairs.
A trickier problem confronts the exchange with the steady departure of many
of its listed companies for safe havens in Bermuda and the Cayman Islands.
About 30 per cent are now based elsewhere, or planning to go. Jardine
Matheson, which led the exodus, has applied for a special form of 'exempt
listing' that would enable its shares to be traded in Hong Kong, but without
being fully subject to Hong Kong rules.
The exchange and the SFC both know that permission in this case would set a
major precedent which could seriously undermine the exchange. Yet they are
keen to find a solution which would retain as many listings in Hong Kong as
possible.
Despite the corporate exodus, there has been little sign of a drift away
among Hong Kong's financial community itself. The number of licensed brokers
remains high (there are about 900 of which 700 are active), and many
international firms use Hong Kong as a regional base. GT Management, for
example, processes trades from as far afield as Australia and New Zealand
there.
The international investment community is dominated by two locally-based
firms, Wardley, the merchant banking arm of the Hongkong Bank group, and
Jardine Fleming, the joint venture between Robert Fleming of London and
Jardine Matheson.
Wardley manages about USDollars 10bn of funds worldwide, and Jardine
slightly less - about USDollars 8bn. Other leading players include Schroders
and Fidelity of the US. Jardine was one of the few investment banking firms
in the region which increased its profits last year, despite the
difficulties in the international markets. Mr Alan Smith, the managing
director, points out that his firm made more money than big London-based
names such as Schroders and Barings.
The Japanese investment community is also growing steadily. There are now 46
Japanese securities houses in Hong Kong, twice as many as there are in
London - 'it shows that worries about 1997 are much stronger in places like
the US and the UK than they are in Japan', says a government official.
Although Hong Kong must have lost some of its investment allure with the
transfer of so much of its private wealth overseas, its importance as a
regional centre has, if anything, grown with the steady opening up of the
Chinese market. The Hong Kong stock market has also surprised people with
its strength. It overcame political uncertainties to grow by six per cent
last year, and it put on another strong surge in the early weeks of this
year, pushing the Hang Seng Index close to a record high in early April.
Since then, worries about the airport have pulled it back.
Confidence has been helped by the consistency of the government's currency
strategy, which is based on the peg to the US dollar. Now seven years old,
the peg has withstood a number of political shocks as well as the pressures
of Hong Kong's recent bout of inflation. The Exchange Fund, which manages
the currency, has kept Hong Kong interest rates slightly higher than US as a
counter to the negative forces.
Among the prospects for the investment community is a new law creating the
legal framework for retirement schemes, which are the moment are funded
directly by employers. It is estimated that some 10,000 to 15,000 schemes
will have to be launched in the years ahead, providing considerable volumes
of business for the life insurance and fund management industries.
The government also intends to develop a debt market to help finance a
forecast budget deficit. The new pensions industry will play a role in that
 -'we want to build up an appetite among investors so that when we need the
money the market will be there,' says Mr David Nendick, the secretary for
monetary affairs.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
