<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAARFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Survey of Hong Kong (11): Still large and profitable -
Banking / The precautions that Hong Kong's international banking community
is making in advance of 1997
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE of the more sensitive barometers of the Hong Kong climate is the state
of its banks. On that score, the colony is holding up as well as can be
expected. Hong Kong's banking community remains large and profitable, though
it, too, is taking its precautions in advance of 1997.
The most conspicuous example of this was the Hongkong and Shanghai Banking
Corporation's decision at the beginning of this year to create a new holding
company, based in London.
While such a move might have had a devastating effect on confidence a year
or two ago, it passed with barely a ripple now - a sign of either Hong
Kong's resilience or its fatalism.
Otherwise the most notable departures from the Hong Kong bank scene have
been for reasons unconnected with 1997 - such as the withdrawal by some US
banks as part of their wider retrenchment from international banking, or the
more selective strategies adopted by some European banks, such as Lloyds.
But these have been offset by new arrivals, and the decision of some banks
like Bank of America and Yasuda Trust to establish their regional
headquarters there.
According to Mr Tony Nicolle, the Banking Commissioner, the number of fully
licensed banks in Hong Kong at the end of last year was a record 168, which
'showed clearly that it was an attractive place for international banks to
establish'.
In his 1990 report, he said profitability for most banks remained good, and
their capital was well above levels set by international standards. Hong
Kong's future as an international financial centre 'seems bright', he wrote.
Although the Hongkong Bank now has a different home, its focus is still very
much on Hong Kong where it dominates the overall market and, through
subsidiaries like the Hang Seng Bank and Wardley, the merchant bank, various
market segments as well. But the bank reported its first profits decline in
recent history last year because of severe losses suffered in other markets
like the US, Europe and Australia - all the result of efforts to diversify
geographically.
Mr William Purves, the chairman, rejects suggestions that the message is
that the bank should stick to markets it knows. He says the Hongkong Bank
had made a decision to become an international institution, and he still
believed that to be correct.
However, the bank suffered a setback with last December's decision not to
proceed with its proposed alliance with the Midland Bank because of
difficulties on both sides.
Mr Purves does not rule some kind of alliance in future - 'we will revisit
that scene at the end of this year,' he says. Hongkong Bank is still keen to
strengthen its presence in Europe, the one major geographical region where
it lacks a big operation.
The other leading players on the local market are headed by the Bank of
China and its 12 'sister banks,' now headquartered in Hong Kong's tallest
skyscraper, and growing steadily as links with China become stronger.
Standard Chartered, the other note issuing bank along with the Hongkong
Bank, is fighting to recover ground lost during the turmoil of the 1980s.
Staff and strategies have been overhauled, and American expertise has been
brought in to sharpen its marketing edge.
'We are still only scratching the surface of the market,' says Mr Ian
Wilson, chief manager of the Hong Kong branch.
Among overseas banks, Citibank is an important player, as are certain
European banks such as Banque National de Paris. But the largest growing
foreign community is now the Japanese who have steadily expanded their share
of commercial banking, though they have yet to move into retail banking.
They have 31 full-licensed banks, compared to 20 from the US and 15 from
China. Hong Kong officials say their presence reflects both their eagerness
to expand their Asian and Chinese business, but also a desire to escape
their toughly regulated home market.
Although it is clear that Hong Kong banking is a profitable business, part
of the difficulty of judging the health of the banking community is the fact
that none of the leading players publishes full information.
The local banks maintain secret inner reserves - though the Hongkong Bank is
likely to start making full disclosure in a couple of years - and
London-based Standard Chartered does not break out details of its Hong Kong
branches.
Their position is also protected to some extent by an cartel-like agreement
among the main banks on interest rates.
The future of this agreement is moot. Mr Purves argues that it helps to
sustain a strong and flourishing banking industry, but government officials
say it is being undermined by innovation in the market.
Now that the government has developed ways of controlling the liquidity of
the banking market, it is not needed for monetary policy reasons either.
Apart from retail banking, the main avenues where bankers see growth are in
trade finance and services related to the growing personal wealth of the
region - such as private banking and custody services. The colony's growing
links with China also hold out prospects for a wide variety of financial
services. Citibank already uses Chinese labour to process its letters of
credit in the Shenzen economic zone.
The government can be expected to encourage the growth of the banking sector
as the Hong Kong economy shifts towards becoming more services-based. Banks
currently employ about 75,000 people, and the number has been rising each
year. However the number of banks may shrink.
Some observers expect to see more mergers among the small family-owned banks
as competitive pressures increase.
