<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAAPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Survey of Hong Kong (7): Slowdown reflects uncertainties -
The Economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT IS a sign of the times that Hong Kong has become the slowest-growing of
the Far East's dragons.
After pushing ahead at an average of 11 per cent a year between 1986 and
1988, Hong Kong's economy grew by only 2.4 per cent last year. In his March
Budget, Sir Piers Jacobs, the Financial Secretary, forecast that growth this
year will be about 3.5 per cent, rising to an average of 5.5 per cent a year
over the first half of the decade.
This marked slowdown to levels in line with more mature economies is partly
a reflection of more uncertain times on the world markets which are so vital
to Hong Kong's economic fortunes. But it also has its cause in the colony's
own problems, particularly the uncertainties created by 1997 and a severe
labour shortage.
Like everything else in Hong Kong, the economic slowdown can be partly
traced back to the shocks created by Tienanmen Square in June 1989. The rest
of that year saw a tailing off in growth (GDP was up only 2.3 per cent), and
any recovery that might have occurred last year was quickly snuffed out by
the Gulf crisis and deepening recession in key client economies like the US
and the UK.
Domestically produced exports rose by only one per cent last year, though
this was compensated by a 16 per cent rise in re-exports (mainly goods which
have been sent for processing in China's cheap labour markets).
Slower economic growth has not, however, helped to ease Hong Kong's
straining capacity. With unemployment at a negligible 1.8 per cent, there is
an acute labour shortage which is pushing up wage levels and contributing to
an alarming rise in inflation.
The consumer price index rose by over 10 per cent in 1989 and by 9.8 per
cent last year. The forecast for this year is 9.5 per cent, but the rates in
January and February were 10.8 per cent and 11.9 per cent with further price
rises due from tax increases in the Budget. The government has tried to ease
these strains by relaxing immigration rules. But the causes have their roots
in profound structural problems which will not be solved that easily. The
monetary levers which other countries use to control inflation are not
available in Hong Kong because the currency is pegged to the US dollar.
Interest rates must be kept broadly in line with US rates.
This suggests that inflation could become an unwelcome political aggravation
for the colony's government at a sensitive time. Externally, however,
inflation is having less impact. The currency's pegged value of Dollars 7.8
against the US dollar has been holding-up well. This is mainly because Hong
Kong's exports have remained competitive with prices rising only about three
per cent, thanks largely to the extremely low labour costs available in
China's economic zones.
The immediate prospects for the economy depend on recovery in foreign
markets. Ms Elley Mao, the government's principal economist, says that the
Budget forecasts were prepared before the end of the Gulf war and may
therefore be a bit pessimistic, particularly if the US recovers faster than
expected.
But others are more cautious. Mr Alan McLean, the chief economist at the
Hongkong Bank, originally forecast 3.6 per cent growth this year. But he
says he would shave that back a bit now - 'where is the growth going to come
from?' he asks.
Longer-term judgments need to take account of deeper shifts that are taking
place in Hong Kong's economic structures. Broadly, there are three:
First, the colony is changing from a manufacturing centre to a
services-oriented economy. More and more labour intensive industry is
migrating across the border to China where workers earn USDollars 2-3 for a
12 hour day.
In 1989, manufacturing accounted for only 18 per cent of GDP compared to 67
per cent for services. Nearly two-thirds of the workforce is now in service
industries, mainly wholesale and retail trading, tourism and financial
services.
This is clearly a sign of Hong Kong's economic evolution. But it does also
increase the colony's vulnerability because service industries can take
flight much more easily than manufacturing if the political climate becomes
unpleasant.
Mr John Greenwood, chairman of GT Management, points out that the capital
inflow which boosted Hong Kong's economy in the 1970s and early 1980s has
been reversed since the Sino-British negotiations on the colony's future in
1983-84.
The huge outflow must be hitting the pace of investment. Hence its need for
big infrastructure projects like the new airport.
Second, Hong Kong is moving steadily upmarket. As any tourist shopper
quickly discovers, it is a place for high quality and, if not high, then
certainly higher prices. Street markets which once displayed cheap plastic
goods and synthetic fabrics now offer stylish designer items, silks and
top-of-the line gadgetry. The important goal now is not just to produce but
to add as much value as possible.
Third, the structure of Hong Kong's markets is changing. Despite the setback
of Tienanmen, the China factor looms steadily larger. It is estimated that
up to 2m mainland Chinese are now processing goods for Hong Kong businesses,
helping the boom in re-exports which is providing the much-needed offset for
the slump in domestically produced exports. Hong Kong-based services
companies like banks, accountants, insurers and even the stock exchange are
peddling their expertise across the border.
This is speeding a further shift in dependence away from the US which has
traditionally taken about 30 per cent of Hong Kong's production. Japan,
Germany and even East Europe are seen as promising long-term markets.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-795</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAAOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Survey of Hong Kong (10): A severe brain drain - Emigrant
total may reach 60,000 this year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HONG KONG is suffering from a severe 'brain drain' as wealthy and
well-educated people leave the colony in search of a foreign passport. The
problem first appeared in 1987 and the numbers of emigrants has risen ever
since. This year 60,000 people are expected to leave, or more than 1,000 a
week.
They are concerned about Hong Kong's return to Chinese sovereignty in 1997
and what it will mean for individual freedoms, prospects for their children
and living standards. Among many other reasons, some people also say they
are worried about Daya Bay, a nearby Chinese nuclear power station due to
begin operations next year.
The number of students leaving Hong Kong to study overseas has also risen
rapidly, reflecting a shortage of places in the colony as well as political
worries. Last year nearly 25,000 left for the main destinations of Canada,
the US, Australia and the UK, compared to 19,169 in 1989 and 15,026 in 1988.
Although the vast majority of these students return after completing their
studies, there are worries that once they have gone abroad they are more
likely, and more qualified, to leave Hong Kong again.
The brain drain is a major headache for companies who face high staff
turnover, dwindling employee loyalty and competitors poaching staff. In
order to cope, companies are offering higher salaries and improved training.
Larger companies are trying to organise postings overseas. Some companies
are even offering special bonuses of up to HKDollars 1m to staff staying
until after 1997.
As talented people continue to leave, there are worries overall management
standards are slipping as less experienced people are promoted to fill
senior vacancies too quickly. Higher bonuses and salaries to attract and
keep staff continue to raise operating costs and contribute to Hong Kong's
high inflation rate.
The government hopes the number of people leaving has now plateaued after a
record 62,000 people left last year. About one-in-four were professionals or
managers. The most popular destinations are Canada, Australia and the US.
The government also hopes 'insurance schemes' like a British Nationality
package, designed to give passports to 50,000 key heads of families, will
persuade people wanting to emigrate to stay in the colony longer.
The package was less well received than expected. Just over 55,000 people
applied for 32,700 passports in the largest 'general occupational' class.
Within this class, some categories - such as lawyers and translators - were
over-subscribed in the first tranche. But the important category of managers
and administrators was 10 per cent under-subscribed. The first passports
under the package are due to be handed out in June.
The US now has a similar scheme. This offers about 10,000 employees of US
companies in Hong Kong, and their families, visas which can be delayed until
2002. About 6,000 applications have been filed so far. The US has also
doubled its quota for Hong Kong migrants to 10,000 a year and this will
almost double again in 1994.
Australia, which this year expects to take 17,000 Hong Kong emigrants, does
not offer a specific package for Hong Kong employees of Australian
companies. But under existing emigration rules some emigrants can delay
taking up permanent residency in Australia for up to five years. France and
Belgium also offer smaller packages to employees of their companies in Hong
Kong.
Singapore has a scheme to attract 25,000 technicians and skilled workers and
their families. These people can delay taking up residence for five years.
So far, 17,500 families have been approved while a further 12,500
professionals have been cleared under a separate package, according to
Gordon Seow, Singapore consul in Hong Kong.
If these schemes succeed by keeping businessmen and professionals in the 30
to 40 age group, the profile of emigrants in the next few years is likely to
shift towards both younger and older people, who are less economically
active. Even so, the government does not expect the overall number of
emigrants will decline from around 60,000 a year for the next few years.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-796</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAANFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Survey of Hong Kong (9): Companies seeking domicile overseas
 -Corporate Exodus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS HONG KONG people head overseas in search of a foreign passport, Hong Kong
companies are also looking abroad for their own type of 'insurance policy'.
Hongkong and Shanghai Bank and Jardine Matheson and, two of the best-known
companies in Hong Kong, have announced plans to distance themselves from
Hong Kong. Other companies are moving legal domicile, applying for overseas
listings and investing overseas. These measures combine a desire to protect
overseas assets with a natural diversification in search of new investment
opportunities.
A total of 68 of Hong Kong's 306 listed companies have switched domicile to
places like Bermuda and the Cayman Islands. Taking into account companies
now planning to move, bankers estimate that a third of Hong Kong's stock
market will soon be domiciled overseas.
Hongkong Bank's decision last December to set up a new holding company in
London was the most significant switch of domicile since Jardine started the
flow in 1984 and went to Bermuda. Hongkong Bank said it was moving to
reassure customers and banking partners worried about 1997.
Jardine Matheson, controlled from London by Mr Henry Keswick, is asking Hong
Kong to create a special category of 'exempt listings' for big international
companies. This would allow Jardine's shares to be traded in Hong Kong,
where they account for about 10 per cent of market turnover, while
transferring regulation of the company to London.
The proposal is being studied by the Securities and Futures Commission who
will release a public consultation paper on the subject in June or July. One
problem is that London's takeover code does not extend to foreign
incorporated companies.
Jardine's proposal has been criticised by Legislative Councillors who
accused the company of seeking special privileges and trying to avoid
takeover rules in London and Hong Kong.
No one knows how many companies could follow Jardine and switch their
primary listing overseas. But the proposal is important. If Jardine was
granted exemptions from some Hong Kong regulations, for example the takeover
code, smaller companies would press for similar exemptions and this could
undermine Hong Kong's reputation.
Other companies have sought overseas listings to raise capital and attract
new shareholders. A stronger Hong Kong's stock market this year allowed five
companies to launch rights issues in the first quarter, compared to two in
the same period last year and 10 in the first quarter of 1989.
Nevertheless, Hong Kong's volatility and low overall ratings are pressuring
some companies to go overseas - 'the likelihood of Hong Kong being an
international financial centre after 1997 is remote and that affects its
stock market,' says Stephen Clark, director of Anglo Chinese Corporate
Finance.
Gold Peak Industries, an electronics manufacturer, last year listed its
battery division on the Singapore stock market. The Singapore company is now
trading on a price earnings multiple of 18 times, compared to the holding
company's 8.3 times in Hong Kong.
Video Technology, which claims more than 50 per cent of the US market for
electronic learning aids, last year delisted from Hong Kong and is now
planning a listing in London, New York or Singapore - 'the delisting was a
purely a money decision. The price quoted in Hong Kong was undervalued,'
according to Mr William Ho, managing director.
These companies have been able to go overseas because they have foreign
markets and their own brand names. But most Hong Kong manufacturers make
products under contract for foreign companies. They would gain little from a
foreign listing because their shares would still likely be rated on a Hong
Kong multiple.
Other companies with most of their assets in Hong Kong, such as local banks,
utilities and property companies, would still be treated as Hong Kong
companies if they listed overseas. Bankers agree the majority of Hong Kong
companies therefore have to stay in the colony.
Although public listed companies will stay in Hong Kong, private money is
flowing overseas. Hong Kong Chinese have traditionally diversified their
wealth outside Hong Kong. The process has been accelerated by the brain
drain. According to some estimates, based on information from destination
countries, more than HKDollars 50bn is being invested overseas each year by
emigrants.
The corporate exodus has co-incided with natural expansion overseas by Hong
Kong companies. Companies like retail group Dairy Farm has made overseas
acquisitions because prospects for further growth in Hong Kong were limited.
Dairy Farm, an associate of Jardine Matheson, has made acquisitions in the
UK Australia and Spain. But it is one of the few examples of successful
overseas moves by Hong Kong companies.
Groups such as New World Development and Sir Yue Kong Pao's World
International have bought overseas hotel chains - Ramada and Omni,
respectively - while Mr Li Ka-shing bought Canadian oil and gas company
Husky Oil.
But, so far, none of these moves have proved successful. Some analysts argue
Hong Kong companies, designed to react quickly to business opportunities in
fast growing economies, do poorly in mature economies where management needs
to be well structured.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-797</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAAMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Survey of Hong Kong (4): Government feels strain - The
build-up to legislative council elections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN ELLIOTT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HONG KONG'S stretched government machine, which is already having trouble
coping with the complexities of the run-up to 1997, will come under
considerably increased strains this autumn when the first-ever
directly-elected candidates take their seats in the Legislative Council.
Party politics are emerging for the first time, polarised around attitudes
to China, in readiness for the elections which take place in September. In
addition, the 18 people who are to be directly elected to the 60-person
council will constantly be performing for their constituences, electorates
and pressure groups.
These developments will break down some of the consensus traditions on which
the authority of Hong Kong's non-democratic colonial administration has been
based, and will lead to more confrontations in the council.
'It will become more difficult and time-consuming to get decisions through
Legco - and we must discover how to make that work,' says Mr Hamish MacLeod
who takes over as Financial Secretary in August. 'For me, there will be
pressures about what budgets are attainable and how to cope with possibly
unpopular issues, for example like a sales tax, which may be sensible long
term but difficult to sell in the short term'.
The September elections follow recent district board and regional council
elections, during which party politics have started to emerge.
Liberal-leaning groups that favour a faster development of democracy and are
prepared to confront Peking did better on the district boards than business
groupings and pro-Peking trade unions which want closer relations with
China. But a rough 50-50 split is expected in the legislative council
elections.
The process of democratisation was agreed last year during the final
drafting in Peking of the Basic Law that will govern the territory after
1997. China's views predominated and the council's 18 directly seats will go
up to only 20 in 1995, 24 in 1999 and 30 (50 per cent) in 2003.
The 18 this September will be elected from nine constituencies on a
first-past-the-post basis.
The rest of the 60 seats will be filled by: an appointed vice president, who
will deputise for the governor as council chairman; the government's top
three officials (the chief secretary, financial secretary and attorney
general); 17 lay government appointees; and 21 indirectly elected people
(more than half of whom are expected to be pro-government) from functional
constituencies based on business areas and occupations such as financial
services, construction and lawyers.
The proceedings will therefore still be government-dominated, despite the
expected breakdown of a governing consensus.
A currently close and almost clubbish relationship between senior
departmental secretaries and council members will be reduced because seven
secretaries will lose their existing seats and will only be present when
summoned to present policies or to account for themselves.
No governing party is envisaged in the democratisation plans because no
single party can achieve an overall majority of the seats. This is in line
with the wishes of China which dislikes the emergence of pro-democracy
parties and wants Legco merely to be an adjucnt to a powerful executive
machine which will be headed by a Peking-approved chief executive from 1997.
'We aim to exert public moral pressure so that we can stop the government
winning arguments simply by stating that it is right,' says Mr Martin Lee,
Hong Kong's most prominent politician and leader of the main pro-democracy
party.
'But the government will probably be terrified of being seen to be making
concession to us over the heads of the indirectly elected members - so there
is likely to be more confrontation when there could be consensus'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
