<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Survey of Hong Kong (5): Lively Liberal campaign - Angus
Foster highlights the two main political groupings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UNITED Democrats of Hong Kong, led by Mr Martin Lee, an outspoken
lawyer, is the colony's best-known political party.
It was formed last year from a collection of liberal pressuregroups united
by their opposition to China's Tiananmen Square crackdown. As well as
prominent leaders such as Mr Lee, university lecturer Mr Yeung Sum and
teacher Mr Szeto Wah, the party has strong grass roots support among Hong
Kong's middle class and younger voters.
In the March district board election, the party won 56 of 80 seats it
contested, leading to its claim to be Hong Kong's largest political party.
In the September elections, the United Democrats will field 14 candidates on
a populist platform calling for full democracy for Hong Kong. It will also
push for stricter environmental protection. In a bid to attract working
class voters, the party will campaign for higher public spending and oppose
the importation of foreign labour.
But the party will be attacked for being idealist, for its confrontational
stance towards China and its links with groups branded as 'counter
revolutionary' by Peking. Mr Lee and Mr Szeto were both expelled from the
Peking-appointed Basic Law Drafting Committee after their criticism of China
in 1989.
Business and conservative groups will also claim the United Democrats'
public spending policies will raise taxes. Because many of the party's
leaders are professionals, its opponents will claim they are more interested
in emigrating.
Other liberal groups contesting the elections include the Hong Kong
Democratic Foundation, Meeting Point and the Association for Democracy and
People's Livelihood. Successful candidates from these parties will probably
link up with the United Democrats to form a liberal platform in the
Legislative Council. The Democratic Foundation was founded by two prominent
legislative councillors, Dr Leong Che-hung and Mr Jimmy McGregor, a former
government official and one of the few British expatriates involved in
politics. The grouping has 360 members and will field between one and four
candidates. But Mr McGregor has decided not to recontest his seat after
falling out with his constituents.
The Foundation will push for a faster pace of democratic reform although it
sees its role as moderating between the mainstream liberals and
conservatives. But outside middle class constituencies, the Foundation will
have little support.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III Photograph Martin Lee, outspoken lawyer (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-799</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAAKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Survey of Hong Kong (6): Pro-Peking lobby - Angus Foster
highlights the two main political groupings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GROUPS united by their conservatism, broad pro-China views and determination
to undermine the liberals may form an informal alliance to contest the
September elections.
The alliance includes the pro-business Liberal Democratic Federation, the
leftist Federation of Trade Unions and traditional rural interests
represented by the Heung Yee Kuk.
The grouping has the blessing of China and will claim it can influence
China's policies towards Hong Kong. The grouping is committed to maintaining
Hong Kong's stability, a by-word for conservative economic management and
minimal democratisation.
But underlying differences, for example on labour policy, prevent the groups
co-operating too closely. In some constituencies they could work well
together, for example in the working class areas of Kowloon. But in others
they will compete and, in others still, their combined influence is weak.
The Liberal Democratic Federation grew from the conservative 'Group of 89'
business lobby, formed to protect business interests when Hong Kong's Basic
Law was being drafted.
The Liberal Democrats now have over 200 members, are well-funded and are
have the backing of top business tycoons including, it is believed, Mr Li
Ka-shing. The party will field candidates for between five and eight seats.
It has the support of several Hong Kong political heavyweights, including
legislative councillor Maria Tam, a vice chairman and possible election
candidate, and prominent businessman Vincent Lo. However, other leading
businessmen who were expected to join such as Stephen Cheong and Allen Lee,
both senior legislative councillors, have so far preferred to retain their
independence rather than be linked to a party.
Despite the advantages of funding and well known leaders, the Liberal
Democrats are poorly organised. They are more used to the politics of
patronage and privilege, they enjoy scarce media access and command little
grass roots support or experience.
The pro-Peking Federation of Trades Unions (FTU) is well organised and
claims a membership of 170,000 people. But membership is split across
constituencies. Outside urban areas like Kowloon the FTU will have to seek
other supporters, according to Mr Tam Yiu-chung, FTU member and legislative
councillor.
The FTU will field two or three candidates, one of which is likely to be
prominent unionist Mr Cheng Kai-nam. In what will be one of the most high
profile races, he intends to stand against Mr Martin Lee in Island East.
The Heung Yee Kuk, representing rural interests from Hong Kong's New
Territories, could also play an important role in the elections. The Kuk has
traditionally shunned politics. But, fearing its influence is waning, it has
helped set up the 120-strong Federation for the Stability of Hong Kong.
Lau Wong-fat, chairman of the Kuk, says the new organisation could evolve
into a political party 'at some stage.'
The Kuk claims to represent 500,000 people who look to it for guidance. But
as more people have moved into the New Territories from the urban areas, it
is not known how much support the Kuk can still mobilise.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III Photograph Vincent Lo, a prominent businessman and supporter
of the Liberal Democrats. He is this year's chairman of the General Chamber
of Commerce and was also the Convenor of the Group of 89. (Omitted).
