<DOCNO>FT911-801</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAAIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Survey of Hong Kong (2): Peking seeks more power - A
showdown in relations with China
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN ELLIOTT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE always had to be a bust-up. When Britain signed away its rights to
Hong Kong in December 1984 and agreed that China would resume sovereignty 13
years later in 1997, it was inevitable that a struggle for power would one
day disrupt Sinologist diplomats' dreams of a cosy handover and cast doubt
over the colony's autonomy.
It was generally assumed that the crisis would break in the early 1990s when
the proximity of the handover, perhaps combined with some upsurge in China,
would lead Peking to try progressively to supplant British rule ahead of
time.
What no-one could have guessed was that the showdown would come over
something so basically harmless - and so economically important - as an
airport. Nor could one have guessed how quickly Peking would win and that at
the same time it would attempt to encroach on the most sensitive of all
areas - the independence of the judiciary.
Yet that is that has happened in the past 18 months. Peking has forced Sir
David Wilson, the colony's governor, and Sir David Ford, the chief
secretary, to delay plans for a HKDollars 100bn international airport until
they win its agreement.
It is worried about the airport draining fiscal reserves, but it basic
demand - which Hong Kong has been opposing - is for extensive scrutiny and
consultations leading to consensus on decisions such as financial borrowings
and contracts. Hong Kong says that this would amount to control and would
cause long delays in decision-making on the airport.
It would also set a precedent for China to gain control far ahead of 1997
over economic and fiscal policy and other issues ranging from education
policy to choice of top government officials.
China has also demanded extensive rights over the choice of judges on a
planned Court of Final Appeal before and after 1997, encroaching on the
autonomy of the colony's judicial system. This is one of several items
caught up in a Sino-British Joint Liaison Group which has made little
progress with its basic work of making detailed preparations for 1997.
These moves have been made so blatantly and effectively by China that they
have confounded British sinologists, whose personal and professional creed
rests on a belief that one can do business with Peking and that deals, once
done, are honoured.
The deal in this case is the 1984 Sino-British Joint Declaration on the 1997
handover which under-pins British rule, albeit with increased consultation
as the handover approaches.
It pledges that the new post-1997 Special Administrative Region of Hong Kong
will have a 'high degree of autonomy' for the next 50 years in everything
but defence and foreign affairs, and that it will be 'vested with executive,
legislative and independent judicial power, including that of final
adjudication'.
No-where in the joint declaration, according to British experts, is there
any justification for the sort of control that China is seeking so long
before 1997 over airport decisions, nor for the influence it is demanding on
the choice of final appeal judges.
Behind China's move, it is assumed, is deep distrust of Britain as a
colonial power, plus perhaps a wish to settle 150-year-old scores for
China's perceived humiliation when Hong Kong was colonised. There is
believed to be a fear that the British, behaving like other departing
colonial powers elsewhere, will cream off the riches, leaving behind a
run-down fragile economy.
In this context, UK companies would win airport construction contracts and
so drain Hong Kong's HKDollars 72bn accumulated fiscal reserves.
Peking's 1989 Tiananmen Square crisis heightened the distrust and concern,
firstly because of the way that hundreds of thousands of Hong Kong people
massed on the streets in support of China's pro-democracy students, and
secondly because the UK and Hong Kong governments then stepped in with a
morale-boosting package. That package included plans for the airport, as
well as a Bill of Rights and British passports for Hong Kong people, which
sharpened China's anger.
Peking officials then realised that the airport was the one issue they could
directly affect because franchise periods and debt repayments would not
start till 1997 or later: international investment would therefore not be
forthcoming unless China gave its backing.
China probably always intended to interfere and keep Britain in check by
demanding a measure of control in the second half of the 1984-97 transition
period, which has just begun. The airport has enabled it to do this earlier
than might otherwise have been the case.
The intention to interfere has been evident in the detailed work of the
Joint Liaison Group which has made scarcely any progress since June 1989.
Its most well-known points of deadlock concern the appointment of judges to
a new Court of Final Appeal (which is needed to replace London's Privy
Council), and Hong Kong's right to re-develop defence establishment land
before 1997.
But there has also been extremely slow progress on more mundane but
important issues such as the negotiation of new air service agreements to
replace UK-based arrangements. Only about six have been completed out of 30
that will be needed. China has also blocked progress on other issues such as
investment protection agreements, re-arrangement of hundreds of
international treaties on detailed issues.
Such stone-walling by Peking has made Hong Kong realise - not for the first
time - that it is weak when it faces a determined Chinese government.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page II Map (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-802</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAAHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Survey of Hong Kong (1): Vital factors for the future - Hong
Kong thrives when business confidence is strong, but this resilience has
been shaken recently by Peking's hardliners who are seeking more power, both
before and after the UK hands over sovereignty of the colonial territory to
China in 1997
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN ELLIOTT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SUCCESS of Hong Kong as one of the world's great economic growth stories
depends on three primary factors: a deep-water harbour which is its only
natural resource, a population of approaching 6m largely made up of Chinese
refugees who are desperate to capitalise on their money-making skills, and a
tolerant Chinese communist government to the north which allows this
rampantly free-market British colony to do its own thing.
Together, these three factors are needed to generate the confidence for
expansion which produces the high annual rates of economic growth of 12-14
per cent achieved in the late 1980s. The result is an annual income per
capita this year of about USDollars 13,400, second only to Japan among
Asia's industrialised economies and roughly the same as Singapore.
But remove any one of the factors and confidence crumbles. The domestic will
to invest wanes, international companies look elsewhere to places like
Singapore, and speculation begins about how long it will take for Hong Kong
to decay from being the world's eleventh largest trading economy into a
glitzy multi-storey version of Shanghai.
That is what has been happening since June 1989 when China's tolerance was
dramatically altered by hundreds of thousands of Hong Kong people marching
in support of the student demonstrations in Peking's Tiananmen Square. Hong
Kong consequently appeared to China to be more of a subversive political
threat than an economic asset and, as a spin-off, Peking's distrust of
Britain increased.
Peking's hardliners therefore decided to step up their control of the colony
before and after the UK hands over sovereignty in 1997. This has humiliated
the government which has been forced, step by step, to accept that Peking
has a major say over a HKDollars 100bn international airport project.
Before 1989, the government saw no need to provide more than the most
cursory information on the airport to Peking. Now it has had to admit that
it can neither sustain domestic support for the project, nor raise essential
international finance, unless China gives its blessing.
That has been a hard pill for a tightly-controlled colonial regime to
swallow. Even harder is China's parallel demand for virtual agreement in
advance on all major decisions - especially all debts and obligations that
straddle the 1997 handover. Subjects such as large capital projects,
education and housing policy, and appointments of judges and top civil
servants are expected to be included.
A long-running row over these issues has delayed the airport and undermined
the authority of the government. On a broader perspective, it has also
demonstrated that China will always interfere in the territory's affairs,
and that it will do so more aggressively when Peking feels politically
threatened (as with the Tiananmen Square crisis) or when it feels that its
1997 legacy is in some way at stake.
Some Sinologists in the British foreign service cling to a dream that China
will only demand control till the British leave in 1997 and that it will
then allow the 'high degree of autonomy' it has pledged. This seems
unrealistically optimistic. There is little support in Hong Kong for a
series of confrontations - such as the airport row - during the next six
years, because China cannot lose. The UK government is also assumed to want
to avoid being constantly involved in tortuous battles with Peking.
This leads to the conclusion that it is better to tackle the problem now by
trying to allay China's fears and gain its trust by recognising its
legitimate post-1997 concerns and by involving it in decisions. Hong Kong
is, in any case, inextricably linked economically with China. This is best
illustrated by concern over the future of China's 'most favoured nation'
trading status with the US. Cancellation would hurt the colony far more than
China and would, it is estimated, wipe up to 2 per cent off annual economic
growth which is forecast to reach only 3.5 to 4.5 per cent this year.
China and Hong Kong are each other's largest trading partners and China
accounts for more than 80 per cent of the colony's entrepot re-export trade.
At least 2m employees in the southern province of Guangdong carry out Hong
Kong-related work, and estimates suggest that as many as 50,000 Hong Kong
technical and managerial staff work regularly in China.
But economic links develop more easily than political and administrative
co-operation. There is a deep-seated resistance at the top of the colony's
civil service against China being allowed a say in the local affairs - and
this would have to be changed before any real co-operation could take place.
Mr Douglas Hurd, British Foreign Secretary, signalled such a a change when
he said recently that it was 'light-headed nonsense' to believe, as some
people did in Britain and Hong Kong, that Peking should be kept 'as distant
as possible'.
Involving Peking will, however, need to be done in such as way that
minimises the risk of China's bureaucratic approach slowing down economic
developments. The creation of precedents for China to interfere widely after
1997 would also need to be kept to a minimum. Such involvement seems however
to be the only solution for the future.
Hong Kong thrives when confidence is strong. As a highly flexible trading
city, it is adept at overcoming challenges and setbacks, but the confidence
will not survive a series of airport-style confrontations running up to
1997.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page I Photograph The new Bank of China headquarters towers over Hong
Kong Central, a monumental symbol of China's powerful impact on the
territory (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-803</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAAGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Survey of The Food Industry (6): Eastern markets expand -
Opportunity knocks for machinery makers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE world's food equipment manufacturers can look forward to some
mouth-watering prospects in the 1990s, even if the start of the decade has
shown that - contrary to the belief of some in the industry - they are not
recession-proof.
In spite of a series of takeovers in the 1980s by the two biggest players,
APV of the UK and Sweden's Alfa-Laval, the industry remains fragmented by
different worldwide fashions in food. APV, the world leader, had sales of
Pounds 928m last year, almost all of which was in the food business, which
compares with its own estimate of Pounds 11.5bn for the world market.
But the more ambitious companies have realised for some time that the
juiciest prizes in the next few years - in eastern Europe and the Far East -
will go to those with the financial staying power and geographical spread to
match the increasingly international outlook of the big food processors.
'As the market place changes, and some of the medium-sized customers
disappear, suppliers will have to come into line,' says Mr Bo Wirsen,
president of Alfa-Laval's food business.
Until very recently, the gradual process of concentration in the industry
was characterised by horizontal integration. APV's transformation since the
mid-1980s is the clearest example: through the takeovers of Baker Perkins,
the UK bakery and confectionery equipment producer, Pasilac, a big Danish
dairy equipment maker, and Rosista, the German producer of carbonated drink
equipment, APV has doubled in size and gained the broadest product range in
the industry.
At the same time APV has made a number of smaller acquisitions, with the
principal aim, says Mr Neil French, finance director, of filling a specific
gap in the product range. These deals reflect the continuing attraction of
small companies with a strong position in a market niche.
APV nearly bit off more than it could chew, however, and Sir Peter Cazalet,
chairman, says that, with eight takeovers in 1989, it had to spend
considerable management time on handling the new arrivals. The City was
relieved to see APV make just one small acquisition in 1990, the NZDollars
8.4m (Pounds 2.88m) purchase of Moffat Appliances, a New Zealand catering
equipment producer.
Alfa-Laval has also been on the takeover trail, making six acquisitions in
its food business over the last four years, but it was its own takeover,
agreed in January, which created an important precedent for the food
equipment industry. In the industry's first significant attempt at vertical
integration Tetra Pak, the Swedish-owned milk and juice packaging group, is
paying SKr 16.25bn (Pounds 1.53bn) for Alfa-Laval, of which food equipment
is only the second biggest sector after industrial equipment.
Mr Wirsen says the deal is 'a rather logical type of integration,' but in
March the European Commission said it had 'serious doubts' about the merger
on competition grounds and announced a full inquiry.
The Commission said the combination of the two companies' products could
create or strengthen a dominant position in the EC food processing machine
sector or the packaging sector. 'Its competitors are able to provide either
food processing or packaging machines, but not both,' it said. That,
however, is debatable.
Mr Wirsen stresses that Alfa-Laval will be keen to ensure it continues to do
business with competitors of Tetra Pak and, in the short-term, co-operation
between the two companies will be limited to possible co-ordination of
marketing and servicing at the request of customers.
In the longer term, though, Mr Wirsen hopes the link-up will aid the search
for new and improved technical solutions in liquid engineering, especially
in situations where it would require the two viewpoints to spot an
opportunity.
The Alfa-Laval takeover creates two very different companies at the top of
the industry, and the split is emphasised by recent disposals at APV which
focus it even more on the core business of food processing equipment.
The medium-sized equipment suppliers running behind APV and Alfa-Laval might
be tempted to try vertical integration of their own, attracted by the
prospect of offering 'one-stop shopping' for customers.
Failing that, the traditional type of horizontal merger will still hold
sway. An example was a deal in March between two Lancashire companies which
saw Petrie and McNaught buying from Greenbank Engineering the rights to two
new processes which combine hot air and radio frequency energy to bake
foods.
It is in small, entrepreneurial companies such as these that some of the
industry's brightest ideas start, although generally the equipment producers
see themselves as a service industry responding to food manufacturers' needs
rather than shaping them. 'We don't try to second-guess our customers,' says
Sir Peter.
But rising development costs, and the need to respond more quickly and
substantially to customers' expansion plans, suggest that in the 1990s the
smaller players will increasingly be selling their ideas rather than
developing them in-house.
APV, for example, has acquired the technology to produce so-called
'Sintermatic sausages,' skinless sausages which are kept from falling apart
by coagulation of protein around the edge of the product. APV is spending
about Pounds 500,000 developing the machinery to produce these sausages,
which will save processors from buying sausage skins and even offer the
intriguing prospect of new shapes for sausages.
Small companies will also find it difficult to offer their clients
facilities that might help the larger groups win big contracts. APV's Pounds
30m-plus factory being built at Peterborough will have a research laboratory
next door with rooms where customers can use APV equipment to develop their
products.
This investment should help APV benefit from any upturn in markets currently
suffering from difficult trading conditions, such as the UK and US. The
company has undoubtedly been much harder hit by recession than its Swedish
rival: while Alfa-Laval's food business lifted profits by 50 per cent last
year to SKr357m, APV suffered a 34 per cent fall in pre-tax profits to
Pounds 40.2m.
The discrepancy partly reflects the fact that Alfa-Laval has concentrated on
fewer customer segments and made more progress than its UK rival in
assimilating its acquisitions and introducing operating efficiencies.
But APV is catching up, and Sir Peter is encouraged by prospects in the UK,
which suggest that the current reluctance by customers to commit to orders
is due to short-term economic factors.
In the long-term, two key factors justify the industry's optimism. In
western markets, the maturity of the food industry will encourage a
never-ending search for new ideas, and that will normally produce orders for
new equipment.
According to a report in February by Frost &amp; Sullivan, greater demand for
snack and thermoformed pack foods is likely to boost European sales of form,
fill and seal machines from Dollars 720.5m in 1989 to Dollars 1.18bn by
1995.
The largely untapped markets of the Third World and eastern Europe provide
the second big opportunity for the western equipment manufacturers. In the
Third World, Mr French hopes that the next decade will see countries
achieving the level of GNP where processed food takes over from more basic
fare.
Eastern Europe has already produced a few significant orders, notably APV's
Pounds 50m contract in 1989 for ten breakfast cereal lines in the Soviet
Union and a similarly-sized deal won by Alfa-Laval to provide ten margarine
plants. However, although democratisation in eastern Europe has brought more
inquiries, it has yet to be matched by much business, says Mr Wirsen.
The problem, of course, is money. In eastern Germany, however, German
financing is available and APV hopes to take advantage of this by selling
equipment made by western German subsidiaries.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
