<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Survey of The Food Industry (7): When waste is the issue -
Surplus packaging becomes a liability
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EARLIER this year, a group of activists from the Women's Environmental
Network went into the Islington branch of J Sainsbury, ripped off the
'excess' packaging on several items and dumped it at the supermarket's
check-outs.
Whether retailers and food manufacturers like it or not, packaging has
become a hot environmental concern because of its high visibility and
seeming wastefulness.
Supermarket chains have been quick to pick up on the mood and have launched
a variety of projects to seize the initiative. The Institute of Grocery
Distribution, a trade association for food manufacturers and retailers, has
set up an Industry Policy Issues Council, one of whose functions is to
examine what its members can jointly do to tackle environmental concerns.
Individual supermarket chains have also started schemes to encourage better
use of packaging materials and recycling. One of the most interesting of
these has been a pledge by Gateway that within five years it would cut by
half the energy consumption of the packaging passing through its 725 stores.
Mr Iain Wolsey, Gateway's marketing director, says this will involve
'painful changes' in the way that the company conducts its business. But he
adds: 'We have to solve this problem otherwise someone else will solve it
for us.'
Last year, Gateway asked the Landbank Consultancy, an environmental advisory
group led by Mr Bryn Jones, a former chairman of Greenpeace, to study ways
in which the company could improve its activities with regard to the
environment.
The consultancy drew up a report on the relative harmfulness of various
packaging materials which will now form the basis of Gateway's action
programme.
Mr Jones says the report would prove controversial but that he wishes to
stimulate a debate about the use of packaging materials.
'We want to talk to all the industries involved to see if we made any
mistakes. There are substantial environmental benefits to be gained from
discussing these issues together,' Mr Jones says.
The report studied various packaging materials and ranked them according to
environmental performance. It attached penalty points to different materials
depending on the degree of harmfulness to the environment.
The report listed the packaging materials which were least harmful to the
environment in the following order: re-usable glass, paper, laminates,
non-returnable glass, tinplate, aluminium and plastics.
The most important factor in determining environmental harmfulness was the
amount of energy a packaging material consumed throughout its entire life
cycle, from production to disposal.
On this scale, non-returnable glass and aluminium were considered highly
undesirable materials while paper and laminates scored well.
However, the bleach used in paper manufacturing, which is damaging to the
environment, and the difficulty of recycling laminates counted heavily
against these materials in other categories.
Other factors taken into consideration were the environmental costs of
extracting raw materials, the pollution caused in manufacturing the
products, and the ease with which they could be recycled.
The report went on to identify several ways in which Gateway could achieve
this reduction in energy use and proposed a 10 point programme that it
should follow.
It suggested that Gateway could encourage packaging companies to reduce the
volume of material by designing new forms of packaging or using different
materials. It could also encourage new delivery and collection systems for
its products, promote recycling and waste management schemes and use
re-usable or returnable containers more widely.
The Landbank consultancy urged Gateway to initiate a widespread debate on
environmental issues, both within its own company and within the retailing
and packaging companies generally.
Ms Penny Walker, a recycling campaigner for Friends of the Earth, says the
report makes an interesting contribution to the debate on packaging issues
and she highlights two particular aspects which have not generally been
considered in the debate.
First, she says the report placed considerable emphasis on the effects of
material extraction on habitats and species. 'What it attempts to do is to
look at the direct impact on sensitive habitats like rain forests.'
So, for example, aluminium scored badly because of the environmental damage
that its extraction causes.
The second area was the report's emphasis on the re-usability of packaging.
'The retailers' biggest problem is going to be to make the necessary leap of
the imagination to use refillable containers.'
Such containers could be used for drinks or for cosmetics, such as those
used at Body Shop, which are packaged in refillable plastic bottles.
Mr Tony Baldry, a junior environment minister who was present at the launch
of the Gateway initiative, welcomed the move saying it would provide a
'useful lead in the direction we all want to go'.
And he warned that unless other companies demonstrated their willingness to
act on environmental issues then the Government would consider further
action to compel them along the route.
The food industry will also face increasing pressure from Europe to set high
environmental standards as the Commission is currently drawing up a
packaging directive, due to be published in the autumn, which looks as
though it will set stiff recycling requirements.
The Germans have already taken a decisive lead in this area and its
parliament recently passed a tough law on waste management which requires
industry to take back and re-use 80 per cent of packaging materials by 1995.
The environmental trend is clear. Food manufacturers and retailers ignore it
at their peril.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
