<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Survey of The Food Industry (4): Carnivores lose ground -
Vegetarianism loses its 'cranky' image
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAY HARRIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VEGETARIAN food is losing its 'cranky' image in the UK, up to a point. As
more Britons eat less meat, food manufacturers and supermarkets are
expanding their vegetarian ranges.
But their marketing strategy demonstrates conclusively that the target
audience is not so much professed vegetarians, although their numbers
continue to grow, as the much larger number of omnivores seeking a
healthier, more varied diet.
In most cases, manufacturers whisper rather than shout the vegetarian nature
of their food. Vegetarians, after all, are accustomed to checking labels
carefully, while the biggest potential for growth is among consumers whose
eating habits may have evolved more quickly than their self-image.
Marketing Strategies for Industry estimates that 5.6m Britons, or 10 per
cent of the population, now at least have eliminated red meat from their
diets. Of these, 2.2m are believed to be lacto-ovo-vegetarians (eating dairy
products and eggs) or vegans (eating no animal products). According to Mr
Nigel Phillips, marketing director of Haldane Food Group, one of the largest
independent vegetarian food manufacturers with annual sales of Pounds 25m,
9m Britons eat vegetarian meals three or more times a week. It is no
surprise that the restaurant menu without specified vegetarian options is
now the exception.
In 1990, MSI says, UK sales of specialist vegetarian foods, conservatively
defined to include vegetarian grills, ready meals, quiches and flans and
cheddar cheese, soya and tofu products, vegetable stock and free-range eggs,
reached Pounds 335m.
Broader definitions, including vegetarian staples such as vegetables,
pulses, nuts, pasta and rice, would take the total to well over Pounds 1bn,
but would distort the figures, says MSI.
However, the most important pointer to the future is the fact that more
children than adults are vegetarian.
The slow extinction of the 'family meal' because of changing lifestyles and
the microwave revolution means that children now often have more freedom to
choose their food from an early age.
'The growth market by far is the younger generation,' says Mr Phillips.
'Virtually every family will have a vegetarian in it. Generally it's a
teenager and it's a girl.'
But young vegetarians often share tastes with meat-eating peers, and they do
not necessarily want 'adult' food.
This factor was central to the development of one of Haldane's newer
products, the 'No Bull Burger', which looks and tastes like meat, according
to Mr Phillips. It was launched, by coincidence, at the height of public
concern about bovine spongiform encephalopathy, 'mad cow disease.'
Haldane had planned a meat-less burger because burgers remained a growth
market, and teenagers, the single largest vegetarian group, ate 80 per cent
of burgers in Britain.
The company also knew it had to appeal to eyes as well as appetites, so it
consulted 35 discussion groups combining meat-eating and vegetarian
teenagers about not only the product but also about the packaging.
The appeal to teenagers is evidence of a perceived division between two
categories of vegetarian consumers. 'Hardened' vegetarians, Mr Phillips
says, do not want anything which looks or tastes of meat, but the growth
market is in meat analogues, despite the memory of early 'cardboard-tasting'
versions of textured vegetable protein (TVP).
The highest profile meat subsitute is Quorn, a mycoprotein - distantly
related to the mushroom - made by continuous fermentation and marketed by
Marlow Foods, an Imperial Chemical Industries-Ranks Hovis McDougall joint
venture. It is sold both in ready meals and, more recently, on its own.
Mr Ralph Pickles, Marlow's managing director, argues that early TVP flopped
because it was marketed, cheaply, as a meat extender, and failed to deliver
its promise on taste. 'People don't want cheap food, they want good quality
food at a sensible price. Repeat purchases depend on taste.' Two thirds of
people who tried Quorn were buying it again.
Quorn's packaging says 'suitable for vegetarians' only in small letters.
'Our market research tells us that if we make that too prominent', Mr
Pickles explains, 'it labels it as a vegetarian product which for a large
part of the population, marks it out as unsuitable', largely on taste
expectations.
Other manufacturers share this ambivalence, as illustrated by their lukewarm
approach to the Vegetarian Society's green V seal of approval. To earn it, a
product must meet various criteria and the maker pays a negotiated annual
licence fee.
Among the brands which carry the seal on some products are Heinz, Baxters,
Marmite and Golden Wonder. However, other manufacturers, including
vegetarian specialists, find it unnecessary or even counter-productive. Mr
Phillips of Haldane, for example, says: 'It is very expensive to put a V
symbol on everything.' The length of time required for approval also
inhibits manufacturers who are trying to bring out new products in
competitive markets. He believes Haldane's reputation is well enough
established to obviate the need for the symbol. It may be more important for
manufacturers associated with meat products to pay for the symbol to
guarantee that a specific product is vegetarian.
But Dalepak Foods, which made its name in formed-meat grillsteaks but
diversified into chopped-vegetable-and-rice grills a few years ago, has not
felt the need to emphasise the vegetarian nature of the latter.
Marlow's Quorn would not qualify for the V symbol in any case, since it is
not made with free-range eggs, although Mr Pickles says: 'We would be very
happy to use free-range eggs in our product if they were available.'
It appears certain that meat will play a decreasing role in the British diet
 -at least as a routine fuel, it may still be associated with special
occasions for many people.
But the commitment required to become a vegetarian rather than just eating
vegetarian much of the time means it will probably continue to be a quiet
revolution.
This explains why Mr Phillips and his counterparts pay so much attention to
the younger generation. 'If you become vegetarian, 90 per cent of the time
you remain vegetarian.'
Vegetarian Foods, Marketing Strategies for Industry, 19 Heathmans Road,
London SW6 4TJ. (071) 371-0955. Pounds 170.
Vegetarian Foods in the UK, Leatherhead Food RA, Randalls Road, Leatherhead,
Surrey KT22 7RY, 0372 376761. Pounds 55.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
