<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Survey of The Food Industry (5): Battle of the bacteria -
Safety Standards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DELLA BRADSHAW
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHAT is the air temperature inside your domestic refrigerator? How long is
it safe to use cooked meats after the 'use by' date? And how should you cook
frozen food in your microwave oven?
Such are the questions the food manufacturers and retailers throw back at
consumers accused of being responsible for outbreaks of salmonella and
listeria. But although many believe that food scares are frequently the
result of consumer misuse, it is the food industry that is being forced to
clean up its act.
Strict new regulations introduced this year put the onus on food producers
to ensure that when the consumer takes the goods off the supermarket shelf,
or orders them in a restaurant, they are wholesome.
Following the introduction Britain in January, food companies - from the
largest biscuit -maker or supermarket chain to the humblest take-away cafe -
now have to demonstrate that they have taken all reasonable precautions and
shown 'due diligence' in manufacture, transportation, storage and
preparation of foodstuffs. And last month () strict regulations governing
the temperature at which foods such as cheeses and cooked meats can be
stored also came into effect.
In spite of the new regulations, many question whether the consumer will be
better off. The regulations will only be effective if they can be adequately
policed - the job of local health officials.
For the environmental health inspectors there are two problems to overcome,
says Steve Bassam, leader of Brighton council and an assistant secretary for
food and environmental health at the Association of Metropolitan
Authorities. To begin with, he says, there is not enough money allocated to
the appropriate departments of local authorities to police the system
thoroughly.
Although the government allocated Pounds 30m from central coffers to smooth
the introduction of the new legislation, those responsible for implementing
the regulations believe Pounds 40m-45m would have been more appropriate.
Secondly, there are too few qualified environmental health officers and
technical assistants to do the job - a shortfall of 1,000 to 1,500 - and
local councils are having problems in recruiting the appropriate staff.
Despite the increase in regulations, many detractors argue the government
has given the food industry a loophole through which it can avoid
prosecution. Previously, if a fly was found in a can of baked beans then the
company was at fault: now, showing they have taken precautions to prevent
such an eventuality - shown 'due diligence' - could mean they are let off
the hook.
The manufacturers, however, take a very different view, says David Edwards,
operations director of the food Hygiene Bureau, a commercial test house and
training organisation. 'They see the new law as an extra commitment, not an
extra defence,' he says.
One difficulty is that what due diligence means has still to be determined
in court, making it difficult for manufacturers and retailers to gauge what
precautions are necessary.
Previously, for example, a large supermarket chain which sold branded
biscuits relied on a guarantee from the biscuit-makers that their products
were wholesome.
If a problem arose the consumer was referred back to the manufacturer. Now,
supermarkets cannot rely on this guarantee, but need to check suppliers'
working practices themselves. Just how far back into the manufacturing chain
they will have to check is unclear. As David Thurston, senior legal officer
with the Sainsbury's chain, puts it, 'Nobody knows if we have to vet Kellogs
before we can sell their cornflakes.'
For the smaller retailer, or the smaller restaurant, such a task would be
economically impossible.
To ensure protection under the law many large manufacturers are putting
quality control procedures into place. Many are turning to the British
Standards Institution's BS 5750 certification, which has been adapted for
food processing companies to enable the monitoring of processes, machinery
and training. So far, however, fewer than 100 companies out of the thousands
of UK food producers have been certified under the scheme.
Smaller companies are investigating more specific testing procedures such as
HACCP - hazard analysis and critical control point tests.
These focus on the most critical element of a food process and ensure that
it is carried out correctly. In a canning process, for example, heating the
produce to the right temperature might by the critical element of the
process.
Technology is also playing its part with a variety of tests and procedures
under development or available to help demonstrate due diligence, both in
processing and temperature control. These include:
Tagging systems designed to reassure the consumer that the food has been
stored at the right temperature, such as the Fresh-Check indicators already
widely-used in the US. The indicator is a circle in the centre of which is a
polymer dot, which darkens when exposed to heat. If the central dot is
lighter than the outer circle the contents are fresh: if darker then the
packet has been 'thermally abused'.
Many supermarket chains are investigating this sort of labelling system for
use in distribution. If one label was put on the top of a dispatch of cooked
ham, for example, it could indicate if the whole consignment had been stored
at the correct temperature.
Edible inks which could be used to print the 'use by' dates, on to the food
itself, rather than on the wrapper. This would prevent unscrupulous food
retailers from unwrapping products that had passed their 'use by' date -
pork pies, for example - and selling them on the delicatessen counter.
Rapid biological tests, to determine whether bacteria are present in the
food manufacturing chain. Today, most tests involve sending away samples or
growing them in a laboratory, which can take days. By the time a problem is
discovered the food could be on the consumers' plate. Within three years
tests could be available to spot bacterial problems before the food leaves
the factory.
Computer systems to help maintain appropriate records. Pace, of Moira,
Northern Ireland, for example, has developed a software package which
handles product specification, auditing of suppliers, calibration of
machinery and training.
All should help manufacturers and retailers ensure their products are
wholesome. It is then the consumer's job to ensure they are properly cooked.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-807</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAACFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Survey of The Food Industry (3): Mitsubishi's exotic palate
 -A takeover with a difference
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAY HARRIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRINCES, based in Liverpool for more than a century, is as British as fish
paste and tinned salmon.
After two years under Japanese ownership, none of that has changed, although
Princes is now also as Italian as conchiglie pasta and as Danish as
marinated herring.
What Princes does not betray, so far at least, is any trace of a Japanese
accent either in its management style or its product range. Perhaps more
interestingly, Mitsubishi Corporation's acquisition of Princes in January
1989 was not the bellwether for a flock of similar Japanese purchases.
When Nestle sold Princes to Mitsubishi in January 1989, the transaction was
widely hailed as one of the first Japanese acquisitions in the European food
industry. What is remarkable more than two years later is that it has
remained a singular event; there has been no comparable deal since then.
The reasons remain hard to fathom, although all takeover activity has waned
in the European food market since then.
Mr Jim Grover of OC&amp;C Strategy Consultants, London-based food and drink
specialists, suggests Japanese buyers are very brand-conscious but have been
inhibited by high asking prices.
Mitsubishi was Princes' third owner in less than a year. Buitoni, the
Italian pasta manufacturer, had bought Princes from J Bibby &amp; Sons, the
industrial and agricultural group, in the 1970s, to marry authentic foreign
food in a fast-growing sector with traditional, but mature, British
products.
But the Buitoni family sold out to Mr Carlo De Benedetti in 1984. When he
could not generate enough growth out of the business, he sold it to Nestle
of Switzerland in 1988.
When Nestle unpacked its shopping basket after the deal, it decided that
Princes' collection of tinned products, even though it carried one of the
largest grocery brands in Britain, really was not worth shelf space in its
pantry.
The emergence of Mitsubishi as the ultimate buyer raised belief in itself at
Princes, according to Mr Stephen Clegg, marketing director. 'Mitsubishi
bought Princes not because it was part of a package but because they really
wanted it.'
Princes already did business with Mitsubishi in a small way; the Japanese
company's tuna-canning plant in Mauritius was one of its suppliers. A
coincidence, Mr Clegg said.
Two years on, Princes retains considerable operating autonomy within the
group. There is little hands-on involvement from the parent company.
Princes' board has only one Japanese member, Mr Tak Akiyoshi, co-ordinating
director, who handles communications between Liverpool and Tokyo.
Princes, which has only one employee based outside the UK, does tap into
Mitsubishi's global network for weather forecasts, help on commodity trading
and information on product sourcing. However, it retains full responsibility
for all decisions, including quality control, says Mr Clegg.
Quality control and security of supply are central to the success of
Princes, whose modus operandi would be recognisable to its founders, a Mr
Simpson and a Mr Roberts, who began to import tinned salmon and lobster from
Canada in 1880.
With expected turnover of more than Pounds 200m this year, Princes is still
overwhelmingly an importer of canned goods. Its only UK-manufactured
products are meat and fish spreads and pasta sauces, made in Southport.
Together they account for only 4 per cent of turnover by volume and 6 per
cent by value.
'Our strength is our sourcing,' says Mr Clegg. 'Unless you're able to source
from a wide variety of locations, you can be caught out.' It now buys
products from 40 countries and works closely with suppliers to improve their
standards.
Crab meat, for example, used to be imported from North America. But costs
rose so much that Princes had to shift to Thailand, where it persuaded
suppliers to wrap the crab meat in parchment within the tins to prevent
discoloration.
Similarly, as South African fruit became less politically acceptable,
Princes turned to Greece for its tinned peaches. It found, however, that
quality often failed to come up to scratch, so it worked with five canners
to improve the selection of fruit and the printing and affixing of labels.
The need to ensure that its tuna is caught in a 'dolphin-friendly' manner,
without the use of high seas drift nets, made Princes impose tough standards
on all canneries it uses around the world. None can handle drift-netted tuna
at any time if it wants to keep Princes' business.
Some of Princes' leading suppliers do not need any external pressure to
reach or maintain standards. The Dutch company Van der Laan makes its canned
meats, a market in which Princes is the UK brand leader even though it
entered it only in 1982, and Saeby Fiske in Denmark supplies mackerel and
herring.
New products are critical for growth because so many of Princes' old
favourites are in mature or declining sectors. UK demand for fish and meat
pastes, for example, has halved in the past 10 years, and neither Princes
nor its rivals is committing much effort to reversing the trend or fighting
for market share. 'One of the characteristics of this market is inertia,'
comments Mr Clegg. 'I hesitate to call it loyalty.'
Princes is focusing on creating new segments and niches in growth markets.
Tiny pots of fishpaste may be out of favour, but Princes has launched
chilled spreads and slicing sausages.
It is becoming difficult, moreover, to find Princes herring or mackerel that
has not been adorned with an 'added value' sauce. The old-established Trex
brand of vegetable shortening has been opened as an umbrella over a new
International Collection* of exotic oils like pistachio and toasted sesame.
The latter, again by coincidence, is supplied by Mitsubishi.
The exit from Buitoni left Princes with a gap in its portfolio because
retailers had come to identify it with a range of authentic Italian food. It
now imports pasta made by Federici, a century-old family-owned company in
Umbria, and makes sauces under the Federici name in Southport.
It might seem that another entrant is the last thing needed in a pasta
sauces market fiercely contested by industry giants such as Unilever (Ragu),
Mars (Dolmio) and Nestle (Buitoni) and private label producers. But Mr Clegg
sees a role for Federici's pasta-and-sauces package among more timid
shoppers: 'Less assured consumers have a desire for authenticity.'
There is no doubt, in any case, that Mitsubishi got the real thing, in terms
of a solid and growing UK grocery brand, when it acquired Princes. And it
made clear from the beginning that it would back the right European deals
with deep pockets.
Mr Clegg is unperturbed by the lack of action since then, knowing his
Japanese parent is playing a patient hand but will not hesitate when the
time comes. Mitsubishi has a saying: 'If it's worth doing, it's worth doing
today.' The European food industry should keep its eyes peeled for that
signal.
*Management Page, FT, March 14 1991.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page II Photograph York hams in Marsh &amp; Baxter's maturing room,
centuries of tradition protect local products (Omitted). Photograph
Bassett's factory at Sheffield, it takes all sorts to suck a winegum
(Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
