<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Commodities and Agriculture: Brazil set to import Dollars
1bn worth of grain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VICTORIA GRIFFITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAOLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE drought in Brazil's south-central region will force the country to
import Dollars 1bn (Pounds 578.8m) worth of grains this year, according to
the Technical Trade Co-ordinator (CIC), which forms part of the the Ministry
of Economics.
Argentina is likely to provide about 80 per cent of imports, strengthening
the country's position as the world's biggest grain exporter.
This figure includes plans to import up to 120,000 tonnes of soyabeans -
traditionally one of Brazil's main export products. Heavy damage from the
drought has led analysts to predict a 22 per cent drop in the soyabean crop
this year, compared to 1990.
The agency has also received government authorisation to import 13,000
tonnes of soyabean oil, and expects total foreign purchases of the product
to reach 60,000 tonnes this year.
Brazil will import between 800,000 and 1m tonnes of rice, said a CIC
spokesman, including 350,000 tonnes from Argentina and Uruguay and the rest
from the US, Thailand, Vietnam and other countries.
The rice scheduled to come in from Argentina and Uruguay will bear no import
tariff, while imports from other sources will be taxed at 15 per cent.
Brazil will also take in about 1.5m tonnes of corn, and 3m tonnes of wheat
from abroad, according to the CIC. Again, Argentina will be supplying the
bulk of purchases.
'The prolonged drought in Brazil's key south-central growing area has been
devastating,' said a CIC spokesman. 'This, coupled with tight agricultural
credit, has led to severe shortages in all these products.'
</TEXT>
