<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Commodities and Agriculture: Shell puts Dollars 74m into
Chilean offshoot
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SANTIAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ROYAL DUTCH/SHELL, the petro-chemical group, has injected Dollars 74m
(Pounds 42.8m) of new capital into its subsidiary in Chile, where it is
investing in forestry and mining.
Chile is the focal point of Shell's relatively new forestry business. The
company owns 60 per cent of a Dollars 460m pulp mill at Nacimiento in the
Bio-Bio region, which has its formal opening next month, and an associated
Dollars 110m eucalyptus forest.
Partners in this project, which will produce 220,000 tonnes of pulp a year
for use in tissue paper, are two US groups, Scott Paper and Citicorp
Banking.
Shell has more than 60,000 hectares of plantations in Chile. Mr Robert
Turner, president of Shell Chile, says Chile has a natural advantage in
forestry - trees grow twice as fast as in the northern hemisphere.
But he says Shell Chile will now pause to consolidate its position in
forestry. 'Growth in Chile in the immediate future will come from mining.'
Billiton, Shell's mining and metals division, is spending Dollars 14.5m on
exploration this year, mainly on a huge copper deposit at Collahuasi in the
Tarapaca region.
Mr Rodney Lay, managing director of Billiton Chile, points out that the
world's three biggest copper mines are in the country and that Collahuasi
'appears to be a classic Chilean deposit. Everywhere they look they find
copper.'
Billiton's partners in the copper project are Falconbridge of Canada and
Chevron of the US.
If the go-ahead for a mine is given, Collahuasi would cost between Dollars
200m and Dollars 300m and produce 75,000 to 80,000 tonnes of copper in
concentrates a year to start with, but Mr Lay says a mine could not start up
until 1995.
Billiton's sole current operating mine in Chile is Choquelimpie, near Arica
in northern Chile, which is pioneering high-altitude, low-grade gold mining
and last year produced 100,300 troy ounces of gold and 64,000 ounces of
silver.
With its partners, Northgate of Canada (35 per cent) and Citibank (23 per
cent), Billiton is spending Dollars 3m this year exploring for more reserves
at Choquelimpie, which in theory runs out of ore in 1993.
Shell now has more than Dollars 600m invested in Chile, up from Dollars 70m
ten years ago, and the number of employees in Shell companies has grown from
300 to 3,000.
</TEXT>
