<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Commodities and Agriculture: India reins back its sugar
exports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KUNAL BOSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CALCUTTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Indian government has decided for the moment not to export the full
525,000 tonnes of sugar which it sanctioned last month. Even though there is
a huge surplus, the caretaker government headed by Mr Chandra Shekhar has
accepted the industry's suggestion to restrict the export to 225,000 tonnes
for the time being.
The decision to withhold export has been taken in view of the prevailing
depressed sugar price in the world market, according to Mr Om Dhanuka,
spokesman for the Indian Sugar Mills Association. The Indian Sugar and
General Industry Export Import Corporation, the trading arm of the industry,
is still looking for buyers for 50,000 unsold tonnes out of the 225,000
tonnes.
Whether India will finally export 525,000 tonnes will be decided by the new
government to be formed following the elections later this month.
The Indian sugar industry had produced 10.04m tonnes of sugar by mid-April,
compared with 9.12m tonnes in the corresponding period last season. Experts
believe total production in the current season, ending September, could be
12m tonnes, against actual production of 11m tonnes last year.
If production touches 12m tonnes, the total availability in the current
season will be 14.2m tonnes, when brought-forward stocks are included.
Domestic demand will at the most be 10.6m tonnes.
When the industry's stock was taken recently, it was found that 328 mills
were still engaged in cane crushing as on April 15 last, against 289 mills
on the corresponding day of the previous season.
Mr Dhanuka said: 'There is still plenty of cane in the field and a good
number of mills in north and west India will remain operational till June
when monsoon sets in full might.'
India's cane production in 1990-91 is estimated at 233.45m tonnes, compared
with 222.62m tonnes last year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 28
</PAGE>
