<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / International Capital Markets: Italian banks close to Soviet
finance deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER, Euromarkets Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ITALIAN BANKS are close to finalising a large loan for the Soviet Union, the
first to be raised under an Italian government programme announ- ced last
year aimed at supporting the weak Soviet economy.
The funds are being raised under an Italian pledge to provide up to L2,200bn
(Dollars 1.7bn) in financial support to the Soviet Union.
The loan of Ecu427.9m (Dollars 509.2m), carrying the guarantee of the
Italian Treasury, will finance payments to Italian exporters for the supply
of goods to the Soviet Union. The Soviet Union has built up arrears on trade
debts with western exporters, amounting to an estimated Dollars 5bn.
Banca Commerciale Italiana is arranging the credit, which will be available
for a year. It will be repaid in four equal semi-annual instalments with a
final maturity at the end of 1995. BCI declined to disclose the interest
margin. The syndicate of 15 to 20 banks is expected to be entirely Italian.
The Soviet Union borrowed directly from banks until late 1989, but it would
now be impossible without guarantees from governments in the industrialised
countries.
According to a report from the Institute of International Finance, a
Washington-based research group financed by international banks, commercial
banks provided more than Dollars 8bn in new credit in 1989 but withdrew
about Dollars 12bn last year. This year it expects a further Dollars 7bn
will be withdrawn. Most of this swing was accounted for in short-term
lending, through a fall in the availability of trade credits and foreign
deposits with Soviet banks.
It calculated official disbursements of medium and long-term credits to the
Soviet Union this year should total Dollars 13.1bn, of which Italy accounts
for Dollars 1.4bn. The report, published at the end of last month, estimates
Germany will provide Dollars 3bn, Korea almost Dollars 2bn and France, Italy
Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and the US at least Dollars 1bn each.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 27
</PAGE>
