<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / International Company News: Peters quits as Columbia
Pictures' co-chairman
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SONY Software yesterday confirmed that the co-chairman of its Columbia
Pictures Entertainment division, Mr Jon Peters, will give up his title and
day-to-day management duties. This is the second shuffle of Hollywood
executives this month.
The move comes only 19 months after Sony paid a high premium to acquire
Guber-Peters Entertainment, Mr Peters' former production company.
It also comes only days after Paramount Communications appointed Mr Brandon
Tartikoff to head its Paramount Pictures unit.
Sony's regard for Mr Peters and Mr Peter Guber was reflected in the Dollars
200m, or Dollars 17 1/2 -a-share, it paid for Guber-Peters in 1989, at a
time when the stock was trading at Dollars 12 3/4 a share and in the costly
lawsuit it fought for Guber-Peters.
Sony said Mr Peters would establish a new entertainment company which would
be tied exclusively to Columbia. The new company would produce films, music
and television.
Mr Peters, a former hairdresser, is one of Hollywood's most colourful
characters. He formed a relationship with Barbra Streisand in the 1970s when
he was working as a hairdresser, and in 1976 helped produce Ms Streisand's
remake of A Star is Born.
Mr Peters joined forces with Mr Guber in 1980 and the pair produced such
film hits as Batman, Rain Man and The Colour Purple before joining Sony.
The duo have poured money into Columbia Pictures and its Tri-Sta Pictures
unit. They are expected to spend about Dollars 700m this year on films,
nearly twice as much as Paramount Pictures intends to spend.
At Columbia, Mr Guber, who trained as a lawyer and had some experience of
studio management, focused on corporate affairs while Mr Peters concentrated
on creative matters.
Rumours started in February that Peters, who had never worked inside a big
corporation, was planning to leave Columbia. Mr Guber, will remain as
Columbia's chief executive.
</TEXT>
