<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / International Company News: PepsiCo commercial leaves a
bitter taste
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
COCA-COLA and PepsiCo are suddenly at each other's throats in Japan, lodging
competing claims with the Fair Trade Commission over a Pepsi commercial that
Coke wants canned.
Advertisements ridiculing a competitor are unusual in this
consensus-conscious country, but, for the past month, PepsiCo has served a
mildly amusing, gently mocking commercial to Japanese viewers.
The US-made commercial shows the high-octane rap singer M. C. Hammer having
his customary Pepsi switched for a Coke during a performance. He then breaks
into an off-key rendition of the ballad Feelings, which prompts an audience
member to offer him a Pepsi, inspiring a return to the rap beat.
PepsiCo Japan has filed a claim with the FTC alleging Coca-Cola (Japan) has
put unfair pressure on Japanese television stations not to broadcast the
commercial, which has disappeared from the television screen in recent days.
Meanwhile, Coca-Cola had lodged a complaint with the FTC against Pepsi,
alleging that, under the Japanese advertising code, the commercial unfairly
disparages Coke. Four years ago, the FTC ruled comparative commercials would
be allowed only if the method was impartial and the content verifiable.
A Coca-Cola official said unfair pressure had not been applied to Japanese
broadcasters, though 'we informed key television stations that we did not
authorise the use of our trademark and that the information implied was
untrue and therefore unsupportable and disparaging'.
Pepsi said yesterday the commercial was the first of its kind in Japan, and
a survey of young people showed it was the second most popular nationally
last month. The company said Pepsi sales for the month were up 50 per cent
from a year earlier, though Coke is still reckoned to have a 90 per cent
share of the cola market.
'We would like to continue airing this popular commercial. However, when we
placed orders for May television spots to five key stations, they all
replied that they cannot accept,' PepsiCo said.
The success of the commercial has surprised the Japanese advertising
industry, which will be tempted to indulge in the gentle art of the put-down
if the FTC rules in favour of Pepsi. Commission officials yesterday said
they could not comment on cases under review.
Coca-Cola said that the company had no objection to PepsiCo screening the
commercial in the US because the country was accustomed to comparative
advertising.
He said that Japan was 'a completely different situation' and that 'we have
always tried to respect Japanese customs in presenting our product'.
</TEXT>
