<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Hogg to cut involvement at Courtaulds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER, Industrial Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR CHRISTOPHER Hogg, chairman and chief executive of Courtaulds, the
speciality materials manufacturer, will in August relinquish his position as
chief executive, clearing the way for Mr Sipko Huismans, the group's
managing director, to take over.
Yesterday's announcement of Sir Christopher's impending move to part-time
chairman, marks a further stage in the company's evolution during his 11 1/2
years as chairman and chief executive.
Mr Huismans' appointment is indicative of Courtaulds' internationalisation
in recent years: he will be the first non-Englishman to hold a position of
such seniority.
When Sir Christopher became chairman and chief executive at the start of
1980 Courtaulds was an ailing textiles and chemicals conglomerate. He has
overseen a transformation through rationalisation and internationalisation
which culminated in the demerger of Courtaulds Textiles and Courtaulds in
1990.
Mr Huismans said of Sir Christopher: 'He took a group which was an unwieldy
mess and turned it into two sensible, sizeable companies.'
Sir Christopher's move is bound to provoke speculation that he plans to move
to another senior job in industry. He will leave the chief executive post on
August 1, a day before his 55th birthday, still significantly younger than
many chairmen of comparable industrial groups.
However, he said he had no plans beyond fulfilling his duties as part time
chairman of Courtaulds, Courtaulds Textiles and Reuters, the financial
information group. Although Sir Christopher said there was 'non-hidden
agenda' in the move he did not rule out moving to another post in due
course.
Mr Huismans, who was born in the Netherlands, joined Courtaulds 30 years ago
as a chemist in Swaziland after an education in South Africa. He has been
managing director of Courtaulds for the last two years. His appointment,
with a main background in sales and marketing, will present a significant
change of style from the quietly spoken and intellectual Sir Christopher.
With the radical restructuring of the group largely completed Mr Huismans
said his main task would be to raise performance throughout the group to the
highest international standards.
Observer, Page 18 ip
</TEXT>
