<PROFILE>_AN-BEIBNAFLFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910509
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Administrators urge Polly Peck creditors to
play waiting game
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'PATIENCE IS a virtue' sums up the message from Polly Peck International's
administrators to the group's many creditors in their report distributed
yesterday.
Rather than settle for the quantifiable, albeit meagre, returns that a
liquidation would yield, they urge that creditors should hold their fire in
the hope that money will start to flow back to the group from Turkey and
northern Cyprus at some indeterminate future date.
That would reverse what are said to have been 'very large sums' flowing in
the other direction, leading to debts of about Pounds 959m being owed to the
rest of the group by businesses in the area.
The administrators also say that they have been told that, between July and
October last year, as Polly Peck's financial crisis developed, Pounds 230m
was pumped into proposed leisure developments in northern Cyprus. They have
not been able to verify this, but say that 'substantial further investment'
would be needed to achieve any return.
Meanwhile, the core businesses would be primped up to enhance values with
the aid of strategic partners who would be brought on board. And
investigations into the possible enhancement of returns through legal claims
would continue.
If all went well, the implication is, creditors might eventually expect to
receive more than the 52p in the pound dividend implied by the directors'
estimate contained in the report, since this includes no estimated
realisable values for 'certain' northern Cypriot and Turkish subsidiaries.
The likely return from a liquidation would approximate to just 20p in the
pound, with some creditors, acting to improve their position at the expense
of others, receiving 30p. This implies a deficit of assets against
liabilities of more than Pounds 900m.
The report puts unsecured creditors at Pounds 1.15bn. 'The group was in a
more parlous state than we imagined,' said joint administrator Mr Richard
Stone of Coopers &amp; Lybrand Deloitte.
Under the broad strategy for 1991 and 1992 outlined by the administrators
yesterday, approximately Pounds 500m of debt (equivalent to a range of
30p-60p in the pound) would be settled by way of repayment or refinancing.
The proportions of each would depend on the performance of the principal
underlying companies within the group.
'A substantial part' of the remaining debt would be converted into an
instrument giving rights to participate in returns from the food, packaging
and leisure businesses in northern Cyprus and Turkey. The rump of the
group's borrowings would be written off or converted into equity.
The current equity would be reduced to a nominal value, 'with a view to
launching a possible rights issue' to raise funds to support the on-going
businesses.
The operation in the most obvious need of support at present is Sansui, the
Tokyo-listed electronics group that Polly Peck bought control of last year.
The administrators said yesterday that the strategy of expanding Polly
Peck's Far Eastern electronics operations by utilising the Sansui brand name
on the output of Capetronic, another subsidiary, had not yet been
successfully implemented. As a result, Sansui incurred trading losses of
Pounds 30m in the nine months to December 31 1990.
The administrators said that they had been advised that there was 'little
prospect' of realising their investment in Sansui in the short term and that
restrictions existed on selling Polly's shares within two years of
acquisition. They are accordingly working urgently on the preparation of a
recovery plan, as well as seeking a partner to 'provide financial and
management resources and to assist in restoring the profitability of the
group'.
A partner is also being sought for Del Monte, the US fresh fruit arm, to
help the company to exploit the developing European market. Proposed
deregulation, coupled with the emerging situation in east Europe, is a
source of great potential, the administrators stated.
In the year to December 31 1990, Del Monte made pre-tax profits before
interest of Dollars 80m on turnover of Dollars 799m. The company is
structured 'so as to be financially independent' of the rest of the group,
the report confirmed.
On the food, packaging and leisure interests in Turkey and northern Cyprus
where the principal uncertainties lie, the administrators said that there
had been 'an encouraging improvement'.
An understanding has now been reached as to 'the method by which the
relevant businesses' could be reorganised, they said. One of a number of
'avenues' being considered is the possible flotation of the food and
packaging entities as one group and of the leisure interests as another.
Less encouragingly, they said that trading in the foreseeable future was
likely to be 'at a considerably lower level than previously reported'. This
was due to the impact of the Gulf war and the uncertainty caused by the
appointment of administrators. A number of valuable markets for Meyna, the
fresh foodstuffs producer, and Unipac, the carton box-maker, existed in
Iraq, Kuwait and other countries, they said.
Vestel, the Turkish consumer electronics company, made trading profits of
Pounds 52m on turnover of Pounds 270m in the year to December 31 1990. Since
last October, it has negotiated its own financing facilities with the
assistance of the administrators which are regarded as adequate to meet
on-going needs. The administrators believe that realisation of the assets,
whether by a sale or a share placing, would currently only be possible at 'a
significant discount to the current market capitalisation'.
In general, the administrators said that they had 'serious reservations' as
to the quality and fairness of Polly Peck's published results.
Mr Paul Hipps, senior partner of Stoy Hayward, Polly Peck's auditor, said
yesterday: 'The administrators have had full access to our audit working
papers (those dealing with the group accounts) and no queries have been
raised with us.'
