<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Trafalgar interim falls to Pounds 51.5m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRAFALGAR HOUSE, the construction, property, shipping and hotels
conglomerate, yesterday reported a slump in pre-tax profits from Pounds
116.9m to Pounds 51.5m for the six months to March.
The fall would have been worse without a 40 per cent rise in construction
and engineering profits to Pounds 38.3m (Pounds 27.4m) thanks to a strong
order book of Pounds 2.9bn.
Taxation rose from 27 per cent last year to 33 per cent because the group is
not making sufficient UK profits to offset against its advanced corporation
tax (ACT).
Sir Eric Parker, chief executive, said: 'We are very concerned with the
level of our tax. It is very difficult in a recession as tough as this to
retain UK profits. However, we are looking at ways of mitigating ACT.'
Sir Eric said the group was looking at three possible solutions: skipping
the dividend payment, issuing convertible loan stock or acquiring UK
businesses.
The convertible loan stock is understood to be the most desirable. Interest
paid on the stock would be tax deductible.
Shareholders would not want the group to pass the dividend, and any
acquisitions through an increase of debt could affect gearing, already at 54
per cent.
Borrowings for the end of March stood at Pounds 450m compared with Pounds
830m of shareholders' funds.
Turnover fell from Pounds 1.7bn to Pounds 1.6bn and earnings per share
before extraordinary items more than halved from 16.9p to 6.7p.
The interim dividend has been maintained at 8.8p.
The group has had to reduce costs and overheads which has led to the loss of
500 jobs from its 18,000-strong UK workforce and 250 out of the 10,000
employeed overseas.
Sir Eric said the second half would be tough. 'We need further cuts in
interest rates before things are going to get a lot better.'
The recession hit Trafalgar's property and investment division which
suffered a 55 per cent fall in profits to Pounds 127.4m (Pounds 224.6m).
The commercial and residential markets in the US remain slow, although Sir
Eric said there were some signs that the UK market was improving.
In a significant change of policy, certain development properties for sale,
worth around Pounds 200m, are to be reclassified as fixed assets which will
be revalued in September.
The shipping and hotels division was badly affected by the Gulf war.
Group hotels were only half full and profits fell from Pounds 337.6m to
Pounds 290.6m.
Business from the shipping sector, valued in sterling, will now be
calculated in dollars, allowing the group to increase its borrowings in the
US and reduce them in the UK.
The share price rose 6p to 268p.
Lex, Page 20
