<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Spain calls for solution on Gibraltar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER, Diplomatic Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DISAGREEMENT over Gibraltar was now the only important obstacle to better
relations between Britain and Spain, Mr Felipe Gonzalez, the Spanish prime
minister, said in London yesterday. He said Madrid was waiting for London to
make a move to solve this 'historical anachronism'.
The Spanish leader stressed after talks on Tuesday with Mr John Major, the
prime minister, that London and Madrid were in broad agreement on the future
economic and monetary development of the European Community. Both
governments considered it would be a mistake to rush into full monetary
union before achieving greater convergence between the economies of members.
There were continuing differences over the organisation of European defence.
Although Spain agreed with Britain that Nato should not be undermined by any
new European defence arrangements, Mr Gonzalez said he could not imagine a
common European foreign policy that was not complemented by a common defence
policy.
Although Mr Gonzalez declined to give any details of his discussions with Mr
Major on Gibraltar, he made clear, both in an interview with the Financial
Times and at a press conference, that Spain was not prepared to wait
indefinitely for a solution to the problem. Spain has a long-standing demand
for sovereignty of the Rock. The Spanish prime minister indicated that he
was looking for step-by-step progress, starting with the joint use of
Gibraltar airport.
Mr Gonzalez issued a thinly-veiled warning that Spain might take retaliatory
measures if Mr Joe Bossano, Gibraltar's prime minister, went ahead with
plans to establish a modern off-shore financial centre on the Rock and to
reclaim land on its east coast.
He hinted that Spain could neutralise the tax advantages Gibraltar offers on
investments in Spain channelled through the Rock.
