<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / US to renew campaign for lower world interest rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER RIDDELL, US Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US intends to renew its campaign for a commitment by leading industrial
countries to a growth strategy involving lower world interest rates, in
spite of a bruising confrontation over the issue at the recent meeting of
Group of Seven finance ministers and central bankers.
Germany, supported by Japan and Britain, rejected the call made by Mr
Nicholas Brady, the US treasury secretary, for a shift in emphasis towards
tackling slower growth rather than inflation.
Senior US officials concede that they failed to persuade the other G7
members of their case in what non-US participants described as a tense and
difficult discussion. However, the US intends to revive the issue at the
summit of the heads of government of the G7 countries - the US, Japan,
Germany, Britain, France, Italy and Canada - in London in mid-July.
The US tactics are apparently not to take a high profile on the issue for
the time being, partly for fear of worsening divisions and in the hope of
winning people round in time. Instead it plans to pursue the matter behind
the scenes through the 'sherpas' or senior officials who prepare the summit
agenda.
The US case is that there is a serious shortage of investment capital. Much
less money is available from such traditional sources as the Arab oil
producing states, Japan and Germany, but that big demands exist in the
Middle East, eastern Europe and Latin America.
US officials stress current high real interest rates in Europe and note that
banks will not undertake sufficient cross-border lending.
The US argues that the current European, and especially German, strategy is
too heavily determined by the desire to fight inflation - which is already
low - and that it ignores the real difficulties.
The US urges industrial countries to shift to what it sees as a more
forward-looking strategy to solve the difficulties of growth in the 1990s.
US officials see such an approach as important also for sustaining economic
and political reform in eastern and central Europe. Such a dynamic approach,
officials believe, would at least provide hope for expansion rather than
what they see as an over-emphasis on inflation.
Some of these issues may be taken up in a speech which President George Bush
plans to deliver on Sunday on the economics of the new world order.
The administration has been talking about signs of recovery in the US
economy but is concerned that any improvement may be delayed and may not be
strong if the European and Japanese economies are weaker.
</TEXT>
