FT  09 MAY 91 / Pit closures could lead to 6,000 job losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FURTHER seven coalmines are to close over the next year with the possible
loss of up to 6,000 jobs, British Coal disclosed yesterday.
Confirmation of the closures, already announced locally, came at a meeting
of the Commons energy select committee.
Mr Kenneth Moses, British Coal's company's technical director, told the
committee that seven pits around the country were scheduled for closure,
reducing the total number functioning to 62.
A British Coal official later said that the likely reasons for closure would
be the exhaustion of recoverable reserves. The closures had been negotiated
with unions locally, and there were no appeals.
Miners affected by the closures would be offered early retirement or
alternative work, and no compulsory redundancies were expected.
The pits scheduled for closure are in several regions, including the
north-east, north-west, Yorkshire and south Wales. They are Dawdon, Barnsley
Main, Denby Grange, Dinnington, Sutton Manor, Allerton Bywater, and
Penallta.
Mr Neil Clarke, British Coal chairman, was also questioned by the committee
on the likely shape of Britain's coalmining industry as negotiations get
under way with PowerGen and National Power on future coal demand.
Under questioning, Mr Clarke said it was impossible to predict the future
size of the industry prior to the outcome of talks with the generating
companies.
