<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Yugoslav PM backs army role in crisis
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER, DAVID BUCHAN and JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE, BRUSSELS,, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
YUGOSLAVIA'S army was last night given full backing by Mr Ante Markovic, the
prime minister, in an attempt to stop the spread of ethnic conflict which
has brought the country to the brink of civil war.
At the same time, he called for the disarming of all citizens following last
week's violent clashes between Serbs and Croats which left 18 dead.
His move came as Britain sought a European-wide initiative to resolve the
crisis. It has asked its European Community partners to consider a possible
mediating role for the 34-member Conference on Security and Co-operation in
Europe. All the EC countries are members of CSCE, which also includes the
Soviet Union, Canada and the US.
Meanwhile, Mr Douglas Hurd, the UK foreign secretary, appealed for an end to
violence as a means of solving the ethnic disputes, the worst since the
Second World War.
Mr Markovic, who presented his five-point plan to the federal government,
said: 'Conditions should be created for the Yugoslav People's Army to act
according to the constitution and the federal law to carry out its basic
functions - the defence of the borders, and in this situation, it is also to
stop inter-ethnic armed conflict.'
The army has wanted to impose a state of emergency. However, this requires
the consent of the collective presidency - consisting of representatives
from the six republics and two provinces - which so far has refused.
The deadlock has encouraged some army factions to consider imposing martial
law.
Admiral Stane Brovet, the deputy defence minister, warned parliament
yesterday that the army was losing patience.
Mr Markovic's statement is aimed at a compromise between the army and the
presidency. By spelling out the role of the army, he may hope to win
constitutional backing for the military to quash unrest, but not impose a
state of emergency.
He said that 'any attempts (by the republic or individuals) to change 'the
internal or external borders of the country' would not be tolerated.
The crisis has been sparked by sharp political differences between Croats
and Serbs, the country's two largest ethnic groups.
Britain's mediation attempt, to be put formally to the EC's foreign affairs
council in Brussels next Tuesday, will be the first concerted international
attempt to try to provide Yugoslavia with a forum to find way to resolve its
problems.
However, any efforts to convene a meeting of the CSCE countries will require
the consent of Yugoslavia.
