<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Observer: Swaps knock
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Michael Heseltine's decision to sit on his hands over the local authority
swaps affair is yet another disaster for the UK banking lobby. The trade
groups representing UK banking interests already had an impressive record of
failure in their Whitehall battles.
The latest setback - which will cost the banks Pounds 550m - came despite
two official visits to the Treasury by Sir Jeremy Morse, chairman of the
British Bankers Association, and a lobbying campaign by Sir Martin Jacomb,
chairman of the British Merchant Bank and Securities Houses Association.
Even Robin Leigh-Pemberton, governor of the Bank of England, weighed in. All
argued that the affair was harming the City and needed to be righted by
retrospective legislation. But to no avail.
It puts a heavy onus on Sir Nicholas Goodison, the new BBA chairman, to
strengthen the bank lobby's firepower. Early signs suggest he's wasting no
time in rallying his forces and will play a more up-front role.
The Bank of England also might come to regret the way its ineffectiveness in
the affair has damaged its image among its flock, particularly the foreign
bankers who turned to it for help. As one said: 'The BBA described this as
regrettable. Personally, I'd have used the word disgusting.'
</TEXT>
