FT  09 MAY 91 / Observer: Spoken for
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Aptly named Larry Speakes, who put his own words into Ronald Reagan's mouth
while serving as the US president's chief spokesman, has found a new job
that will carry his voice to British ears. He is to be communications
vice-president of Canadian telephone-equipment group Northern Telecom, which
lately bought control of STC.
Little has been heard of him in the three years since he quit as public
relations chief at Merrill Lynch amid a fuss over his book, Speaking Out, in
which he admitted occasionally inventing Reaganisms.
One came in 1985 when, feeling the president was being upstaged by Mikhail
Gorbachev in their summit meeting, Speakes spread the myth that Reagan had
told the Soviet leader: 'There is much that divides us, but I believe the
world breathes easier because we are talking here together.' Speakes later
acknowledged he was wrong 'to take such liberties'.
Northern Telecom, for one, has clearly forgiven him. Its chairman, Paul
Stern, says his new mouthpiece is an experienced professional who will be 'a
real asset'.
</TEXT>
