<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Observer: Talent spotted
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
At 80, Lord Kearton may have long ceased treating Courtaulds as his personal
domain. But the appointment of Sipko Huismans as its chief executive shows
he still has influence over its fate.
It was Kearton, a colossus of post-war industrial Britain, who first spotted
Dutch-born Huismans in 1961. At the time, he was 21 and a 'very bad chemist'
with a Courtaulds offshoot in Swaziland. But Kearton saw a latent sales and
marketing man hiding inside and brought him to England.
What caught Kearton's eye? Dynamism, he recalls, ability and an
irrepressibly adventurous approach. All of which paints Huismans very
differently from the cerebral, precise and very English Sir Christopher
Hogg, another Kearton recruit who has been chairman and chief executive for
nearly 12 years.
Hogg, 54, says it is time to give someone else a go. He will remain chairman
of Courtaulds and of Courtaulds Textiles, which was successfully hived off
last year. With the chairmanship of Reuters also in his quiver, he claims he
has no immediate ambition elsewhere.
He describes his successor as 'a bloody good decision-maker with great
judgment'.
The new chief executive, for his part, remembers travelling in the lift with
Kearton, dreaming of the job which will be his from August. 'I have wanted
to be here for 30 years. We will see how things go but seven or eight years
in the seat may be enough.'
He has been on the board since 1984 and managing director of the speciality
materials business since last year's de-merger. And while he does not
envisage any shake-up in strategy or personnel, his appointment as the first
non-Brit to the top job in Hanover Square seems appropriate.
'When Chris arrived,' he says, 'Courtaulds was a UK business with overseas
offshoots. I take over when two-thirds of sales and more than half the
workforce are outside the UK.'
His five languages should come in handy.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
