<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Parliament and Politics: Labour plan to introduce
ministerial policy teams - Civil Service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR will raise the public esteem of civil servants, review but not revoke
the move to administrative agencies and broaden the political input to
decision-making through ministerial policy teams, Mr John Smith, the shadow
chancellor, said yesterday.
The proposals came in what was Labour's first important statement on
government administration, delivered in a keynote speech last night to the
Royal Institute of Public Administration.
In a clear effort to differentiate Labour's approach from that of the
Tories, Mr Smith argued that the 1980s had seen a fashion for disparaging
the work of the public sector. 'The case for efficient, adequately resourced
and highly motivated public services is neither hard to explain nor
difficult to justify,' he argued.
Yet in recent speeches, Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, and Mr John Major,
the prime minister, had continued to stress that the government was still
committed to reduce the size of the administration.
'It is certain that significant cutbacks will be necessary if the
Conservatives are to achieve their goal of a basic tax rate of 20 pence,' Mr
Smith warned.
Putting the case for devoting the 'growth dividend' to investment and
improvement in public services, he said that Tory efforts to achieve private
affluence 'ignore the risks of public squalor.'
Labour would attempt to keep pay 'broadly comparable with equivalent
movements elsewhere.' Acknowledging that there remained scope for improved
efficiency, he endorsed a recent speech by Lord Armstrong, the previous head
of the civil service, for more training.
Tackling the issue of political input to policy making, Mr Smith backed the
Treasury select committee's recommendation of Ministerial Policy Units
comprising both political appointees and career civil servants.
On new administrative agencies, he hinted that Labour would not scrap the
system, though their role would be reviewed. What was vital was that
agencies were not a first step to privatisation.
In his concluding remarks, Mr Smith emphasised that at least some of the
problem of accountability would be resolved by a new Freedom of Information
Act, to be introduced by Labour in the first session of a new parliament.
</TEXT>
