<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Parliament and Politics: Lang seeks to head off dispute over
devolution - Scottish Conservatives' Conference
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR IAN LANG, the Scottish secretary, yesterday sought to quash speculation
that the party leadership in Scotland was softening its opposition to
devolution.
In a speech to the party's annual conference in Perth, however, he
concentrated his fire on the assembly with tax-raising powers proposed by
the other Scottish parties in the Constitutional Convention.
He acknowledged that the government would listen, if sceptically, to
suggestions for a deliberative assembly as part of its plans to restructure
local government in Scotland.
Mr Lang's speech, marking the start of the three-day conference, was
designed to head off a damaging row in the party over devolution in the run
up to the general election.
Recent comments by party officials suggesting a more responsive approach to
the issue have provoked a fierce response from the Thatcherite wing of the
party.
In yesterday's conference debate, a number of speakers suggested that the
planned move to single-tier local authorities in Scotland would leave a gap
that could be filled by some form of national representation in Edinburgh.
Mr Michael Hirst, the president of the Scottish associations, made a coded
appeal for a wider debate by opening the conference with the comment that:
'It is through examining, debating and justifying our policy positions that
we can be sure that our policies are right for Scotland.'
Mr Lang, however, insisted that the review of local government structure
would not become 'the Trojan horse of a tax-raising Scottish assembly'.
Devolved powers for Scotland, he added, could only be accepted in the
context of a similar trend across the whole of the UK.
The divisive potential of the issue was underlined by repeated statements by
Mr Chris Patten, the Conservative party chairman, denying recent press
speculation that he is in favour of a move towards Scottish devolution.
Mr Patten denied that he had even 'thought, let alone said anything', on the
subject.
The conference opened with the latest opinion polls showing the
Conservatives holding some 24 per cent of the vote. That remains well above
the level last year when Mrs Margaret Thatcher's unpopularity pushed it down
to about 17 per cent, but it has dropped back from the 26 per cent the
Tories achieved in the wake of Mr John Major's succession to Downing Street.
</TEXT>
