<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Parliament and Politics: Tories in 'band' criticism: Council
Tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TORY backbenchers joined with Labour MPs yesterday in criticising the narrow
base of the new council tax which the government is proposing to introduce
as a replacement for the poll tax.
Mr Steven Norris (C Epping Forest) called for the number of property
valuation bands to be increased from seven to nine, with Pounds 20,000
introduced as the new base, and Pounds 250,000 and over as the top range.
Changes were also advocated by Mr Roger Sims (C Chislehurst) who complained
that retention of the seven bands would result in people in his constituency
with modest properties being placed in the same category as those in
'millionaires row'.
Mr Michael Heseltine, environment secretary, said the government had looked
at 'various permutations' and had concluded that the seven-band arrangement
(with Pounds 160,000 at the top of the range) was the most appropriate.
He promised that if the consultation process being undertaken by the
government indicated that there were specific areas in which the capital
value process needed modification 'we will look at that'.
Mr Heseltine said as the tax was designed for local authorities to
administer and collect, it was appropriate for the government to proceed by
consultation and not imposition.
Mr Bryan Gould, shadow environment secretary, argued that the seven-band
range reflected the government's determination to retain the poll tax
principle by ensuring that the rich be protected from paying their 'full
whack'.
Mr Michael Portillo, local government minister, stressed that those in the
most expensive properties would pay 2 1/2 times as much as those in the
least expensive properties.
He said this was 'a very fair apportionment of the burden'.
</TEXT>
