FT  09 MAY 91 / Businessman is jailed for forgery
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
DR Shrian Oskar, a businessman, was sentenced to three years' jail at the
Old Bailey yesterday after a jury found him guilty of forgery and on two
counts of perverting the course of justice.
The court had been told that, using a forged affidavit, he had hoped to
overturn a two-year sentence imposed in 1985 for dishonesty and to fight
extradition proceedings launched by the Australian government.
Dr Oskar is already serving six years after being convicted last autumn of a
Pounds 400,000 fraud on Midland Bank.
After that trial, the home secretary issued a deportation order against him.
Judge Lawrence Verney, the Recorder of London, said yesterday the three-year
term should be concurrent with Dr Oskar's existing sentence so that the
deportation order was carried out at the earliest opportunity.
