<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Brown envelopes seal future of commercial TV
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BROWN envelopes that will determine the fate of the UK's 16 commercial
television companies will be opened next Thursday.
The envelopes will contain bids that might commit applicants to paying the
government a total of Pounds 3bn to Pounds 4bn for a 10-year commercial
broadcasting licence from the beginning of 1993. There are expected to be 35
to 40.
The ceremonial opening of the bids by the Independent Television
Commission's chairman, deputy chairman, chief executive and secretary is
part of the process of validating information submitted by applicants. Bids
will be checked, then locked in a safe.
So far, the gaze of the television industry has fixed on one date and time -
noon on Wednesday, May 15, the deadline for bids. Less attention has been
given to what happens next, how the commission will handle the mountain of
paperwork that will be delivered on Wednesday morning and how the commission
will make decisions.
A careful procedure will tend to place a greater emphasis on highest bids
than has been widely realised before.
Some ministers have backtracked in private on the wisdom of the Broadcasting
Act's provision that each licence will go to the highest bidder that reaches
a quality threshold, unless there are exceptional circumstances such as an
underbidder offering exceptionally high programme quality.
The commission is clear on the issue. Whatever ministers say, it has to
implement the law to the letter if it is to avoid having its decisions
challenged in the High Court. Until recently there was a feeling in the
independent television industry that somehow deals could be done to prevent
too many ITV companies losing their franchises.
Mr David Mellor, chief secretary to the Treasury, appeared to encourage that
view when he was broadcasting minister by suggesting that continuity of the
network might be a reason for setting aside a highest bid under the
exceptional-circumstances clause. The commission believes 'continuity'
cannot be legally defined. It will decide, franchise area by franchise area,
without considering what effect those decisions are having on the overall
shape of the ITV network.
Mr David Glencross, the ITC's chief executive, said: 'What we are really
saying is that the quality threshold is similar to what has already been
achieved and that those who get over it will be able to provide a service at
least as good as people get now.'
The commission believes that the demands on applicants and the costs
involved in mounting a bid for a large region - up to Pounds 2m - have
effectively weeded out frivolous bids.
Next Thursday, a licence working group under the chairmanship of Mr Michael
Redley, the commission's official in charge of licensing, will begin work on
the applications to draw up a list of bidders that pass the quality
threshold. The working group will draw on the financial, regional and
programming expertise of the commission's officials. Each of the eight
members of the commission - excluding the chairman and deputy chairman -
will oversee two of the 16 contests.
The officials will submit recommendations and briefing papers to the
commission, which has 10 members, within two or three months for the final
decision on which applicants will make it to the last bidding round. Only
then will the cash bids be brought out of the safe.
When a winner is established in each area, commission members will consider
whether there are exceptional circumstances that would overturn the verdict
of the brown envelopes. If exceptional circumstances are being considered,
all the companies involved will be invited to the commission for a private
hearing.
The final stage before the winners are announced, probably by the end of
October, will be to look at the priorities of the applicants.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
