FT  09 MAY 91 / UK News (Employment): Poaching seen as big obstacle to
training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRAINING and Enterprise Councils (Tecs) should promote practical measures to
tackle skills shortages, according to a report by the Business Strategies
research group, published yesterday.
Reviewing the role of Tecs, the group says the threat of poaching is the
most serious obstacle to skill training. As training levies are 'unlikely to
be implemented in the near future', Tecs should concentrate on removing
other barriers that contribute to skill shortages.
Those include practical child-care issues, which preclude women from
working, and lack of information for companies about local skills training
and the mobility of labour.
'Most of these functions are performed already by specialist companies or
individuals, but not comprehensively and certainly not in an integrated
fashion,' the report says.
Mr Richard Holt, senior economist at Business Strategies, said: 'This is not
just a problem for Tecs to deal with, it is also up to major employers to
help improve labour supply mismatches. There is a major business opportunity
for the Employment Service companies to provide a far more integrated
recruitment, relocation and retraining service.'
Figures published by the Department of Employment yesterday show that more
than half of all unemployed people of working age - 57 per cent last year -
have some academic qualifications. That is a slight increase on 1989, when
55 per cent of unemployed people had qualifications, the 1990 labour force
survey says.
Skills Creation, Business Strategies, 10 Kendrick Mews, London SW7 3HG,
Pounds 85.
