<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / World Trade News: EC hits at Japan audio cassettes -
Brussels' dumping arsenal likely to come under renewed scrutiny
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE EUROPEAN Community is due on Monday to impose definitive anti-dumping
duties on Japanese audio cassettes in a controversial move.
The cassette dispute has already provoked a threat from Tokyo to cease
investing in the EC. The case still excites concern in a minority of EC
member states and is bound to lead to renewed scrutiny of the EC's
anti-dumping arsenal.
The EC Commission has secured a qualified majority of the 12 member states
to impose the levy, Brussels officials say. To do so, it has dropped a more
contentious case against imported tape used by Japanese companies to
assemble cassettes in the EC.
The tape case is incendiary because the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade last year outlawed the EC's so-called 'screwdriver' rules against
products assembled in the EC using imported parts. Critics saw the tape
action as an EC attempt to reintroduce the anti-circumvention provisions
banned by Gatt.
Brussels has agreed to drop the tape inquiry, but lawyers acting for
Japanese companies say it has not altered the figures used to calculate
injury to EC producers.
These, they claim, are related to a percentage of market share which could
only have been reached by including output of Japanese affiliates producing
inside Europe.
The Commission denies this. The measure is designed and drafted to specify
that this output is not included in the injury, an official insisted.
The definitive duties are likely to be lower than expected - an average of
about 17 per cent.
This compares with provisional duties ranging from 14.7 to 22.3 per cent
imposed last November and a 22-24 per cent band suggested by the Commission
last month. Commission investigators originally calculated there was a
dumping margin of 60 per cent.
The case has been bitterly fought. On April 30, Tokyo told Gatt's
anti-dumping committee that if the EC went ahead with definitive levies on
cassettes, Japanese companies would review plans to invest in Europe.
According to one EC diplomat, Japanese companies have made veiled promises
of investment in member states voting against the measure. But lawyers
acting for Japanese companies in the row insist their clients have merely
stressed that the EC's methodology amounts 'objectively to an attack on
inward investment'.
The row over methods centres on the reference period, fixed unusually far
back in 1985-88. Injury has been related to EC cassette producers' market
share in 1985 and the prices they would have needed to get a 12 per cent
profit then. The Commission admits that during the reference period, market
share of imports from Japan fell from 42 to 35 per cent. Hence the parallel
investigation into audio tape. If cassettes produced inside the EC using
imported tape are taken into account, Japan's share rose significantly.
The Commission says the flaw in this argument is that 'it assumes that the
remaining 35 per cent (market share) was not injurious, and was not unfairly
gained'.
EC diplomats say Ireland, the Netherlands, Spain and Belgium, among the
original dissenters from Brussels' view, now accept the cassettes case has
been definitively cleansed of 'screwdriver' taint.
Those member states almost certain to vote against the levies - the UK,
Luxembourg and Denmark - also appear to accept that EC output by Japanese
companies is not considered by the regulation. But the UK, for one, while
not objecting to the dumping finding, is still unhappy with the methodology
and the resulting figures.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-890</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEIBNAD9FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910509
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Sales south of the border seen to be basis for growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SELLING more electricity, particularly south of the Scottish border, will be
the key to profit growth for ScottishPower and Scottish Hydro-Electric, the
two electricity companies announced in their pathfinder flotation
prospectus, published yesterday.
Pool - or spot market - prices in England and Wales would also be critical
in determining the future profitability of the two companies, the prospectus
said.
Hydro-Electric, the smaller of the two companies, was more forceful than
ScottishPower about exporting electricity. Mr Roger Young, chief executive,
told a London press conference yesterday: 'Virtually all our profit growth
will come from generation and supply.'
Since the industry was restructured last March, both companies' electricity
sales have increased significantly, the prospectus shows.
Hydro-Electric's sales have grown from 7.4m megawatt-hours in the year
ending March 1990, to 10.1m MW-hours this financial year. ScottishPower's
sales have increased from 19.8m to 21.9m over the same period. In both cases
the increase stemmed largely from increased sales outside the companies'
area.
Hydro-Electric was also more assertive about competing in the electricity
market, selling directly to large industrial customers in England and Wales.
It has won 11 contracts to supply 39 customers outside its region.
ScottishPower, which has been less openly aggressive, won contracts to
supply 10 customers outside its area, and has since lost two. It will
consider alternatives to direct sales, in particular selling to the pool in
England and Wales, the company said.
ScottishPower was cautious about the future of prices to large customers,
which it believed might fall significantly. If that happened, the company
said, it may become uneconomic to supply those customers.
Both companies said they expected to make considerable cost savings in the
generation business, particularly because they will have lower cost
gas-fired generation from mid 1992, when gas from the North Sea Miller field
will be available to supply the power station at Peterhead, Aberdeenshire,
whose output they share.
Mr Young gave a warning that the quantity of Miller gas that would be
delivered was one of a number of uncertainties faced by Hydro-Electric.
Another risk was the plan by both companies to upgrade the interconnector,
which connects the Scottish grid to the National Grid in England and Wales.
ScottishPower said it expected demand for electricity to bring some natural
growth to its other main business, the transmission and distribution of
electricity to end customers.
This 'wires' business, which is generally regarded as stable and
predictable, represents 70 per cent of ScottishPower's operating profit, but
only 45 per cent of Hydro-Electric's, the prospectus disclosed.
Hydro-Electric said its distribution business should continue to make a
substantial contribution to profits, but it was vulnerable to growing
competition from gas. About 52 per cent of end users in the company's area
were served by a natural gas network compared with 84 per cent in the UK
overall, the company said.
Unlike the 12 electricity companies of England and Wales, the distribution
businesses of the Scottish companies will not be able automatically to
increase revenues by raising prices. The 'x factors' that regulate how much
they can increase prices on top of inflation every year are much lower - at
0.2 for each company - than their southern rivals.
</TEXT>
