FT  09 MAY 91 / World Trade News: Bush opens US ports to E Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bush, in an important revision of US policy, yesterday threw open
all US ports to former Soviet satellite nations and declared his intention
'to stimulate commercial trade between the US and the region'.
Mr Marlin Fitzwater, White House spokesman, said the decision was another
step towards ending Cold War restrictions and welcoming eastern Europe into
'the international community of democratic nations'.
The action had been taken, after an intensive inter-agency review, 'in
recognition of the progress these countries have made toward democracy. The
new port policy follows other recent moves to expand US trade with eastern
Europe. Last month duty-free trade benefits were extended to Czechoslovakia,
Poland, Hungary and Yugoslavia.
The new port policy maintains the same delineation between the Soviet Union
and the eastern Europeans that the Bush administration has retained on other
trade matters. Export controls, for example, have been liberalised towards
the eastern bloc more than for the Soviet Union.
The new port policy opens all US ports for commercial, cargo, passenger and
fishing vessels from eastern European nations. In the past, access for ships
from Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, Hungary, Poland and Romania was severely
limited. They could not enter 12 'high security' ports at all and they were
required to give two weeks' notice for other ports.
Now the six will be required to give only 24 hours' notice for any ports.
Soviet ships must give two days' notice at 49 ports and two weeks' notice at
others. Access to 12 high security ports is still denied to Soviet ships.
</TEXT>
