<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / World Trade News: Danish tunnel in trouble
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HILARY BARNES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COPENHAGEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CONSTRUCTION of a 7.7km rail tunnel under the Great Belt, the main waterway
into the Baltic Sea, has become a nightmare for MT Group, the international
consortium constructing the tunnel.
The tunnel is now 13 months behind schedule, all work is at a standstill,
and the state-owned company which has commissioned the tunnel has issued
barely concealed warnings that changes will be made in the consortium if
work does not progress more smoothly.
James Howden, the Glasgow group which delivered the four tunnel-boring
machines, also built the machines which have nearly completed the work of
boring the Channel Tunnel.
The rail tunnel under the eastern half of the Great Belt is one part of a
three-part DKr19bn (Pounds 1.68bn) project to build a rail and road link
across the 14km belt to link Sjaelland, the large island on which Copenhagen
is sited, with the Jutland peninsula.
A road and rail bridge across the western half of the belt to the tiny
island of Sprogo in mid-belt will link up with the rail tunnel and a
motorway bridge across the eastern half. MT Group is led by Monberg and
Thorsen, a Danish company, and includes Campenon Bernard, France, Dyckerhoff
and Widmann of Germany, Kiewit Construction of the US, and Sogea of France.
A six-month delay in the delivery of the machines was the first setback for
MT Group. Since the first machine was started up last August, there have
been endless problems getting them to work properly.
On Tuesday this week, all four machines were halted for repair work and the
personnel working on the tunnel have been laid off. So far, the machines
have tunnelled 840 metres. According to the schedule, they should have
tunnelled 2,400 metres by now. MT Group has until May 17 to say when
tunnelling can restart and when the tunnel will be completed.
</TEXT>
