FT  09 MAY 91 / Saddam holds talks with Kurdish leader
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Saddam Hussein of Iraq yesterday met Mr Masoud Barzani, leader of
the Kurdish Democratic Party and a longstanding enemy, as negotiations
continued over nationwide political reforms and autonomy for Iraqi
Kurdistan.
Mr Saddam had talks two weeks ago with Mr Jalal Talabani, who heads the
Patriotic Union of Kurdistan, the other main guerrilla group in the Iraqi
Kurdistan Front.
Mr Talabani spoke then of an agreement in principle on Kurdish autonomy, but
many Kurds doubt that the Iraqi government will meet their demands for
international guarantees to uphold an accord. Nor has Iraq expressed a
willingness to allow the oil town of Kirkuk to be included in the Kurdish
region.
The official Iraqi news agency said only of yesterday's meeting that Mr
Barzani had led a four-man delegation of Kurds.
Kurdish leaders are anxious to reverse the exodus of Kurds from northern
Iraq which followed a failed uprising in March, while Mr Saddam apparently
wants to bring peace to the north so that he can tighten his grip on Iraq as
a whole.
The allied forces - whose victory over Iraq in the Gulf war prompted the
Iraqi uprisings - have set up 'safe havens' for the Kurds in northern Iraq.
Yesterday an allied military spokesman said Iraqi anti-aircraft gunners
fired twice at US navy aircraft scouting the area on Tuesday, without
hitting the target. Baghdad denied its gunners had opened fire.
Meanwhile, the last US troops pulled out of southern Iraq. Units of the 3rd
Armoured Division rumbled across the desert and into Kuwait, while UN
peacekeeping forces in white four-wheel-drive vehicles patrolled the Iraqi
border town of Safwan and the surrounding area.
</TEXT>
