FT  09 MAY 91 / Bangladesh cyclone relief effort delayed by snags
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REAZUDDIN AHMED and K K SHARMA
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DHAKA, NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RELIEF efforts for the millions of people affected by last week's cyclone in
Bangladesh have been hampered by a lack of co-ordination between the
civilian government and senior army officials organising the operation.
Mrs Khaleda Zia, Bangladesh's new prime minister, who has been in office for
less than two months, yesterday cancelled a visit to Saudi Arabia because
she wants to head the relief effort and avert possible friction with the
military .
Officials admitted in Dhaka that millions of survivors of the cyclone in the
coastal areas are still not getting food, drinking water and medical
supplies. It could be several days before the relief operations become fully
effective, they said. Small non-governmental organisations whose
representatives have reached the affected areas have proved to be more
effective than the official machinery.
International aid pledges now total about Dollars 400m, but disbursement has
not yet started.
Some ships carrying food have are standing off Chittagong port, which is
only partly operational, and unloading is proving to be a problem.
The authorities are considering diverting the ships to another port.
