FT  09 MAY 91 / Seoul acts in land row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTH KOREA has frozen bank credit to 14 companies from eight of the
country's largest business groups for failing to obey a government order to
sell surplus land by Tuesday.
The measure is the strongest yet taken by the government in its attempts to
curb real estate speculation which has driven up land prices and diverted
funds from productive investment.
Last year, the government announced that companies must dispose of a total
of 57.44m pyong (149.55m square metres) of land which was not being directly
used for their business operations. At the beginning of this week, the
deadline for the disposal, only 63 per cent of this land had been sold.
The 14 companies - which belong to the Lotte Group, the Hanjin Group and six
other conglomerates - are expected to suffer financial difficulties as a
result of the credit freeze. They will face further penalties if they fail
to dispose of their non-business land by the end of the month. In
particular, they will be restricted to selecting just one company to be
freed from existing credit constraints under a new government policy.
