FT  09 MAY 91 / No chemical weapons at front, says UK general
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MYSTERY surrounding Iraq's tactics in the war over Kuwait deepened
yesterday when General Sir Peter de la Billiere, who commanded British
forces, said Baghdad had apparently not sent chemical weapons for use
against the US-led coalition.
Shortly before the allies launched their offensive in February, UK officials
said there was evidence that Iraq had moved chemical shells and rockets to
frontline units.
But Sir Peter told the House of Commons defence committee yesterday that to
his knowledge no chemical weapons had subsequently been recovered.
'I believe the reason for this is that they weren't deployed,' he said. It
had previously been assumed that Iraqi forces did not resort to chemical
weapons either because they had no opportunity to employ them effectively
against the rapid allied advance, or because of allied threats of
retaliation.
Sir Peter promised 'full disclosure' of the results of an investigation into
the deaths of nine British soldiers whose armoured vehicles were attacked by
a US A-10 aircraft.
His comment followed a reported statement by Lt-Gen Charles Horner, the US
Air Force commander in the war, that a British air controller had indicated
there were no allied forces in the area.
