<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Hawke uses his iron fist on the waterfront: Australia's
docks will no longer be a graveyard of good intentions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT TOOK nearly 19 hours of non-stop talking, and a whole packet of cigars,
but Mr Bob Hawke, Australia's Labor prime minister, appears to have pulled
off a deal which will clear the way for reform of the country's inefficient
docks.
The outcome was a much-needed political victory for the prime minister, who
ran the risk of losing his reputation as a master of consensus. If the deal
holds, he will gain a prize which has eluded governments for decades.
The Australian waterfront is a graveyard of good intentions. At least 11
official inquiries have recommended reform since the Second World War,
warning that high costs and bizarre labour practices were hampering trade.
All have sunk without trace in the face of lukewarm support from employers,
and implacable opposition from the Waterside Workers' Federation (WWF), the
monopoly supplier of labour.
In the union's eyes, every attempt at reform threatened a return to the
pre-war system of casual labour, when foremen would throw each day's work
tickets in the air for the strongest and quickest to catch, leaving the slow
and the unlucky without work.
To the employers, protected by limited competition and pooled labour costs,
any attempt to rock the boat raised the spectre of a prolonged dispute with
a union which could bring the wharves to a halt.
The result is that Australia has some of the world's most inefficient ports,
manned by some of the country's highest paid and most cosseted workers.
Among other benefits, dockers are guaranteed a job for life, paid for
travelling to work, and sometimes paid for not working. The dockers of
Thevenard, South Australia, were paid ADollars 370 (Pounds 169) a week last
year for an average of six hours' work.
The economic costs are high. The Inter-State Commission (ISC), a government
advisory body, estimated that Australian cranes move an average of 13.34
standard 20ft containers per hour, compared to an average of 24.72 at
overseas ports with which Australia trades.
The ISC put the cost of unnecessary labour and delays to shipping and cargo
at ADollars 620m a year, but exporters' organisations say the cost is closer
to ADollars 850m if lost business is included.
The Hawke government set out last year to reduce these costs through a
ADollars 290m restructuring scheme, to be funded jointly over three years by
the taxpayer and the employers, through a levy on cargoes. The scheme was
intended to reduce the workforce from 6,500 to 4,500 by financing redundancy
payments averaging just under ADollars 100,000 each for 3,000 older workers,
and training 1,000 younger recruits.
The ISC calculated the scheme would increase productivity by an average of
35 per cent. But only one company, National Australian Terminals, has so far
implemented an agreement, while others say negotiations with the union have
been unproductive.
It was against this background that negotiations on reform came to a halt
when the Industrial Relations Commission, the statutory authority which
oversees Australia's centralised wage-fixing system, put a national limit of
2.5 per cent on pay rises.
The decision meant that productivity-linked pay rises could not be paid to
waterfront workers without a special hearing before the Commission, which
both sides ruled out.
Mr Hawke stepped in because the deadlock threatened to undermine the
credibility of the government's wider programme of structural reform, which
is intended to increase Australia's international competitiveness.
The deal reached under his auspices will deliver a flat pay rise of ADollars
12 a week to dockers, plus 6 per cent over the next two years, but only
after reform agreements have been implemented, effectively locking the union
into the process.
The Commission will be asked to approve the deal to keep it within existing
industrial relations law, which also regulates arbitration and the conduct
of disputes. But Senator Bob Collins, the shipping minister, says the
government is determined to make the deal stick, even if it has to legislate
to create an 'alternative mechanism'. The immediate impact will be to force
the union to implement an outline reform agreement relating to the Sydney
container terminal run by Conaust, a P&amp;O subsidiary which handles about 50
per cent of container trade.
The Conaust agreement is significantly tougher than the earlier agreement
with National Terminals, and is likely to provide a blueprint for reform in
other ports.
However, the reform could yet be threatened by the refusal of employers to
recruit the 1,000 young workers specified by the government. Mr Richard
Setchell, Conaust managing director, says recruitment would be 'madness' in
the face of a severe decline in trade caused by Australia's stagnant
economy.
'We are not interested in hiring more people. Why would we overman the
industry again?' he says. 'What the unions are saying is a nonsense. We will
get rid of the people that we don't want; we are not going to go out and
hire them again.'
Hawke pressed on mining, Page 28
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
