<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Polly Peck may never repay Pounds 650m warn administrators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOME Pounds 650m of the Pounds 1.15bn debts of Polly Peck International may
never be repaid, administrators of the group warned yesterday in their first
formal report on the group's finances.
The three court-appointed administrators also reported serious misgivings
that the group did not hold legal title to assets bought with its money and
said accounting deficiencies had thrown up 'serious reservations as to the
reliability and fairness of the published results'.
News of Polly Peck's financial situation, which was worse than had been
generally expected, came in a report to creditors from the three - Mr
Michael Jordan and Mr Richard Stone of Coopers &amp; Lybrand Deloitte and Mr
Christopher Morris of Touche Ross.
If the proposals outlined yesterday are approved by creditors at a meeting
on May 24, Mr Asil Nadir will be replaced as chairman and chief executive.
The bulk of the group's operations would be continued, rather than sold off.
Only about Pounds 500m of Polly Peck's debts are likely to be refinanced or
repaid, according to the report. This would amount to an average of 44p for
every Pounds 1 owed, compared with only 20p in the event of an immediate
liquidation.
Most of the rest of the debt would be converted into an instrument which
would pay a return based on the future performance of the group's food,
packaging and leisure businesses in northern Cyprus and Turkey.
The administrators offered little hope of this instrument paying a
substantial return. They said they had gained virtually no access to the
businesses in the Near East, and had 'serious reservations' about claims in
Polly Peck's reports that these businesses had generated two thirds of group
profits last year. To ensure the maximum possible return to creditors, Mr
Nadir, a Turkish Cypriot, may be given a role in the Near East.
'It is too early to decide what his role might be; he has influence that can
be of benefit to the creditors,' said Mr Stone. Mr Nadir has been charged
with 18 counts of theft and false accounting involving sums exceeding Pounds
20m.
In their report, the administrators warn that the Pounds 1.16bn value put in
the group's accounts on its net assets in the Near East 'cannot now be
relied on upon'.
'These do not appear to have been fully under the control of the main board
of PPI,' they said, adding: 'The administrators understand that certain
assets are not held in the name of Group companies.'
Mr Paul Hipps, senior partner of Stoy Hayward, Polly Peck's auditor, said:
'The administrators have had full access to our audit working papers (those
dealing with the group accounts) and no queries have been raised with us.'
Background, Page 22
</TEXT>
