<PROFILE>_AN-BEIBNADGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910509
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Gorbachev decree puts strikers at risk of jail
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON and JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
STRIKERS IN essential industries in the Soviet Union face the prospect of
fines and possible imprisonment under the terms of a decree to be issued
next week by President Mikhail Gorbachev.
The annnouncement came as the last big group of striking coal miners - in
the Kuzbas area of Siberia - agreed to return to work tomorrow, though they
reserved the right to resume protests in two months if their demands for
better pay were not met.
Mr Valentin Pavlov, the Soviet prime minister, concerned to stifle any new
wave of strikes in essential sectors such as those which have plagued the
coalfields for the past two months, said yesterday that the decree would
give the authorities the right to prosecute strikers and those who incite
industrial action.
The decree, part of the government's anti-crisis programme, was agreed with
the leaders of nine republics in their landmark joint statement last month.
Mr Pavlov also urged the west to abandon its 'wait and see' approach to
events in the Soviet Union and provide substantial economic aid to ensure
the success of market reforms.
He said the country above all needed western assistance for making the
rouble convertible, a move which he described as 'the second stage' of
economic reform. 'If you want to intervene, you should do so resolutely in
order to obtain concrete results instead of giving advice from the side,' he
said.
Having already introduced price reform, the country would need substantial
imports to flood the market with goods, together with stand-by credits to
support the rouble once convertibility was introduced. Mr Pavlov did not say
when he wanted to switch to a convertible currency.
But he suggested that if invited, President Gorbachev would present these
requests for assistance to the Group of Seven leading industrialised
countries at their London summit in July.
He was confident that all 15 Soviet republics, including those which want
independence, would soon subscribe to a common economic reform programme.
Representatives of all the republics were expected to to complete final work
on the anti-crisis programme on Sunday. This would be followed next
Wednesday by a meeting, to be chaired by Mr Gorbachev, of the Soviet cabinet
and republican envoys.
Soviet and western critics of the Pavlov plan, which combines institutional
reforms with anti-crisis measures, have said it is unlikely either to
achieve financial stabilisation or to break the state's stranglehold over
industry. G7 countries have so far been cool about unleashing aid.
Economic light, Page 2
Observer, Page 18
</TEXT>
