<PROFILE>_AN-BEIBNADAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910509
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / London Stock Exchange: Equities drift lower in poor volume
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
ANOTHER unimpressive trad-ing session in London saw equities give back the
gains of the previous day, discouraged by corporate developments and the
less certain trend on Wall Street.
Interest rate optimism found fresh support from sterling's continued
firmness, as well as from a cut in mortgage rates by Nationwide Anglia,
second largest of the UK building societies; but over-enthusiasm was checked
by a warning from the Governor of the Bank of England against reading too
much into the recent drop in the headline inflation rate in the UK.
Once again, the chief feature was the low level of business in the equity
market. Not since the middle of last month has daily retail volume in
equities reached the Pounds 1bn mark regarded as the minimum for a healthy,
and profitable, trading session in the London market. Seaq-recorded volume,
which takes in both retail and intra market business and is therefore a
somewhat unreliable guide to the level of genuine investment business,
reached only 387.9m shares yesterday, compared with 431.2m on Tuesday, when
turnover was swollen by the large placing of shares in Saatchi &amp; Saatchi.
The return to low trading volumes since the end of March has been
discomforting for London-based securities houses, and has been reflected
this week in further cutbacks in staff at City firms. The first quarter of
the year, when the London equity market showed one of the highest levels of
total return for the past decade, according to Barclays de Zoete Wedd, had
also been accompanied by a substantial improvement in volumes.
However, there were indications yesterday that the institutions still have
heavy cash balances ready to commit when suitable situations offer
themselves. In addition to their ready response to the Dollars 1.35bn
purchase of the North Sea assets of Occidental Petroleum by Enterprise Oil
and Elf Aquitaine, the big players took up the outstanding tap stock issue
in the gilt-edged market. It was also disclosed that 89 per cent of the
Pounds 96m recent rights issue from Morgan Crucible had been taken up, and
the rump of 4.7m shares placed in the market; this was considered a highly
satisfactory outcome.
The market was on the downside throughout yesterday's trading session, with
attempts to rally repeatedly unsuccessful. A final downturn was featured by
weakness in the international oil shares as the sector backed away ahead of
today's trading statement from British Petroleum. Also unhelpful was Wall
Street's weak start to its new trading session following reports that
President Bush had suffered a further health problem.
The final reading left the FT-SE Index at 2,523.4, the fall on the day of
17.1 virtually cancelling the advance of the previous session. Market
strategists have read little into either day's market trend. Attention
remained focused on the prospects for another half- point cut in UK base
rates at the end of next week, when the April retail price index will
provide the latest evidence on UK inflation levels.
Once again, investors played closer attention to individual company
statements than to the overall trend of the market. A maintained interim
dividend from Trafalgar House, the construction, property and shipping
group, removed one market uncertainty.
However, SmithKline Beecham, the pharmaceuticals group, closed lower after
erratic price movement in spite of interim results much in line with
expectations.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 38
</PAGE>
