<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / World Stock Markets (Asia Pacific): Second-liners feature as
first section weakens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INVESTORS turned to second-liners yesterday as share prices on the big board
were weakened by the fall on Wall Street and the lower yen, writes Emiko
Terazono in Tokyo.
The Nikkei average lost 32.35 at 26,309.79. The index touched a day's low of
26,178.22 in the afternoon, but arbitrage buying brought a partial recovery
and the index later reached the day's high of 26,367.99.
Overall activity remained lacklustre as volume rose slightly to 270m shares
from 220m shares. Declines outnumbered gains by 669 to 275, with 170 issues
unchanged. The Topix index of all first section stocks shed 9.67 to
1,987.04, and in London the ISE/Nikkei 50 index eased 1.69 to 1,499.08.
Traders said investors, who had expected a cut in the discount rate after
the Golden Week holidays, were disappointed by the stable monetary policy.
Concern over high arbitrage positions also depressed sentiment.
Mr Masami Okuma at UBS Phillips &amp; Drew said that if market conditions failed
to recover, heavy selling by investment trusts could push the Nikkei below
the important 26,000 level.
Small and medium-capital stocks with brisk earning outlooks were sought by
investors. The second section rose 8.79 to 3,397.83, while the
over-the-counter index finished 17.52 ahead at 3,286.64.
The big four Japanese brokerages promoted issues related to Japan Railway's
capital investment. Nippon Signal, a railway operation equipment maker,
closed Y50 up at Y1,620 after making a record high of Y1,670. Totetsu Kogyo,
a track maker, put on Y50 to Y1,260.
Companies which announced cuts in the minimum trading units for their shares
mostly gained ground. Tachikawa, a curtain and blind manufacturer listed on
the second section, finished a net Y120 stronger at Y4,150 after climbing to
an all-time high of Y4,320. The company announced that it would reduce the
minimum trading unit from 1,000 to 100 shares.
Nippon Television Network moved ahead Y400 to Y26,900 on declaring that it
would reduce its unit from 100 to 10 shares. On the other hand, Asatsu, the
advertising agency which was popular recently for the same reason, retreated
Y160 to Y7,830 on profit-taking.
Nihon Nohyaku, the day's most active stock, rose Y80 to Y2,540 on
speculative buying. The issue has climbed from Y750 since February 1, and
some traders are concerned about its high margin level.
Liquid crystal display makers were sought on hopes of strong sales, but fell
on late profit-taking. Sharp, which has a dominant market position, slipped
Y30 to Y1,590, while Casio Computer lost Y10 on balance at Y1,300 after
touching a year's high of Y1,340.
In Osaka, the OSE average dipped 175.39 to 29,185.32 on volume of 21.1m
shares. Shima Seiki attracted small-lot buying on stating that it would
reduce its trading unit to 100 from 1,000 shares. Profit-taking later pushed
the issue down to Y15,200 for a net fall of Y100.
Roundup
FINE TUNING seemed to be taking over from foreign buying yesterday, although
the latter continued to lift shares in Australia, where the Hong Kong
Chinese are said to be active, and is expected to return to New Zealand
where US activity was perceived.
NEW ZEALAND saw profit-taking after a five-day rally, the Barclays index
surrendering 23.14 or 1.5 per cent to 1,556.61 following a 7.6 per cent gain
in the previous five trading days. Turnover eased from NZDollars 21.4m to
NZDollars 20.4m. Brokers said sentiment remained generally bullish.
Brierley Investments slipped 3 cents to NZDollars 1.24 on 2.6m share volume,
after a rise of 17 cents in the previous two sessions on news that the
Singapore government is paying NZDollars 126m for a 4.7 per cent stake in
the company, and a further NZDollars 660m for a 30 per cent shareholding in
its UK hotels unit.
AUSTRALIA attracted more overseas buying as the All Ordinaries index added
7.9 at 1,545.7. Turnover expanded from ADollars 180m to ADollars 294m.
Trading volume was boosted by the sale of 25.9m shares in TNT, the transport
group, for around ADollars 34.5m by the shipping and coal concern McIlwraith
McEacharn. TNT firmed 4 cents to ADollars 1.43 after short sellers had to
buy back the stock at a higher price.
MANILA's initial gains were shaved by profit-taking, leaving the composite
index 12.54 up on the day at 1,113.43. BANGKOK's SET index ended 8.61 better
at 848.67, recovering less than a third of Tuesday's 27.94 or 3.2 per cent
drop on political worries.
HONG KONG, where the vice-chairman of the stock exchange resigned yesterday
after advocating preferential treatment for council members in new share
issues, closed modestly higher. The Hang Seng index improved 6.29 to
3,747.80; turnover was little changed at HKDollars 1.12bn.
SEOUL's increasing concern over political uncertainties left the composite
index down 4.05 at 631.12, its fifth fall in a row.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
