<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Commodities and Agriculture: Chevron pours oil on troubled
waters - As the Angolan ceasefire approaches, Julian Ozanne looks at the oil
sector's prospects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BOW-LEGGED Americans in jeans, cowboy boots, and shiny rodeo belt buckles
stand around the air-conditioned pool hall in Chevron's Malongo camp,
sipping Budweiser, Miller Lite and US-imported Coke Classic.
Outside in the steamy equatorial heat, helicopters flown by Vietnam veterans
ferry oilmen between the offshore rigs and platforms to the camp, passing
over a well-watered nine-hole golf course, astro-turf greens, tennis courts
and the steady flow of Ford and Chevrolet pick-ups along a network of
immaculate tarmac roads.
Malongo camp, on the sweltering central African coast, is the base of
operations for the Cabinda Gulf Oil Company (Cabgoc), a successful and
productive joint venture oil company in which the Angolan state oil company,
Sonangol, has a majority 51 per cent shareholding.
Operated by Chevron, the largest private shareholder, the camp is more like
Texas than Angola. It is one of the reasons why the war-torn and
economically crippled country has become one of the fastest-growing oil
producers in Africa and the second largest after Nigeria.
A huge influx of foreign investment and expertise in the early 1980s has
laid the basis for a doubling of Angola's production in the last six years
from 232,000 barrels per day in 1985 to 476,000 bpd last year. Cabgoc's
Cabinda offshore concession contributed about 45-50 per cent of national
production in 1990. Proven reserves last year stood at 2.34bn barrels, the
equivalent of nearly 14 years of production at current levels.
The oil industry has played a vital role in the Angolan economy, plagued by
16 years of destructive civil war and inefficient socialist central
planning.
The sector earned Angola Dollars 2.7bn (Pounds 1.56bn) in 1989, accounting
for about 91 per cent of export earnings, 57 per cent of real GDP and 62 per
cent of fiscal revenues.
Investment in exploration and development in the Angolan oil industry in the
last three years is estimated at about Dollars 2-2.5bn, largely due to big
discoveries and development in Block 3, a production-sharing agreement
operated by Elf Aquitaine - Angola's second largest producer  - and
continued development in the Cabinda offshore concession, including the
recent construction of two new production platforms and a water injection
platform.
According to Mr Joao Lourenco Landoite, Angola's petroleum minister, the
pace of investment and development will pick up dramatically over the next
five years.
Bidding is due to open for five of 16 new deep water concessions ranging
from 500-2000 feet. A model contract has already been drawn up setting out
the number of wells to be drilled, the minimum expenditure and the signature
bonus.
Preliminary talks have already been held with several interested oil
companies, including British Petroleum and Shell, which are not currently
operating in Angola.
'We want to get more foreign companies coming into Angola for oil
exploration, and if they are British companies they are welcome,' said Mr
Landoite, who visited London in March. 'We need new experience, new money
and we want to better understand the international oil industry.'
In addition to the new deeper water blocks, significant investment is
expected in exploration activity in several new areas recently awarded or
under negotiation, including an onshore concession at Cabinda with BP and
other shallow water offshore concessions with Unocal, Conoco, Elf, Total and
Texaco.
Mr Landoite is also currently tying up a Dollars 120m financing package to
allow Sonangol to act as operator for the first time with technical
assistance from Range Oil in Block 4.
Further exploration, development and recovery in the Cabinda offshore
fields, where four rigs are currently active, is expected to boost Cabgoc's
production to 325,000-350,000 b/d in 1994. The Ministry of Petroleum
projects total national production in 1994 from existing producing
concessions at 611,000 b/d.
With a ceasefire in the 16-year civil war now agreed for May 15, Mr Landoite
is also optimistic about the development of other onshore concessions and
the five southernmost shallow water offshore concessions - blocks 9-13 -
whose prospects have been hindered because of insecurity and the threat of
rebel attack. Peace will also dramatically reduce the huge foreign exchange
costs of transport, insurance and importing all goods, even basic foodstuffs
and beverages.
While the enclave offshore oil sector has been largely insulated from the
civil war, isolated attacks did create problems. In February, 120 foreigners
working for Conoco had to be evacuated from Ambriz after rebels besieged the
town.
Foreign companies have found the investment climate favourable in Angola.
The oil industry operates outside of the administrative and foreign exchange
controls imposed on the rest of the economy. Profitability has been high as
a result of low costs of production, the high exploration success rate and
the government's flexible policy on fiscal matters.
Foreign investors have also been attracted to Angola because crude
production is not limited by quotas imposed by the Organisation of Petroleum
Exporting Countries.
Domestic distribution of petroleum products is currently carried out
exclusively by Sonangol, but Mr Landoite says the government will privatise
distribution this year.
'It has been a mistake. We must open the market to privately owned local and
foreign companies. There is no way of going on as we are now,' he said.
While most industry analysts foresee a healthy and exciting future ahead for
the Angolan oil sector, some doubts remain over the operations of Sonangol,
allegations of high-level government corruption and the real net inflow into
the country of oil earnings.
In an otherwise candid interview, Mr Landoite excused himself from
addressing the question of the net inflow of earnings, confirming suspicions
that a controversy is raging in government about the huge outflows from the
oil sector in expatriate salaries, dividends, transport, insurance and
oil-industry imports.
Maximising the benefits of the oil sector for the domestic Angolan economy
will be a pressing task as the oil industry continues to expand rapidly in
the coming years.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 28
</PAGE>
