<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Commodities and Agriculture: Tin prices forecast to rise
strongly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TIN PRICES will rally to Dollars 6,500 a tonne in the next six months,
correct and gradually rise to Dollars 7,500 a tonne 'within the next 12
months,' according to a special report from Rudolf Wolff, the London trader,
writes David Blackwell.
Yesterday cash tin on the London Metal Exchange closed at Dollars 5,770 a
tonne, a rise of Dollars 15 on the day.
In the short term, says Wolff, any significant rally is likely to be met by
a knee-jerk reaction from lower cost producers. But trade buyers willing to
take a longer view will in the end force the consumer's hand, provoking
forward buying.
'This will provide the market with a solid floor until confidence is
restored and producers find an application for strategic hedging, which has
been unnecessary for so long in the tin market.'
On the supply side, Wolff expects the market imbalance to be redressed quite
quickly. At present price levels Wolff estimates about 60 per cent of
production is uneconomical.
</TEXT>
