<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / International Bonds: Elf Enterprise Petroleum in innovative
finance deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ELF Enterprise Petroleum, the new joint company formed by Elf Aquitaine and
Enterprise Oil, secured economically attractive financing yesterday by
making innovative use of an equity-linked structure.
Elf Enterprise Finance issued Pounds 438m of bonds exchangeable into Elf
Enterprise Petroleum ordinary shares, the second largest offering in the
sterling convertible market after Hanson's Pounds 500m issue last month.
Previously, the exchangeable structure has been used by companies to trade
out of hostile stakes in target companies, for example, General Cinema
issued bonds exchangeable into Cadbury-Schweppes shares, News Corporation
into Pearson and Bond Corporation into Allied-Lyons.
But in this instance, Elf Aquitaine's 25 per cent holding of Enterprise Oil
shares is to provide funds for a joint venture between the two companies,
while at the same time closing out the overhang of Enterprise oil equity,
which had put some pressure on its share price.
'(The exchangeable bond structure) balanced marketing requirements with the
need to deploy shares into mutually-owned assets, to maximise proceeds from
the exchangeable bonds without putting undue pressure on our ordinary
shares', said Mr John Walmsley, financial director of Enterprise Oil.
An equity placing would have raised less than the convertible, as the shares
would have had to be priced at a discount to the current market price. The
exchange price for the bonds is 640p, 15 per cent above Tuesday's closing
level.
The deal was primarily aimed at UK investors, but was also broadly
distributed in Europe. Dealers said the issue met strong demand from both
equity investors - the bonds yield about 5 per cent more than the underlying
shares, with the exchange price set at a reasonably premium - and bond
investors.
Lead manager SG Warburg, joint lead Goldman Sachs and co-lead Cazenove split
an 'exempt list' of more than 100 big institutional accounts, mainly UK,
between them, which other underwriters banned from calling. Although this
practice, sometimes seen in the domestic market, helped facilitate orderly
distribution of the deal, the size of the list was felt to be excessive.
The deal performed strongly to close at 100 1/4 bid, above its par issue
price.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
