<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / International Capital Markets: Blazing a trail in southern
Italy - Haig Simonian explains the change of status for Banco di Napoli
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANCO di Napoli, the large public-sector Italian bank, is called many names,
but 'trail-blazer' is not one of them.
However, the Naples-based bank, which is the biggest financial institution
in southern Italy and the fifth largest nationally, is the first big bank to
decide to use new laws letting it list up to 49 per cent of its shares on
the stock exchange.
Precisely when the bank goes ahead will depend on market conditions, says Mr
Antonio Sussi, its deputy director-general, who is also responsible for its
international activities. However, he adds, 'we expect to issue within the
year'.
Although some large public-sector banks, such as Banca Commerciale Italiana
(BCI) and Credito Italiano, are quoted, most are not.
Neither municipally-owned savings banks, such as Milan's Cariplo, are
listed, nor the handful of large banks which, like Banco di Napoli, are
owned by charitable foundations.
The closest private investors can get to such institutions is to buy special
categories of shares such as the non-voting savings stock which some have
listed, or the ordinary shares of quoted subsidiaries, such as Monte dei
Paschi di Siena's Banca Toscana operation.
Last year, legislation allowed such big banks to change their legal status
to joint stock companies, and thus move towards floating up to 49 per cent
of their ordinary shares. The decision at Banco di Napoli's annual meeting
on April 29 to change its status means it should be the first to go ahead.
How much the move will raise remains unclear. However, Mr Sussi stresses the
bank has put its long-standing problem of shortage of capital behind it.
The change to joint stock status will be accompanied by a revaluation of
assets which is set to more than double the bank's net worth from L1,742bn
at end-1990 to L3,620bn.
'At this point, we become a much bigger bank,' says Mr Sussi.
The figure will reach more than L5,000bn if subordinated loans and other
factors, such as the first L140bn tranche of a four-tranche L850bn cash
injection from the Italian Treasury, are included.
The changes will leave the previously under-capitalised bank much better
placed. At the end of last year, it had reached the Bank of Italy's current
capital standards.
The recapitalisation will also put it above the 1993 norms from the Bank for
International Settlements, Mr Sussi says. 'We will have a lot of room to
grow.'
Shareholders in the 'new' joint stock Banco di Napoli, which will be
formally launched on July 1, will be the foundation - which currently owns
all the bank - and the Italian Treasury. Following the translation of last
year's injection of Treasury funds into new shares in the bank, they will
have stakes of about 93 per cent and 6.5 per cent stake each.
Mr Sussi cannot say whether the bank will float 49 per cent of its stock on
the bourse in one go or will opt for smaller tranches. 'We really haven't
thought about that yet. It will depend on the market.'
Discussion of possible foreign tranches and potential lead managers for the
offering is also premature. 'We have to be sure the shares get placed with
investors who won't immediately sell them back in Italy,' notes Mr Sussi.
Although the bulk of the issue will be sold domestically, 'we could also
sell some shares abroad if we get the feeling that there are long-term
investors", says Mr Sussi. As matters stand, the bank reckons that more than
10 per cent of its savings shares are held outside Italy.
Banco di Napoli has grown in attractiveness as an investment since the early
1980s, when it barely made money. Even if profits remain relatively low, net
earnings jumped by 40.5 per cent to L104bn in 1989 and leapt a further 52.4
per cent to L159bn last year.
That came despite a contraction in total assets to L82,870bn from L85,128bn
in 1989, reflecting the bank's tougher policy on lending. According to
Barclays de Zoete Wedd, its loan loss provisions are now in line with
industry averages.
Shareholders have already had some reward, with the dividend on savings
shares being raised last year to L1,600 a share from L1,400.
Analysts say there is further profit potential in the bank's pension scheme.
The current, fully-funded in-house scheme is believed to be over-provided,
allowing scope for considerable savings in future. No allocation was made to
the fund last year.
The bank, which now has 617 branches, has been expanding its domestic
coverage, notably in the south. 'The south of Italy is still underbanked,'
says Mr Sussi. The bank plans to open almost 140 new branches this year,
most of them small units.
Further internationalisation is also in the pipeline, although Mr Sussi
rejects rumours that the bank is on the brink of a cross-equity deal with a
foreign counterpart.
'We have an operating agreement with Banco Exterior of Spain, but there is
nothing else planned,' he says. 'Our position is first to change the bank's
status; that will show our full strength. Then we can talk with others.'
With its new capital, is there not the risk of suddenly throwing caution to
the winds and spending wildly on acquisitions? 'It won't happen to us. We've
spent too many years living within very tight capital bounds,' says Mr
Sussi.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 27
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-937</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEIBNACYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910509
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / International Capital Markets: HK issue will mature under
Chinese rule
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Financial Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HONG Kong's heavily indebted, state-owned Mass Transit Railway yesterday
announced the issue of the first international bond from the colony with a
maturity stretching beyond 1997 - when Hong Kong reverts to Chinese
sovereignty, writes Our Financial Staff.
International bankers' confidence in Hong Kong has been shaken by Peking
refusing to back a HKDollars 100bn international airport project.
The MTR has built a reputation among international financial institutions as
a reliable borrower. It said its HKDollars 280m private placement bond,
maturing in 1998, was the first on the international market by a Hong Kong
issuer with a post-1997 maturity.
Mr Roger Moss, MTR finance director said the issue should not be seen as a
measure of confidence in the colony. 'We haven't suggested this deal signals
confidence in Hong Kong beyond 1997. There are bigger (political) issues to
look at if you want to discuss confidence in Hong Kong.
'This is a signal that a well-known borrower can complete a deal that goes
beyond 1997. We've always said that when the time is right, we would go for
a deal beyond 1997.' The issue, to be signed in Tokyo on May 22 but already
completed with lenders, is arranged by the Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan
and co-arranged by a syndicate of six Japanese banks.
'I'm quite sure this issue will be a success given the quality of the MTR
and their relationship with the international market,' a source at a
European bank said.
However, a source at a Japanese bank which took part in the latest deal
said: 'It's interesting, but it's too small to be significant. It's
basically a private, targeted deal'.
Mr Moss is credited with steering the railway company down an innovative
borrowing path through instruments such as Eurocommercial paper with Euroyen
options, Canadian dollar Eurobonds and Hong Kong dollar/US dollar dual
currency medium-term notes.
In 1989, a Euromoney survey published three months after the Tiananmen
square massacre, showed that the MTR was considered the world's third most
professional borrower after the World Bank and Sweden. At the end of 1990,
MTR's total outstanding debt stood at HKDollars 18.49bn against HKDollars
17.39bn in 1989.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
