<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / International Company News: Benefits sought from Canadian
rail link
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AIR CANADA and Canadian Pacific are studying how they could both benefit
from a proposed USDollars 6bn high-speed rail system between Quebec City and
Montreal and Toronto-Windsor.
They are jointly exploring business and leisure travel patterns that would
emerge in the so-called Quebec City-Windsor corridor, where nearly half of
Canada's 26m population lives.
The Montreal-Toronto air route is the only profitable domestic run in
current conditions, and Air Canada has more than half the traffic.
Canadian Pacific, through its CP Rail freight subsidiary, owns one of the
two rights-of-way in the corridor. Some of its track might be used for the
high-speed system, and although it has long moved out of long-distance
passenger services, it manages commuter rail systems in Toronto and
Montreal.
The CDollars 500,000 study is aimed at identifying business opportunities
for both companies if and when the high-speed link is built.
'We specialise in high-speed transportation,' said Mr Claude Taylor, Air
Canada chairman. 'We have a sophisticated computerised reservations system
and well-developed routes and connections. Our frequent flier programme is a
strong marketing tool.'
Air Canada believes connector services for the high-speed rail system could
be provided jointly with CP, using Toronto and Montreal, the country's two
largest cities, as hubs.
Bombardier and GEC-Alsthom are proposing to use an adapted French high speed
train for the corridor and Asea Brown Boveri wants to use Swedish or German
equipment. However, opponents argue that population density in the corridor
is still insufficient to make a high-speed rail link economic.
</TEXT>
