<TEXT>
SEARS, Roebuck, the troubled US retailing conglomerate, said yesterday that
two shareholders had failed in a legal attempt to delay the company's annual
meeting, which will take place today in Chicago.
District Judge Ronald Buckwalter denied a motion by the stockholders, who
together own 500 Sears shares, seeking a delay in the meeting on the grounds
that Sears failed to disclose, in proxy materials for the meeting, the
existence of a 1988 shareholder suit in Chicago against the company.
The Chicago case, revealed last weekend in a newspaper article, alleges that
a restructuring of Sears in 1988 was meant to entrench management against a
possible takeover threat.
