FT  09 MAY 91 / International Company News: German metal groups decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MANNESMANN and Metallgesellschaft, two leading German diversified
engineering and metals groups, yesterday reported a fall in earnings
reflecting a slowdown in world economic growth and weakness in some key
markets.
Both companies, among the most acquisitive on the German business scene
during the last few years, have been preparing shareholders for a downturn
in profits as a result of worsening trading conditions in recent months.
Mr Heinz Schimmelbusch, chief executive at Metallgesellschaft, which has
activities in metals, engineering and chemicals, told shareholders at the
annual meeting that group pre-tax earnings fell 28 per cent in the first
half of the year ending September 30.
He said the company did not expect 'to meet its profit targets fully'.
Mr Schimmelbusch, who has pioneered a move by Metallgesellschaft into the
environmental technology field, told the meeting that the international
growth slowdown, lower raw material prices, and the fall in the dollar were
all factors behind the profits fall.
Mannesmann, which has a stake in Britain's TI group, reported 1990 group net
profits of DM464m (Dollars 269.7), down from DM505m in 1989. This
represented a lower figure than indicated in February, when the company
expected to match 1989 results.
Mannesmann said it was proposing a DM9 dividend for 1990, unchanged from the
1989 payout made up of a DM8 dividend with a DM1 bonus.
Operating profits last year fell slightly to DM1bn from DM1.05bn in 1989.
Mannesmann parent company net profits rose to DM355m from DM287m.
</TEXT>
