FT  09 MAY 91 / International Company News: Woolworth tumbles to Dollars 13m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WOOLWORTH, the large US retailing group whose interests range from Woolco
department stores to Susie's fashion shops and various shoe chains,
yesterday reported a slump in first-quarter profits, at Dollars 13m after
tax.
This compares with Dollars 38m in the same period a year earlier.
Helped by favourable exchange rate comparisons, sales advanced very modestly
to Dollars 2.13bn, against Dollars 2.06bn. Within this overall figure,
speciality stores saw a 6.3 per cent sales improvement, but general
merchandise remained unchanged.
Had 1991 revenues been translated at 1990 foreign exchange rates, the
overall increase would have been reduced to less than 1 per cent.
On the stock market, which was prepared for drab first-half performance in
1991, the shares eased by Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 30 1/8 yesterday.
Woolworth attributed the profits fall to recessionary conditions in North
America and to the goods and service tax which took effect in Canada on
January 1.
It said that its Canadian operations had also been hit by the recent court
ruling insisting on Sunday closing in Ontario, home of about 40 per cent of
Woolworth's Canadian stores.
Neither was the company optimistic about an early improvement in the trading
environment: 'Adverse economic conditions continue to negatively impact
consumer spending in the US, Canada and Australia and the consensus view is
that economic recovery will not commence until the latter part of 1991',
said Mr Harold Sells, chairman.
Total operating profits in the first quarter, ahead of corporate expenses,
almost halved from Dollars 91m to Dollars 49m.
Domestic operations saw their contribution slip from Dollars 73m to Dollars
53m, while foreign operations plunged from an Dollars 18m profit to a
Dollars 4m loss.
Woolworth said the 'strong operating profit gains' of its German subsidiary
were offset by the poor performance of the Canadian business.
</TEXT>
