<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / International Company News: San Paolo buys Banesto
subsidiary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ITALY'S INSTITUTO Bancario San Paolo Di Torino is due to sign a letter of
intent today with Banco Espanol de Credito (Banesto) to acquire the Spanish
bank's Barcelona-based subsidiary Banc Catala de Credit, which has 106
branches in north-east Spain.
The acquisition follows the purchase by Credit Lyonnais of Banco Jover, a
subsidiary of Spain's Banco de Santander, also based in Barcelona. The deal
underlines growing foreign interest in the prosperous Catalonia region.
Banc Catala, with assets of Pta152bn (Dollars 1.4bn), is the result of a
merger, organised by Banesto, of two small lossmaking local banks. Nursed
back to financial health two years ago, it increased net profits by 97 per
cent last year, to just over Pta1bn.
The decision to sell Banc Catala confirms a shift of opinion by Banesto's
chairman, Mr Mario Conde, once a staunch opponent of foreign acquisitions of
domestic bank networks.
San Paolo's move into Spain follows last year's purchase of a 35 per cent
stake in the small Banca Abel Matutes family bank in the Balearic Islands.
</TEXT>
