<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Trusthouse name to be shed in THF revamp -
Founder's son, Rocco Forte, denies that egotism lies behind return to family
name
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID CHURCHILL, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ROCCO Forte, chief executive of Trusthouse Forte, confirmed yesterday
that the company planned to drop the Trusthouse part of its name and - once
ratified by shareholders - would in future simply be known as Forte.
The move is part of a Pounds 15m revamp of THF's 343-strong UK and
continental Europe hotel chain aimed at creating several distinct brand
identities for its hotels, most of which will carry the Forte name as part
of their branding.
The decision to drop the Trusthouse part of the corporate name represents a
final victory for the Forte family after the acrimonious merger in June 1970
of Trust Houses, a chain of traditional inns, and the Forte hotel chain.
For several years after the merger the clash of cultures between the
established Trust House management - headed by Lord Crowther and Mr Michael
Pickard - and the aggressive style of Lord Forte created tension between the
two camps of what had initially been described as a 'friendly' merger.
Eventually Lord Forte was successful, ousting both Lord Crowther and Mr
Pickard and then building up Britain's biggest hotel chain over the next two
decades.
Lord Forte, in his autobiography, said of the boardroom battles: 'I do not
want to blame any one individual for wrecking what began so promisingly: the
truth is that there were deep differences of management philosophy and
style, exacerbated by incompatibilities of temperament.'
Yesterday Mr Rocco Forte, Lord Forte's son, insisted that the decision to
drop the Trusthouse part of the name was taken after considerable research
which showed that Forte had the widest marketing appeal both in the UK and
overseas.
He dismissed suggestions that it was egoistical of the company to carry the
Forte family name on all its hotels. 'It was a decision of the board and in
the company's best interests,' he maintained. 'In some ways I am sorry that
we are 'losing' it as a family, because now it will be the corporate
identity rather than a personal one.'
Mr Forte also denied that the name change contravened the agreement made
with Trust Houses at the time of the merger: this had recently been
suggested by Mr Pickard.
'I don't think Mr Pickard's views are valid nearly 20 years after he left
the company,' Mr Forte averred.
He said that the decision to re-brand the company had been planned for the
past two years. In spite of difficult trading conditions in the first few
months of 1991 - THF's pre-tax profits for the 12 months to January 31 fell
27 per cent to Pounds 190m - he believed it was the right time to press
ahead with the changes.
The Pounds 15m cost of the revamp would be spread over two years, he added.
The fee for Wolff Olins, the design company involved, was put at less than
Pounds 1m of the total cost.
Under the re-branding, THF's hotels would be divided into several
categories. These covered: Forte Travelodges, a roadside budget chain; Forte
Posthouses, bringing together three-star properties, some of which presently
trade under the Post House and Crest names; Forte Crest, a four-star
business hotel operation; Forte Heritage, which includes traditional country
house hotels; and Forte Grand, the five-star international hotels such as
the Waldorf in London.
THF's luxury hotels, such as the Hyde Park Hotel in London and the Georges V
in Paris, would still be known by their existing names and the Forte brand
would only be discreetly mentioned.
About 32 existing hotels which do not fit into these categories are to be
sold. THF hopes to raise Pounds 100m.
The City generally welcomed the changes yesterday and marked the shares 1p
higher at 275p.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 23
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-970</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEIBNAB1FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910509
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Tate &amp; Lyle will not pay over ADollars 4.10
per share for Bundaberg
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TATE &amp; LYLE will not pay more than ADollars 4.10 per share for Bundaberg
Sugar, the Queensland sugar miller and refiner, Mr Neil Shaw, chairman of
the world's largest sweeteners group said yesterday.
The ADollars 321m (Pounds 146.18m) offer will be extended shortly to allow
the Australian Foreign Investment Board time to decide on whether to let the
deal proceed, Mr Shaw said.
Tate and Lyle needs 90 per cent of shareholder acceptance and is facing
stiff opposition from Bundaberg.
If the deal goes through it is likely to have a mildly dilutive effect on
Tate &amp; Lyle's earnings in 1992, given the low level of world sugar prices.
But after a six-month period in which Tate &amp; Lyle has shown its resilience
as others have felt the heat of recession, Bundaberg is one of the few areas
where the group appears vulnerable in the short term, notwithstanding its
longer term benefits.
Staley, the US cereals sweetener, mildly disappointed in the six months to
March 1991 with flat profits in dollar terms.
This softness could persist in the second half, primarily because drink
bottlers have reported a slow start and are likely to keep the price
pressure on sweetener suppliers.
Although Tate &amp; Lyle insists that room remains for profits growth from
further squeezing of costs, there are limits to the benefit this year.
Brokers therefore forecast pre-tax profits of Pounds 230m for the full year,
which would give earnings of 33.2p and a prospective multiple of over 11.
Longer term, Tate &amp; Lyle can look forward to high margin profits on
Sucralose, its high-intensity sweetener which it hopes to begin selling in
Canada later this year.
In the US, Monsanto's Nutrasweet is almost certain to have to relinquish
some of its 95 per cent market share if and when the US Food and Drug
Administration approves Sucralose.
In 1992, Tate &amp; Lyle will also benefit substantially from a stronger dollar
and could enjoy pre-tax profits of Pounds 282m. This would give a
prospective multiple of a little over 9, which leaves scope for further
growth in the share price, even though it has risen Pounds 1 in the last
four months.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 23 Photograph Neil Shaw, extending ADollars 321m offer to give
authorities time to decide on fate of deal (Omitted).
</PAGE>
