<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Tepid response to ASB plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK'S top finance directors are lukewarm about the Accounting Standards
Board's proposals for a radical restructuring of company profit and loss
accounts.
Last month the ASB released draft guidelines which proposed that companies
should give a detailed breakdown of the sources of income and expenditure
and publish a prominent statement showing the movement of reserves.
The rules also envisage a tightening up of the distinction between
extraordinary and exceptional items and would require companies to publish
details of discretionary expenditure such as advertising.
The technical committee of the 100 Group of senior UK finance directors met
earlier this week to consider its response to the proposals and concluded
that the document had significant shortcomings.
Mr Nigel Stapleton, chairman of the committee and finance director of Reed
International, was yesterday at pains to say that finance directors were
broadly behind the ASB in its attempts to reform UK financial reporting.
However, he indicated that the committee was worried about the complexity of
the revised profit and loss account - it would have eight columns of figures
 -and had doubts about the principle of disclosing discretionary
expenditure.
Mr Stapleton said that the committee supported the principle of greater
disclosure which lay behind the proposals which would require companies to
show details of income and expenditure from continuing businesses, companies
acquired during the year and discontinued businesses.
But he hoped that the rules would eventually take account of 'materiality',
in other words the scale of the figures in relation to the size of the group
as a whole.
He said the committee was wholly behind the proposed requirement to publish
a prominent statement of movements on reserves. Moreover, it welcomed the
proposed tightening up of the rules on extraordinary and exceptional items.
The draft rules were issued for a brief consultation period which ended on
Tuesday. In due course the ASB will issue a formal Exposure Draft which will
ultimately become a formal Financial Reporting Standard.
Prof David Tweedie, ASB chairman, said earlier this week that so far the
response to the draft rules had been broadly favourable.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
