<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Problem solved for French group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ELF Aquitaine's acquisition of Occidental's North Sea assets neatly solves a
financial problem for the French state-controlled group.
Elf officials are delighted at being able to pay for part of the purchase
with some of the French company's 25 per cent shareholding in Enterprise
Oil, Britain's largest independent oil company.
This allows the French oil group to transform what had become a purely
financial investment into an asset of real industrial value, say Elf
officials.
The group denies that it was influenced by the UK government's hardened
stance against acquisitions by foreign state-controlled companies. Last
July, Mr Peter Lilley, the UK Trade and Industry Secretary, announced that
he would scrutinise all such acquisitions - a policy designed to 'curb
nationalisations by the back door'.
Elf has always argued that its investment in Enterprise was purely financial
and that it had no desire to seize control.
Yet a more stringent UK mergers policy had clearly limited Elf's room for
manoeuvre. Only last week, Britain's Monopolies and Mergers Commission gave
Elf clearance to take over the UK refinery and petrol station business of
Amoco, the big US oil group.
It was the latest of four decisions which ran contrary to the UK
government's attempt to curb such takeovers and, as such, a setback for the
Department of Trade and Industry. Elf officials welcomed the victory, but
stressed that they were keen to avoid a repetition of the months they had to
spend on defending their case at the commission.
</TEXT>
