<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / The Lex Column: UK profits
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
With the spring reporting season just starting, the market's fit of caution
is timely. Current theories about profit recovery now face their first test
 -not how strong the recovery will be, but how deep a hole it will be
filling.
The CBI profit expectations survey is routinely over-optimistic, but its
timing is pretty reliable, forecasting upturns about a year before the
event. The last CBI survey projected a decisive turning point, which can
therefore be expected in the first or second quarter of 1992. How big?
Goldman Sachs can hardly be called pessimistic - it looks for a 15-20 per
cent bounce back next year, with output up and employment down; but it
stresses that the coming quarter may be worse than expected, just as the
first quarter was.
The better the inflation news, the worse the message about margins. Treasury
officials, who designed current policy to squeeze inflation via margins,
think that any hope of profit recovery this year is moonshine, and even a
standstill stretching it. Since this would come after a 10 per cent drop in
1990, Goldman's three-year forecast for an average nominal rise of 3 per
cent real looks far from gloomy.
But at that, it would take a further strong recovery in 1993 to get real
profits back to their 1989 starting point. The market may find this prospect
a little unexciting, unless it is banking on dollar miracles.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
