<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Book Review: Sleight of hand over scientific method
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX WILKINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DISAPPEARING THROUGH THE SKYLIGHT
By OB Hardison Jr
Penguin, Pounds 9.99, 389 pages
Modern man's yearning to understand the significance of science is attested
by a pile of recent popular works, but even the best requires study. How
convenient if it could be done in a single big bang, unifying all
discoveries from chromosomes to cosmology into the framework of what the
average arts graduate learned at school.
Enter O B Hardison Jr, the Mephistopheles of the computer age. He reveals
Everything in 400 pages, then causes it to vanish, leaving hardly a trace
behind, except a pleasant feeling of superiority and some rave notices in
the US and last year's Los Angeles Times Book Prize.
Hardison, an expert on culture and a professor at Georgetown University,
Washington, until his death last summer, certainly offers the broad view and
a long bibliography. His thesis is that modern technology overwhelmed
traditional cultures in a kind of game of progressive abstraction that
caused them to 'disappear'. So each of his five sections is subtitled 'the
Disappearance of . . .Nature, History, Language, Art and Man', respectively.
This may be a complicated joke because the 'Man' section is about artificial
intelligence, for example. Some of it is nonsense, Yet even at his most
preposterous, Hardison sounds as if he might possibly be on to something.
Take, for example, the conclusion of his first section: 'If science is a
human creation, we have caught the mind in the very act of swallowing up the
world, which is another way of saying that we have witnessed nature in the
process of disappearing.' Is this profundity, semantic froth, or just a cry
of pain?
Hardison compares the beauty of Charles Darwin's prose in The Origin of the
Species with the mathematics which D'Arcy Thompson, the Cambridge zoologist,
used to describe the living world in 1917. Then he proceeds to the computer
mathematics of Benoit Mandelbrot, who used computers in the 1960s to develop
fractal geometry, a formalism for describing natural shapes such as
coastlines.
son thinks Darwin was imprisoned in the confusions of a 'mythic' view of
nature, to which he is said to have attributed 'human motives'; his ideas
were thus flawed by the 'logical nonsense' of his supposed belief that the
survival of the fittest was 'tragic' (because of the extinction of the
rest). Then came Thompson ('everything in biology that Darwin was not') and,
later, Mandelbrot, to liberate mankind into the world of numerical
abstraction.
The fact that Hardison misunderstood and misrepresented Darwin, that his
hero, D'Arcy Thompson, though respected by academics, no longer rates a
mention in the Encyclopaedia Britannica, and that Mandelbrot knew possibly
even less biology than Hardison, need not detain us. A man who can say that
the Ford Fiesta car 'appears to have sunk without trace' demands indulgence.
Perhaps he read The Origin in a hurry.
It is harder to forgive him for speculating whether Johannes Kepler, the
16th-century astronomer, would have abandoned his preconceived theory of the
solar system if observations had conflicted with it. Kepler stands - with
Darwin - among the giants of the scientific tradition precisely because he
did abandon the theory which everyone then believed in. He discovered with
much intellectual pain and prodigious analysis of Tycho Brahe's stellar
observations that the planets do not move in ordered circles, inscribed on
geometrical solids, as the ancients believed. Kepler deduced that they trace
less godlike elliptical orbits, a fact which helped Isaac Newton to
formulate the laws of motion and gravity.
Yet Hardison is too intelligent to be hissed quite off the stage. The
advance of scientific rationalism has left perplexing furrows in
20th-century culture. As he says: 'To many people, the world of quarks and
black holes is an affront. Humanity seems to have leaked out of it.' He is
at his best describing this loss of vital fluid, for example in modern and
post-modern architecture. This section is full of fun and insights. So who
cares if it is sound? His celebration of the poetry of nonsense and the
reduction of language to incantation or pattern is also instructive -
provided one ignores the dismissal of Eliot, Pound and Yeats as 'modernist'
(ie: tied to the past).
Then his survey of computer brainpower is racy and comprehensive, even
though he sows confusion about Alan Turing's test for whether a machine is
truly 'intelligent'. He suggests wrongly that Joseph Weizenbaum's famous
psychoanalytic programme, ELIZA, passed this intelligence test 'for some
users' back in 1963. But, as Weizenbaum explained in his powerful book,
Computer Power and Human Reason, ELIZA was as much a fraud as Coppelia
Hardison means the programme sort of seemed a bit intelligent. But where
does that leave his apocalyptic vision of a world dominated by machines, in
which 'silicon life will be immortal . . .for silicon beings, 100,000 light
years will be as a day's journey . . '?
The danger of this readable and provocative book is that it will be taken as
a bona fide exposition of scientific thought, even as a bridge between the
two cultures. But although Hardison is awed by science, he shows little
understanding of its method, preferring metaphors, dextrous conceits and,
sometimes, innuendo or sleight of hand. So, he perversely analyses passages
from Darwin as if he were a flawed nature poet, rather than a theorist who
changed the history of ideas. He fails to see how theories which seemed at
first repugnant to common sense stripped away the illusions of mankind. Nor
does he understand the central source of science's power and authority:
successful prediction. Caveat Emptor]
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
