<TEXT>
Sir, Observer's 'Head Count' article (May 3) reminds me of the following
story:
A man in need of a brain transplant goes to the surgeon for a consultation.
The surgeon advises him that he can have a surveyor's brain for Pounds
15,000, a lawyer's brain for Pounds 30,000 or, best of all, an economist's
brain for Pounds 60,000.
'Pounds 60,000] Why so much?' asks the patient.
'Well,' says the surgeon, 'an economist's brain is as good as new - it's
never been used.'
