<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Leading Article: Labour takes the next step
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
LAST night's speech by the shadow chancellor John Smith to the Royal
Institute of Public Administration marks the first formal endorsement of the
government's reforms of the Civil Service by a senior member of the shadow
cabinet. It thus offers assurance that the creation of agencies to deliver
government services will survive beyond a change of government, a welcome
measure of bipartisan support for reforms designed to increase the quality
of those services while strengthening financial and managerial controls.
In the adversarial atmosphere of British politics, such cross-party support
for institutional reform has become rare enough to merit comment in its own
right. It would be advantageous were similar consensus to be achieved in
other important spheres of public life, such as pensions, education and
health care (or, for that matter, local government finance). Without such
agreement, reforms must be implemented against the opposition of entrenched
interests which look to a change of government to reinstate the status quo.
All too often, whatever success is achieved will be unravelled in future
years.
For the Civil Service reforms, at any rate, the threat of such a reversal
may now be lifted. Mr Smith not only welcomed the reforms set out by Sir
Robin Ibbs in the Next Steps report of 1988; he positively endorsed their
aims as central to Labour's objectives for the public sector. Such
criticisms as he made were not of principles, but of implementation - for
example, the government's alleged failure to carry civil servants and their
unions with it.
Service delivery
The Next Steps report sought to separate the delivery of government services
from policy-making by creating separate agencies to provide specific
services. Agency managers focus on service delivery, whether it be the
testing of heavy goods vehicles, the provision of company information or the
payment of benefits. Service targets are set for a three-year period, agreed
between the agency and its sponsoring department in a framework document
which also specifies the powers devolved on questions such as personnel
management. Agency chief executives are accountable to their sponsoring
department and to parliament for operational matters, a process which seems
to have worked well so far.
Mission statements
The launch of the first agencies was buttressed by much private-sector
paraphernalia - corporate identities, glossy annual reports and impressive
mission statements. More substantially, almost all the first tranche of
agencies launched customer service surveys, leading to improved service
quality and new - usually profitable - services. These early initiatives
indicate that the Next Steps approach has reinvigorated managers and staff
and begun to create more responsive and consumer-friendly organisations.
Agency staff remain civil servants, covered by national pay agreements,
terms and conditions. There is some freedom to introduce employment changes
where these would be more suited to the nature of the work; only one agency
 -HMSO - has used this freedom to create its own pay structure, though
several have introduced staff bonus schemes to encourage greater efficiency.
As the first agencies renegotiate their framework documents this summer,
managers will seek and should be granted greater powers to manage, further
untying themselves from the dead hand of central control.
In short, some progress has been achieved in creating free-standing,
user-oriented organisations, but much of the potential is still to be
realised - which is why Mr Smith's endorsement of Next Steps is significant.
Managers implementing the agency programme can now adopt a longer-term
perspective, secure in the knowledge that it will not be blown off course by
a change of government. While there is much further to go in the evolution
of Next Steps, the principle that government services are best delivered by
dedicated agencies at arm's length from the policy-making process is here to
stay. Its recognition is long overdue.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 18
</PAGE>
