<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Arts: The Women of Troy - Belgrade Studio, Coventry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ST GEORGE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Euripides' The Women of Troy was first acted in 415 BC, immediately after
the Greeks had sacked Melos, and while they prepared for the Sicilian
campaign. Its anti-war ethic bears the imprint of its origins; but it is as
relevant now as it was during the Peleponnesian War. For this is a play
about the aftermath of war: its survivors,
refugees, and criminals. The central debate of the play is simple: is it
better to
survive to face fresh horrors, or better to have died in the war?
The Greek levelling of Troy provides the background to the action which,
like the current scenes from Zakho or Amadiyah, is unbearable misery.
Aristotle believed
that tragedy was a work-out for the emotions, exercising the extremes we
would not normally find in ourselves; The Women of Troy certainly depends on
the pity of others' plight, and fear at their
grief.
The Greeks saw tragedies in groups of three, and appended a satyr-play to
lighten the proceedings. But here, the action is all the more concentrated
for being singular. The central figure is Hecuba, mother of Hector and wife
of Priam. She hears that her sons are dead; her daughter, Cassandra,
enslaved; her son's wife, Andromache, abducted; and her grandson, Astyanax,
thrown off the ramparts. She then has the chance to indict Helen, the cause
of all the suffering, while a
vacillating Menelaus (Helen's first husband) looks on. The play ends as Troy
burns and Hecubais taken off to Odysseus' ship.
Euripides adds his own sharp ironies: each crop of horrors is prefaced by a
sentiment of relative content: 'There is no agony we don't already feel, no
abyss of pain we can discover.' He charts the reaction of victims who have
to give more for less and less. When Edward Bond wrote his version, The
Woman (1978), he followed the Euripidean logic that each new loss should be
worse than the last. The Women of Troy pitches headlong into misery.
The physical brutalities happen off-stage, but are all meticulously
delivered by messengers and chorus. This keeps the mind full of horrors, and
lets the eye focus on the issues embodied in the actors on stage. Greek
tragedies have no knowledge of 20th-century psychology: here, characters
emerge from the plot.
A tendency to over-naturalism nags at an otherwise exemplary production at
the Belgrade Studio. The cast of six is uniformly excellent; Margaret
Robertson (Hecuba), Alison Skilbeck (Andromache) and David Hobbs (Poseidon,
Menelaus) in particular find extraordinary range and power. And if Richard
Osborne's direction is somewhat anxious, the
play's issues are never obscured.
But this is a fine account of the play which remains current. Hecuba asks
the question: 'How can I suffer this and learn to bear it?' in face of new
disasters she has not yet met. Meanwhile, on the Turkish border at Cukurca
just north of Amadiyah, the arriving Kurdish refugees  - survivors of cold
and hunger - face an outbreak of cholera.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-997</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEIBNABAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910509
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Arts: The Plough and the Stars - Young Vic
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
With yet another initiative to solve the Irish Problem currently under way,
this revival of Sean O'Casey's The Plough and the Stars is a timely reminder
of how old and intractable the Troubles are. And how peripheral to the real
lives of the people.
This is no idealistic view of the 1916 Easter Rebellion. The heroes are not
the patriots of the Irish Citizen Army, urged by stirring nationalistic
rhetoric to 'Welcome war like the Angel of God', but the working class poor
of the Dublin tenement who use the mayhem to loot the shops, but who rally
automatically when the conflict enters their home.
O'Casey is magnificent at toying with the emotions of the audience. The
doomed sacrifice of Jack Clitheroe (Breffni McKenna), who puts loyalty to
the Cause before his young wife because he is 'afraid to be called afraid',
hardly touches us.
It is the Empire loving Bessie Burgess (Judi Dench), who intersperses
choruses of 'Rule Britannia' with abuse of the Fenians, who displays the
truer loyalty because her commitment to the tenement is unthinking and
spontaneous. The young communist Covey lives through slogans while the
drunken carpenter Fluther acts courageously without the burden of ideals.
What gives this good old fashioned four-act tragedy enduring life is
O'Casey's ability to throw in everything and lose little. This is how life
felt in Dublin during that fateful weekend. In Sam Mendes' production the
Rebellion is ominously close in the ratatat of machine guns and the boom of
cannons but it never replaces the petty bickerings of the tenants, the
marital strains, the endemic sickness, the mundane poverty of the Dubliners,
seeking small consolations in the liquor and the local tart.
In a wrenching moment Nora Clitheroe (Niamh Cusack) temporarily wins back
Jack's attention and seduces him into singing her a love song. And the
second act, when the gentle shadow boxing of the locals in the pub is
interrupted by the fiery speeches heard at the political rally outside,
beautifully puts people before patriotism.
Cramming a cast of 15 and four sets on to a tiny acting area creates
problems (and makes for some intriguingly public set changes), and the
strongly Irish cast is slow to warm to its task. But once the rhythm is
caught, discreetly orchestrated by Judi Dench as the provoking widow, and
John Rogan, all angles and itches as the nostalgic Fenian, the younger
actors warm to their work. Niamh Cusack seizes her big speech on cowardice
while the abashed men stand like sentries on the four corners of the stage
awaiting the arrival of the inevitable catafalque.
Life goes on, says O'Casey. Men while away the time playing cards alongside
the coffin of the young consumptive; the English squaddies drink up the hot
tea abandoned in the deserted flat. There is laughter here as well as
constant tragedy. Mendes' production remains too earth bound and tentative
to do full justice to the eternal truths but it is a brave stab at a great
play.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17 Photograph Niamh Cusack (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
