<PROFILE>_AN-BEIBNAA8FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910509
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Arts: Hanover Band - Queen Elizabeth Hall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD FAIRMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Even in Salzburg the advance of period performance practice is proving
inexorable. It has been the custom in the city since the 1930s to give an
annual performance of Mozart's C Minor Mass in St Peter's and the local
press was apparently struck by the clarity and expressiveness that John
Eliot Gardiner and the Monteverdi Choir brought to the same music in
comparison when they turned up with it earlier this year.
In London it is almost de rigeur to perform this work on period instruments
now. Gardiner himself gave a single performance of it at the start of the
year, prior to setting out for Salzburg, and he was followed on Tuesday by
Roy Goodman and the Hanover Band. It would be interesting to know what
Salzburg thinks of them, as their music-making has even less inclination to
make Mozart sound like he traditionally used to.
The awkwardnesses of using period instruments were easy to hear. Wind
intonation was often sour; the orchestral balance was as it comes. Goodman
does not often intervene to right inequalities or impose his own ideas. In
some ways a less obviously 'interpreted' approach to 18th-century music like
this is welcome; but when Gardiner conducted the Mass, it was clear that we
were in the presence of a blinding masterpiece, and here it was not.
The vocal parts, solo and choral, were very respectably taken. In the
'Domine Deus' there were two well-contrasted sopranos, Lynne Dawson shining
bright, Anne Dawson more mature and rounded of voice. The 'Et incarnatus',
taken by the former, went with no lingering or sentimentality (and no
trills). The Hanover Band Chorus showed itself no less to be a useful small
choir. But the performance was rarely moving in the way that Gardiner's had
been.
In the first half Goodman and the orchestra warmed up on Haydn's Symphony No
102, a taster of the complete cycle of Haydn symphonies that they are
recording for Hyperion. Again there were doubtful moments of balance, when
the strings were lost from view, but the performance had vitality and fun.
The minuet was taken at Czerny's recommended metronome marking, which shows
that Beethoven is not the only one to have handed down to us speeds long
deemed to be impossibly fast.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1000</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEIBNAA7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910509
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Arts: Hobson's Choice - Sadler's Wells
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLEMENT CRISP
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Birmingham Royal Ballet is making a return to its erstwhile nursery in
Rosebery Avenue for the next two weeks. We shall be seeing new works from
young choreographers - as we so happily have for the past 45 years with this
company - and Tuesday night's showing of Hobson's Choice reasserted yet
again the vital creative identity of the troupe. I am not a devotee of the
piece, finding its unrelenting joviality altogether too much, but it is a
product of the company's traditions, an undoubted success with the public,
and it is performed with quite exceptional spirit and finesse.
David Bintley's realisation of Harold Brighouse's play is affectionate,
rather sentimental, and serves as excuse for every sort of theatrical trick.
What sustains it in the theatre are the ebullient interpretations it has
inspired from its cast, and the dancers' vivid response to every opportunity
for fun. The humour is, shall we say, broad; it is the especial grace of the
Birmingham artists that they never over-step the mark between wit and
slapstick. Timing is impeccable, comedy has been brightly polished, so that
Stephen Wicks as a gormless suitor armed with flowers can extract every last
joke without coarseness, while the drunken Hobson's progress up a flight of
stairs (a series of rushes and teeterings that demand impeccable planning)
is done with blithe skill by Desmond Kelly.
Casting on Tuesday night was the original, with the central trio of Karen
Donovan as Maggie, Desmond Kelly as her father, Michael O'Hare as Will
Mossop. Their roles are plainly very real to them, as they splendidly are to
us, and - whatever reservations one may have about the piece - it is
heart-lifting to see an ensemble as secure in understanding, alert in
response, in communication of feeling and step. This is true of every member
of the cast; the company playing has a warmth and a generosity that have
been a characteristic of the troupe since it was a group of Miss de Valois'
new young dancers who trod this same stage in 1946.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
