<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Technology: The verdict on Alvey's worth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When the Pounds 350m Alvey research programme in information technology was
launched with strong support from the British government in 1983, it was
billed as the answer to the UK electronics industry's flagging international
competitiveness.
Yet four years after the programme ended, the UK electronics industry's
position is worse than ever. Its market share has declined further - even at
home - the national IT deficit has grown and British companies have
withdrawn from important technologies and product markets.
So was Alvey, which received Pounds 200m in government subsidies and
directly involved about 5,000 people, a waste of time and money? Or did the
programme yield some benefits which will prove their worth over the longer
term?
A detailed evaluation, commissioned by the government and conducted by the
universities of Sussex and Manchester*, concludes that, from a purely
technical standpoint, Alvey chose sensible targets and achieved most of
them.
Substantial progress was made in advancing the frontiers of important
computing technologies, including very large-scale integrated (VLSI)
circuits, software engineering and intelligent knowledge-based systems. The
study argues that the programme also expanded Britain's R&amp;D capacity and
gave a fillip to its research community. But it is more ambiguous about the
importance of collaboration as a stimulus to research.
Only 22 per cent of industrial research teams said they saw Alvey as a way
to form new links with competitors, though 71 per cent of those who did
planned to continue working with partners after the programme ended.
There is also more than a hint that government subsidies were an influential
factor for some industrial participants. The study finds that, left to
themselves, some companies would simply have axed research work in several
technologies which Alvey was intended to promote.
The study argues that it was probably unrealistic to expect a long-term
research programme to produce a decisive short-term improvement in industry
performance. It also says Alvey would have benefitted from the involvement
of IT users, which would have made it more market-oriented.
However, the authors criticise industry for not seizing commercial
opportunities more aggressively. They say that only 17 per cent of the
industry teams involved said the results were regularly used by their
companies to make marketable products - a proportion the study calls
'disappointing'.
A third of Alvey researchers said their employers showed little interest in
the programme. Many found it hard to get money from their companies to
exploit their research commercially, while the companies lacked the
production skills to apply it properly.
Though companies which kept R&amp;D separated from production achieved the best
technical results in Alvey, the research was exploited most effectively in
the market by those which integrated R&amp;D closely with senior management
functions.
Factors over which industry had little or no control were also to blame for
the poor take-up of Alvey technology - in particular a chronic shortage of
well-educated staff and a shortage of 'patient' capital to back long-term
investment.
The authors suggest that the takeover by the UK's General Electric Company
of the semiconductor interests of Plessey and Ferranti could provide a base
from which UK industry could use Alvey research to attack world markets.
However, the study argues that Japanese and US companies are far better
equipped to put collaborative research to profitable use. Alvey's most
enduring economic contribution, it concludes, may be to enhance the UK's
ability to attract direct investments by those companies.
* Evaluation of the Alvey Programme. Science Policy Research Unit,
University of Sussex, and Programme of Policy Research in Engineering
Science and Technology, University of Manchester. HMSO.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 16
