<DATE>910509
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Business Law: Self-regulation under threat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JEFFREY JOWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A GREAT DEAL of concern is being expressed about the effects of the European
Commission's forthcoming company law directive on takeovers, foreshadowed in
its draft 13th directive.
The fear is that the directive will force the UK's own self-regulatory Panel
on Takeovers and Mergers to be formally established by statute, which would
in turn threaten the informality, flexibility and speed which are the
panel's hallmarks.
The panel's supporters have raised the spectre of a rigid statutory scheme
administered by non-expert bureaucrats causing a rash of tactical litigation
and a rush for judicial review - even during the course of a takeover bid.
A recent study by the David Hume Institute favours the present largely
unregulated activities of the panel and compares its actions to that of a
football referee, acting to control a 'fast-moving, frequently
unpredictable, competitive event', where an authoritative decision needs to
be made quickly, and without the impediment of formality and appeal to the
courts.
The panel needs to act swiftly, and in practice operates with commendable
efficiency. However, its decisions are much freer of constraint than those
of any footfall referee. It makes the laws it interprets, it waives its own
laws, and it operates virtually free of public scrutiny. By comparison, the
football referee is a model of procedural propriety.
The panel has already been the subject of judicial review, first in the 1987
Datafin case. Despite its lack of 'visible means of legal support', the
Master of the Rolls described the panel as possessing 'a giant's strength'
and considered it amenable to judicial review because it exercises 'immense
power' of a public nature.
However, it was not only the panel's strength and power that convinced the
Court of Appeal to subject it to judicial review. It was also the fact that
the panel violated accepted norms of separation of powers being, as
described in a later case, 'part legislator, part court of interpretation,
part consultant, part referee, part disciplinary body'.
Listening to the pleas of the panel's supporters for freedom from legal
control brings to mind the time when virtually all UK administrative
tribunals and inquiries evaded legality on the ground that their place was
in the realm of 'administration' rather than 'justice'.
The main fear of the panel's supporters is that the implementation of the
directive through statutory enactment will encourage legal challenge to the
panel's decisions during the course of takeover bids.
Legal intervention, however, is unlikely to become more frequent simply
because the panel has statutory status. As has been made clear in countless
cases, judicial review never permits the courts to interfere with the
'merits' of a case.
No court will lightly upset the panel's opinion that the parties have or
have not been acting 'in concert', or that a party has been taking action to
obstruct a bid in breach of the City code on takeovers and mergers. These
are essentially matters of 'fact and degree' for the panel.
The concern is that the panel will be subject to judicial review for not
following the letter of the directive. The panel and its supporters cherish
its privilege of eschewing the literal interpretation of its rules, and
giving precedence to its set of principles.
It is therefore free to waive a rule in favour of a principle, to interpret
a practice that is not covered by a rule in the light of a principle, and
speedily to enact new rules to cover new situations (such as management
buy-outs).
The panel's mix of rule and discretion displays a commendable flexibility
and a willingness to consider each case on its individual merit. But the
draft directive also establishes a combination of principles and rules, and
permits reasoned derogation from a number of its rules.
The UK statute could easily instruct the new principles to prevail over the
rules. In any event, judges in the UK are these days perfectly capable of
interpreting statutes 'purposively'. They have, in past cases, shown
themselves to be sufficiently aware of administrative realities to recognise
that laws may be enforced selectively, and that extra-statutory concessions
are a fact of regulatory life.
When the Court of Appeal held that the panel's decisions were subject to
judicial review, the Master of the Rolls had the American experience very
much in mind when he promised that the relationship between the panel and
the court should be 'historic rather than contemporaneous'.
Thus panel decisions, if held unlawful in the future, would not be quashed
but only admonished by way of a declaratory judgment with prospective effect
(although it was subsequently made clear that in the case of decisions
leading to disciplinary action the court would intervene to protect the
parties from the 'abuse of power').
With or without the directive, it is going to be hard for the courts to
continue defending a secure zone of immunity around the panel - an immunity
which could not be justified in the case of other bodies performing public
functions.
Normally in UK law a remedy should be provided where a right or breach of
duty has been found. A blanket immunity from remedy in practice removes any
incentive to litigation, thus making the opportunity of judicial review in
effect a dead letter.
Nevertheless, there is a key reason why the fear of 'American style'
obstructive litigation is unfounded: the UK procedure for judicial review
(the application for judicial review) has a built-in filtering system.
Unlike US procedure, and unlike private-law procedure in this country, the
application for judicial review is divided into two stages. At the first
stage the decision is taken to grant 'leave' to apply. This stage is
purpose-built to halt obstructive litigation in its tracks, and would mean
that few unmeritorious cases would easily reach the second stage of a full
hearing.
Even in the absence of enforced change from the directive, a procedural
audit of the Takeover Panel would find much wanting in comparison with other
bodies performing public functions.
Its required consultative procedures when rules are amended are minimal.
Its composition looks to an outsider excessively biased towards those with a
direct financial interest in creating more takeover activity. (No doubt the
panel and the executive are scrupulously fair in practice but, as it is
said, justice must not only be done but also be seen to be done.)
Inter partes hearings in a contested matter are very much the exception  -
even though these are often the best way of arriving at the truth.
Nor does the panel normally allow presentation of a case by a legal
advocate. The courts have blown hot and cold on whether procedural fairness
includes the right to a legal adviser before domestic tribunals, and before
disciplinary tribunals in institutions such as prisons.
Even in those situations, however, the view has now formed that legal
representation is a basic 'civil right' that should not be excluded in all
but the most exceptional situations.
If that is so, why should legal representation not be permitted as of right
before the panel. Or, to put it another way, by what right, and on what
principle, does the panel seek to protect a virtual monopoly of
representation by City financial advisers?
The proposed European directive is unlikely to change the relationship
between the panel and the courts. Yet there seems no reason why the panel
should be exempt from controls on its discretion which are routinely imposed
on other decision-making bodies with far less power.
Nor does there seem any good reason why a somewhat increased measure of
control of the panel's 'giant's strength' should impede the undoubted
efficiency and flexibility for which it is justly renowned.
The author is a barrister, and professor of public law, University College,
London.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1005</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEIBNAA2FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910509
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Management: Tape v tape; Philips v Sony - Recorded music
technology / Michael Skapinker assesses the reception awaiting digital
compact cassettes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
American teenagers spent more on trainers than on music last year. Some
might see this as a comment on the outrageous price of footwear. To Gerry
Wirtz, it is a warning that time is running out for the cassette tape.
Wirtz is a senior product manager at Philips, the Dutch electronics group
which invented the cassette. He says that the traditional audio tape is in
decline.
Some companies, headed by Sony of Japan, have come up with a new technology,
Digital Audio Tape (DAT). Philips has hit back with the Digital Compact
Cassette (DCC). Both offer sound quality as good as that of compact disc.
At first sight, the companies' concern appears unwarranted. The
International Federation of the Phonographic Industry reports that cassette
sales tripled during the 1980s, reaching 1.5bn units sold in 1989.
Wirtz says it is vital, however, to introduce a new recording technology
before the old one reaches its peak. Work on the compact disc began before
sales of vinyl records began their precipitous fall. The development of
digital tape is, if anything, a bit late, he says. There are signs that
sales of traditional cassettes have already begun to slip.
Market research reveals that consumers think of traditional audio cassettes
as being old-fashioned, unreliable and offering poor sound. US youngsters,
Wirtz contends, are as disillusioned with the cassettes as with the music on
them.
A popular digital format is necessary if the demise of the audio cassette is
not to drag the entire Dollars 22bn recording industry into decline.
The proponents of digital audio tape have moved faster than Philips. DAT
machines are already on the market, despite legal objections from the record
industry which feared that people would use them to make crystal clear
pirate tapes. DAT has not, however, made much impression. Philips says this
is not surprising; DAT machines play digital tapes only. Anyone owning one
would have to throw their traditional audio cassettes away.
Wirtz contends that the tape market has to be approached differently.
Cassettes still outsell other musical media by a long way. Despite their
decline, 'the music cassette will be with us beyond the year 2000,' he says.
The problem with the cassette is not that it will stop selling. It will
simply sell more slowly. The trick, Wirtz says, is to come up with a
technology which can attach itself to the cassette market while at the same
time boosting tape sales.
Philips believes the DCC machines will do just that. The main difference
between DCC and DAT players is that the new Philips machines will play both
old-fashioned and digital tapes. Both types of tape can be inserted into the
same slot. (The old style of tape player will not, however, play the new
digital cassettes.) As traditional cassette players wear out, Philips hopes
that new buyers will go for DCC, attracted by the idea that they do not have
to throw their old tapes away.
Philips' prototype of a DCC player will soon be available; it plans to
launch the machines and tapes in April 1992. It has already lined up an
impressive array of music companies to support its technology, including
EMI, Bertelsmann, and PolyGram, a Philips subsidiary. Tandy of the US is
also expected to make the players.
The most impressive backer, however, is Matsushita of Japan, the world's
largest consumer electronics company and Sony's traditional rival. Philips
will not confirm that Matsushita is lending its support, but it is believed
that the Japanese group will be a co-licensor of DCC. Philips and Matsushita
will together sell the right to manufacture DCC to other companies.
Wirtz admits that marketing DCC will be a difficult job. The compact disc,
the other digital recording format on the market, has grown rapidly from
almost nothing in 1983 to worldwide sales of 600m discs in 1989. The CD had
the advantage of offering a sound clearer than anything that music
enthusiasts had heard before. DCC, as a subsequent digital technology, will
not have the same novelty value.
Philips, which invented the CD as well as the audio tape, thought each new
purchaser of a compact disc player would buy eight recordings in the first
year of ownership. Instead, new buyers of CD players bought 16 discs in the
first year.
'We don't expect DCC to be the same as the CD,' Wirtz says. 'It's the second
digital child. With your first child you go nuts. With your second you have
a one-day party and then go back to work. We expect people to buy only three
tapes in the first year they own a DCC player. It will be a massive problem
to keep the cassette market going. To do so with digital cassette we've got
to grow like hell.'
Philips is expected to aim DCC at the portable music market, selling
personal digital stereos and car tape players. Alain Levy, PolyGram's chief
executive, says he would like to give DCC tapes a price mid-way between that
of traditional cassettes and compact discs.
Wirtz, however, says he expects sales of DCC tapes to begin at around the
same level as CDs. DCC players will be sold for between Pounds 300 and
Pounds 500 each.
He showed off the new tapes at a London hotel last month, along with a
provisional version of a DCC player. The sound is as good as that of a
compact disc. Wirtz demonstrated this by playing the same piece of music on
CD and DCC players simultaneously and switching between the two. He then
played a traditional audio cassette on the DCC player, producing a
noticeably fuzzier sound.
The DCC tape looks like a cross between an audio cassette and a floppy disc.
Wirtz claims, however, that it will be far more reliable and durable than an
audio cassette. Licencees will have to follow strict guidelines in the
manufacture of DCC tapes. They will, for example, have to use high quality
plastic which does not melt on the dashboard of a car left in the sun.
But DCC still uses tape, however. Although better protected than in a
traditional audio cassette, it still looks vulnerable to accident or wear
and tear. CDs appear more durable.
Apart from the ability to carry on playing old cassettes, it is difficult to
see what DCC offers that CD does not. Some in the industry say DCC will
benefit from being vibration-resistant and therefore more suitable for use
in cars and personal stereos than compact discs. But the CD has quickly
established itself as a popular device. If DCCs are no cheaper than CDs who
will buy them? The answer, one imagines, is people who want to record from
CDs on to blank DCC tapes - an activity the record industry has never liked.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
