FT  09 MAY 91 / Parliament and Politics: Row over 'shopkeeper' statement -
Monmouth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Roger Evans, the Tory candidate in the Monmouth by-election, yesterday
fuelled the continuing row over two local hospitals possibly opting out to
become self-governing trusts, when he compared not balloting patients about
whether hospitals should opt out with a shopkeeper not balloting his
customers to find out what they wanted to buy, Alison Smith writes.
Asked whether he was saying the NHS was like Tesco supermarkets, he said he
was simply suggesting that the organisation was used by a changing class of
person 'which are patients, in exactly the same way that Tesco has a
different group of people using it each day.'
Mr Gerald Kaufman, the shadow foreign secretary, representing Mr Huw
Edwards, the Labour candidate, at a candidates' meeting in Chepstow, said
government plans were turning the NHS into a 'health supermarket'.
But the other parties criticised Mr Edwards' failure to attend the meeting.
Letters, Page 19
