FT  09 MAY 91 / Manchester shopping development in doubt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FUTURE of Manchester's plans to develop valuable land owned by
Manchester Ship Canal were yesterday thrown into confusion by the
government.
Mr Michael Heseltine, environment secretary, stalled further on planning
permission for the 1m sq ft Trafford shopping and leisure centre at
Dumplington, Greater Manchester. The centre is planned for 300 acres of land
which was at the heart of the bitter takeover battle for Manchester Ship
Canal in 1985-87.
Dumplington is in one corner of the big cross formed where the M63 motorway
bridges the canal. However, the motorway's ability to cope with rising
traffic after 1996 has now been seriously questioned by the Department of
Transport. The DoT says its latest forecasts suggest that the northbound
carriageway of the M63 would have to be widened to four lanes over 1 1/4
miles of Barton Bridge - which carries the motorway over the canal - if
vehicles leaving the centre are to merge safely with traffic on the
motorway.
Mr Heseltine's officials said that was new evidence. Manchester Ship Canal
and rivals bidding to build the regional retail centre on a nearby site now
have 21 days to respond or to ask for a public inquiry to be reopened. The
inquiry sat for five months to February 1988 and recommended Dumplington,
which the government still says is the best site for the centre.
The government has just spent Pounds 24m on widening the bridge.
</TEXT>
