FT  09 MAY 91 / Plan to stop English rivers drying up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A PRIORITY programme to save some of England's most attractive rivers from
drying up was launched yesterday by the National Rivers Authority, the water
industry's environmental regulator, Richard Evans writes.
Over-exploitation by industry, landowners and water companies, together with
a succession of dry winters and hot summers, has led to unacceptably low
flow levels in some of the country's best fishing rivers.
The NRA said yesterday there were no 'quick fix' solutions, and the cost of
reversing the decline might reach Pounds 20m. Among the 20 targeted rives
are the Darent, Pang, Wey and Ver in the Thames region; the upper Waveney,
the Hiz and Slea in East Anglia; the Wharfe in Yorkshire; and the Piddle in
Wessex.
