<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / World Trade News: Bush opens US ports to E Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bush, in a major revision of US policy, yesterday threw open all
US ports to former Soviet satellite nations and declared his intention 'to
stimulate commercial trade between the US and the region'.
Mr Marlin Fitzwater, White House press secretary, said the decision was
another step to ending Cold War restrictions and welcoming eastern Europe
into 'the international community of democratic nations'.
The action had been taken, after an intensive inter-agency review, 'in
recognition of the progress these countries have made toward democracy and
the rule of law'.
The new port policy follows other recent moves to expand US trade with
eastern Europe. Last month, the Bush Administration extended duty-free trade
benefits to Czechoslovakia, Poland, Hungary and Yugoslavia under the US
Generalised System of Preferences (GSP).
The GSP suspends tariffs for certain products as a means of helping
developing countries, and to promote free trade. This year's list gave
benefits covering Dollars 337m (Pounds 198m) in trade, more than half of
which went to east European countries.
The new port policy maintains the same delineation between the Soviet Union
and the eastern Europeans that the Bush Administration has retained on other
trade matters. Export controls, for example, have been liberalised towards
the eastern bloc more than for the Soviet Union, which is denied GSP
benefits.
The new port policy opens all US ports for commercial, cargo, passenger and
fishing vessels from eastern European nations. In the past, access for ships
from Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, Hungary, Poland and Romania was severely
limited. They could not enter 12 'high security' ports at all and they were
required to give two weeks' notice before entering other ports. Albania was
denied entry to all US ports.
Now the six will be required to give only 24 hours' notice for any ports.
Soviet ships must give two day's notice at 49 US ports and two week's notice
at others. Access is totally denied at the 12 high security ports.
The 12 ports now open to the former satellite countries but still closed to
Soviet ships are: Charleston, South Carolina; Hampton Roads, Virginia;
Honolulu, Hawaii; Kings Bay, Georgia; New London, Connecticut; Panama City,
Florida; Pensacola, Florida; Port Canaveral, Florida; Port Hueneme,
California; Port St. Joe, Florida; Portsmouth, New Hampshire, and San Diego,
California.
The Bush Administration last month signed a 'framework' trade agreement with
Bulgaria, which grants most-favoured-nation trading status, entitling it to
the lower tariffs the US offers most of its trading partners.
Bulgaria, in turn, guaranteed US companies national treatment, ensuring that
taxes and licensing fees are no higher for American companies in Bulgaria
than domestic businesses.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
</DOC>
