<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Vice-chairman of Hong Kong exchange quits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN ELLIOTT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Philip Wong, first vice-chairman of Hong Kong's stock exchange council,
last night resigned from the council following a confrontation with the
colony's government and the Securities and Futures Commission which could
have undermined the international reputation of the exchange.
The confrontation centred on a now abandoned practice, which until 1987 gave
preferential allocations of share issues to members of the exchange's
council. But behind this there has been a row over stock exchange reforms
between the authorities and local brokers led by Mr Wong, who was expected
to become chairman of the council in October.
Mr Ronald Li, chairman until the world markets crash in 1987, was given a
four-year jail sentence last October because he accepted preferential share
allocations, believing them to be a reward for approving share listings.
Along with six other senior officials and advisers, he faces a further trial
later this year.
Mr Wong was a member of Mr Li's council but was not on the listing
committee. He has admitted in a letter to the exchange that he took
preferential allocations which he says were 'universally known and
implicitly approved by the regulatory authorities'.
Last week he was thwarted in a bid to reintroduce the practice when the
council overturned a decision it had made in his favour a week earlier. He
is believed to have launched the bid, which was almost certainly doomed to
failure, in an attempt to exonerate himself for receiving the allocations.
His defeat gave the issue wide publicity and precipitated yesterday's
resignation which had been informally requested by the government.
The problem has arisen because Hong Kong's Independent Commission Against
Corruption granted Mr Wong immunity from prosecution for receiving the
preferential allocations. It has been suggested he was granted this immunity
because he handed the ICAC crucial information regarding Mr Li in 1987.
But Mr Wong has denied that he reported Mr Li to the ICAC and is believed to
argue that he received immunity because, along with eight others involved in
the old exchange council, he agreed to government requests that he should
not stand in the 1988 council elections. He was subsequently elected and
rapidly became a vice-chairman.
He alleges that, following newspaper reports about the immunity, the
government and SFC built up a case against him and pushed for his
resignation because he was leading local brokers' opposition to stock
exchange reforms. The newspaper reports did not directly name him, but
hinted at his identity and said the immunity had been granted because he had
handed over the information.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1017</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEIBNAAQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910509
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / End of power struggle could be catalyst for reforms: Mr
Wong's departure could prove as significant for change as the 1987 crash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN ELLIOTT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RESIGNATION of Mr Philip Wong marks the end of an era for the Hong Kong
stock market. It might prove to be as significant a catalyst as the 1987
world markets crash, which temporarily closed the exchange and was followed
by the resignation and subsequent jailing on corruption charges of Mr Ronald
Li, then the exchange's chairman.
The significance is that the departure of Mr Wong - who was expected to
become chairman in October - could ease the way for reforms of the
exchange's structure and council aimed at reducing the power of small local
brokers. These brokers have regained control since 1988 when structural
changes were introduced and, led by Mr Wong, have been blocking the further
reforms aimed at underpinning Hong Kong's image as an internationally
important financial centre.
But Mr Wong's resignation has a wider importance because he is believed to
have been using the stock exchange as a stepping stone to other influential
posts elsewhere. He has links with Peking and is widely thought to have
ambitions for high office after 1997.
He has been expected to be elected to the Legislative Council in September
as the nominee of the pro-Peking Chinese Chamber of Commerce. Some
colleagues believe his real target is to be the first post-1997 chief
executive of the new Hong Kong government. Others say that this is shooting
too high, and rate him as part of an inner cabinet. Either way, Mr Wong has
been playing for high stakes and seems to have felt the need to clear his
name for partaking as a member of the pre-crash stock exchange council, in
the council members' then practice of receiving preferential share
allocations.
His unsuccessful attempt in the past two weeks to legalise the practice
appears in this context to have been an attempt to wipe the record clean,
rather than a serious attempt to reintroduce the practice and line his and
other council members' pockets.
In the securities markets Mr Wong is regarded as being a staunch defender of
local brokers against expatriate influence. He has thus used the old guard
of the stock exchange as a political constituency, first for his ambitions
to become the exchange chairman, and then to develop influence elsewhere. In
the past six days he has thrown two large dinners for more than 150 brokers
a time in order to canvass support for his cause.
At the peak of his influence, Mr Wong is believed to have controlled 380 to
390 votes out of 700 involved in stock exchange council elections, many
through proxies. Large international (mostly expatriate) brokers have been
progressively replaced by small brokers (mostly ethnic Chinese locals) in
the elections so that, according to officials, the council's 21 members now
represent only 8 per cent of the exchange's turnover compared with 34 per
cent in 1988.
This has led to led to accusations from officials of the colony's
expatriate-dominated watchdog, the Securities and Futures Commission, that
the stock exchange sees itself as a trade association protecting its
members' rights, rather than the interests of investors and the market. In
effect this is a toned down version of a criticism made after the 1987 crash
by an official inquiry which said that the old stock exchange committee was
an 'inside group that treated the exchange as a private club'.
One of the reforms which have been blocked is to change the exchange's
articles and end its limited company status which carries a profit-making
role. At present its members have a right to a share in its accumulated
surpluses of more than HKDollars 226m (Pounds 17m), built up from seat
purchases and transaction levies. It would become a publicly incorporated
non-profit making body.
At the same time about 150 non-trading members - who are believed to form
part of Mr Wong's vote bank - would be ousted. This issue has been fought
through the courts.
But the primary aim is to reconstitute the council to include listed
companies and institutional investors as well as larger international
brokers. Voting in council elections might also be weighted to take account
of a broker's turnover.
The SFC has pushed these reforms and led the attack on the old-style brokers
at the same time as it has been waging a separate battle with the stock
exchange and the Jardine Matheson Group over allegations of over-regulation
in listing rules and the rights of Hong Kong companies domiciled and listed
overseas. Together with the government it now hopes that the crisis over Mr
Wong will act as a catalyst for a consensus on the reforms.
The question now is whether Mr Wong's resignation will hinder this political
career. The pro-China chamber will have to decide whether he should be its
Legislative Council candidate. That could well depend on whether Peking
decides to continue to back him. It may take a line often heard in the past
and decide that he deserves support as the latest of a series of victims
attacked by Britain in order to keep control in Hong Kong out of ethnic
Chinese hands.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
