FT  09 MAY 91 / Argentine minister renews plea on inflation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BARHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUENOS AIRES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Domingo Cavallo, Argentina's economy minister, has renewed pleas for the
public to support the latest anti-inflation policy.
In a national broadcast on Tuesday evening, the minister acknowledged that
the campaign was President Carlos Menem's fourth assault on inflation since
taking office in 1989.
'The results this time can, and must be, very different. We are convinced
that we can and must inaugurate not months, but decades of stability and
growth,' Mr Cavallo said
In April he introduced Argentina's most coherent and stringent attack on
inflation yet. The results so far have been impressive; inflation fell to
5.5 per cent in April from 11 per cent in March, interest rates have
plummeted to 1.5 per cent a month, industry is booming and officials expect
2 per cent growth this year.
However, Mr Cavallo said stability could only be achieved by stamping out
tax evasion and by eliminating the budget deficit. Although tax revenues
increased in April by a third to Dollars 2bn (Pounds 1.17bn) over March's
Dollars 1.5bn, the government remains Dollars 200m in deficit.
