<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Family life at top of managers' agenda
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FAMILY life, education and the environment are the most important items on
the agenda of international managers, according to a survey of 12,000 men
and women in 25 countries to be published by the Harvard Business Review,
writes Simon Holberton.
Far from being breast-beating free traders, managers show themselves to be
economic chauvinists despite working for multinational companies. Managers
in several countries say they favour legislation supporting local interests,
although those in Japan display a stronger endorsement of free trade than
most.
Ms Rosabeth Moss Kanter, editor of the HBR and author of an article
analysing the survey, says: 'The ideal of a global village where a common
culture of management unifies business practice is still more a dream than a
reality.'
The typical senior manager, a male, is in his early 40s, married and
bilingual. He is employed by an established but private-owned company
employing several thousand people at home and abroad.
He is more concerned about customer service, product quality, workforce
skills and technology than he is about macroeconomic and political issues.
He is sure that trade rules, government policies, currency risks and capital
availability are neither significant success factors for his business nor
significant worries.
He is strongly in favour of work-site child care and is concerned about the
quality of education. He believes that business has a significant role to
play in improving education.
Transcending business boundaries: 12,000 world managers view change. HBR,
May-June 1991. Reprint No 91308. Fax Netherlands 31-3433-1910.
</TEXT>
