<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / CDU battler Volker Ruhe fights on many fronts: David Marsh
talks to the German party secretary who has his sights set on the Foreign
Ministry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DURING HIS frequent trips to east Germany, Mr Volker Ruhe, general secretary
of Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian Democratic Union (CDU), is regularly
addressed as 'Herr Generalsekretar' by devoutly respectful east Germans.
This anecdote illustrates the excessive respect for authority of Germans
east of the Elbe - and their difficulties in facing up to post-unity
economic upheaval forcing them take the initiative themselves.
'I have to tell them I am not Erich Honecker,' says the 48-year-old Mr Ruhe,
recalling the former Communist party general secretary who led East Germany
for 18 years before he was deposed in October 1989. 'They think everything
has to be decided by people at the top, and not by levels further down.'
Cajoling people in the former Communist state to come to terms with market
forces is just one of the battles the pugilistic Mr Ruhe has on his hands.
He also faces the task of rallying the party after recent defeats in
regional polls in Hesse and Rhineland-Palatinate, caused by disarray in the
Bonn coalition and the breaking of Mr Kohl's promise not to raise taxes to
pay for German unity.
Mr Ruhe has a front-line role in trying to soothe passions in the coalition,
where renewed squabbling has broken out with the CDU's Bavarian sister
party, the Christian Social Union (CSU) and the liberal Free Democrats
(FDP).
Finally, and most intriguingly, he has launched a campaign to raise the
CDU's profile in foreign affairs. Before he took over, in September 1989,
the Number 2 job in the CDU behind Mr Kohl, this was Mr Ruhe's main
specialty, built up during years on the international conference circuit.
In an interview on Tuesday, shortly before flying with Mr Kohl for a meeting
with CSU leaders in southern Germany to bury the hatchet after recent
recriminations, Mr Ruhe declared that he had no wish to engage in
'fratricide' with the Bavarians. But he highlighted the potential for strife
with the Free Democrats, who have held the Foreign Ministry portfolio for
22, and for three-quarters of this time in the hands of Mr Hans-Dietrich
Genscher, foreign minister since 1974.
'We have to reconquer the field of foreign affairs,' Mr Ruhe said. The clear
implication is that, when Mr Genscher eventually bows out, the CDU wants to
move in - and that the main candidate for the job will be Mr Ruhe himself.
'The Foreign Ministry is tied to the person of Genscher - but not the FDP,'
said Mr Ruhe. He pours barely-concealed scorn on the idea that Mr Jurgen
Mollemann, the live-wire FDP Economics minister, would eventually succeed Mr
Genscher.
Mr Ruhe has never made any secret of his ambition to become foreign
minister. But he is also prepared to be patient, saying he did not think he
would move to the job directly, but by a 'circuitous route'. He appears
likely to be brought into the government in the expected autumn cabinet
reshuffle, promised by Mr Kohl to put new people into key positions.
He has been tipped several times in the past to take the Defence Ministry
job, at present held by Mr Gerhard Stoltenberg. He views such a prospect as
a highly thankless task, but one which could launch him into the job he
really wants.
Under questioning, Mr Ruhe can also be encouraged to vent some spleen over
his own party. The Christian Democrats, he said, made 'a big mistake' before
the December general election in ruling out tax increases to cope with
unification - a pledge reneged on spectacularly by Mr Kohl three months ago
with one of the largest tax raising packages in German history. Defiantly,
he added that the FDP should take share the blame for its 'destructive role'
last year in adamantly refusing any question of an increase in taxation.
Mr Ruhe also criticised the government's initial lack of response to the
Gulf war in mid-January. 'We were caught wrong-footed.' Mr Genscher, he
said, was so preoccupied with his lobbying for lower taxes in east Germany
that the impression gained hold 'that there was no government at all.'
Mr Ruhe supports proposals for the Bundeswehr to be deployed outside the
Nato area in 'intervention forces' which could be operated with Britain and
France under the auspices of the Western European Union. This would be in
line with Germany's new responsibilities as a sovereign country.
However, he is against a hasty parliamentary decision on whether to amend
the constitution accordingly. In view of strong antipathy in the opposition
Social Democrats towards a wider role for the Bundeswehr, as well as
misgivings among parts of the FDP (including Mr Genscher), Mr Ruhe said: 'It
would be better to make no decision than a wrong decision.'
The country's chief task, he believes, is 'bringing about the internal unity
of Germany'. The financial expense of east German restructuring, he said, as
well as the psychological challenges associated with it, had been increased
by the speed with which the process was taking place. 'We underestimated the
extent of the change. Previously, we thought that living standards between
east and west would be equalised within 6-8 years - now we are talking about
2-3 years.'
Mr Ruhe, born in Hamburg, and with a strong affinity to the depressed region
of the east German Baltic coast, ranks as a forceful advocate of welding the
two halves of the country together again. But he can scarcely claim
foreknowledge of the speed at which it was going to happen. In October 1989,
a month before the breaching of the Berlin Wall, he forecast, somewhat
daringly at the time, that reunification would take place 'within a
generation'.
Now, he says, economic recovery in east Germany will have ironed out the
main social differences between east and west by 1994. Naturally enough, he
believes this will also enable the CDU to win the next general election, due
in that year: 'By 1994, I am sure we will have made the decisive steps.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
