<PROFILE>_AN-BEIBNAAFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910509
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Italy passes law banning insider trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ITALY'S politicians have passed a landmark law banning insider trading,
closing a loophole which has hindered the country's standing as a financial
centre, writes Haig Simonian in Milan.
The new law, which will take effect as soon as it is published in the
Official Gazette, has been under discussion for some years.
The new rules will be enforceable through a jail sentence of up to one year
and fines of up to L300m (Pounds 137,000). However, judges will have the
discretion to raise the financial penalty if necessary.
With the passage last December of landmark reforms for the stockbroking
system, the Italian authorities have now passed two of the three most
important pieces of outstanding financial market legislation. Discussion of
the third element - new rules governing takeover bids - continues in
parliament.
Italian bankers do not expect the new insider trading regime to have any
immediate effect on the Milan stock exchange. However, cynics have claimed
that it might severely impede a market which has a reputation for thriving
on rumour and privileged information.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
