<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 91 / Bonn threat to block Soviet housing finance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MARSH and LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN, MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BONN government yesterday threatened to block its financing of a housing
programme for returning Soviet troops after Moscow's decision to award the
first of the lucrative contracts to Turkish and Finnish companies.
Mr Klaus Beckmann, state secretary in the Economics Ministry, said Bonn
would withhold the earmarked funds unless Moscow agreed to review its
decision, announced on Tuesday.
The row over allocating some of the DM7.8bn (Pounds 2.6bn) Germany has
pledged for rehousing troops threatens to disrupt plans for the Soviet Union
to withdraw 350,000 soldiers from east Germany by the end of 1994.
The withdrawal plan, centre-piece of the accord under which Chancellor
Helmut Kohl won Moscow approval for German unity, is being financed through
DM12bn of Bonn government grants and a DM3bn interest-free loan.
Officials close to President Mikhail Gorbachev have hinted, in recent
contacts with politicians in Bonn, that the Soviet Union could be persuaded
to speed up the timetable by a year provided Germany agreed to put up more
than the DM12bn.
The DM7.8bn promised by the German government covers construction of 36,000
flats for soldiers returning from east Germany. Although tenders for the
projects were put for international bidding, the Bonn government expected
that German building concerns - including hard-pressed companies in east
Germany - would win the lion's share of the orders.
The first batch of contracts was to build 4,000 flats, including 3,000 this
year.
Soviet officials declined to name the companies that had won the orders,
saying the choice had not yet been cleared with Bonn. But they argued that
the Soviet Defence Ministry, which selected the companies after an
evaluation of the offers by German and Soviet consultants, was entitled to
the final say as the contracting party.
'If the German offers had been competitive economically, then there would
have been room for some favouritism,' said one official at
Soyuzvneshstroimport, the state organisation responsible for foreign
construction work. 'But the Turkish and Finnish firms know our market well
and they offered more favourable conditions.
'Since this is an international tender, we have to follow the rules of
international trade.'
</TEXT>
