<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1042</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEHBSAFNFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910508
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / London Stock Exchange: Saatchi stake reduced
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
VOLUME IN Saatchi &amp; Saatchi expanded as funds controlled by Lord Jacob
Rothschild cut their holding in the company. UBS Phillips &amp; Drew placed most
of the 75m shares sold by Lord Rothschild and said institutions applied for
more shares than were available.
The Seaq ticker showed 75m shares changing hands at 19p and another 66m at
19 1/4 p. Traders suggested the difference went at least partly to cover a
short position at UBS. Final turnover was 144m and the price eased  1/2 to
19 3/4 p.
Lord Rothschild previously held 20 per cent of the Saatchi Euroconvertibles.
In the company's rights issue, he opted not to take up the rights after
conversion, but instead to underwrite part of the issue at the rights price
of 10p a share. After the restructuring of Saatchi, Lord Rothschild held
nearly 9 per cent of Saatchi. This stake has now been reduced to around 4
per cent.
Rolls-Royce falls
Adverse US analysis on Rolls-Royce moved the stock against the market trend
yesterday. It closed 3 1/2 down at 163 1/2 p after relatively light turnover
of 1.9m shares. In New York, Goldman Sachs analyst Ms Judith L. Comeau
lowered her current year profits forecast to Pounds 175m, from Pounds 214m,
because of higher research and development (R&amp;D) costs and the lack of
recovery in the market for spares.
Her views surprised UK analysts, many of whom are beginning to wax more
positively over Rolls-Royce. They believe the spares market is showing signs
of recovery and that the group's business can support the rise in R&amp;D costs
associated with the massive development of the Trent engine.
Glaxo recovers
Glaxo recovered some of the ground lost in recent days as Kleinwort Benson
reiterated its buy recommendation on the stock.
Mr Ian White at Kleinwort said the latest independent survey data of doctors
showed that the first few months of sales of Glaxo's new asthma drug,
Serevent, had broken sales records for a UK drug launch. He estimated annual
sales of the drug, currently only approved in the UK, to reach Pounds 300m
to Pounds 400m by 1995.
Glaxo climbed 15 to close at the day's high of 1114p on good volume of 1.5m.
Wellcome rises
Wellcome continued last week's strong rise by advancing 25 to 617p. Turnover
was high for the stock at 2m.
Analysts said there could be good news on the company's Aids treatment
Retrovir revealed at an Aids conference next month in Florence, Italy.
Trials in the US are indicating that the drug's long-term efficacy - which
has been called into question in recent months - is improved when it is
mixed with another drug, DDC, made by Swiss-based Roche Holding. Such
combination therapy has been pinpointed for some time by bulls of the stock
as a means by which the revenue generating life of Retrovir might be
extended.
Lloyds Abbey down
The UBS Phillips &amp; Drew insurance team cited a number of reasons for
downgrading its current year profits forecast for Lloyds Abbey Life. The
latter's shares came under sustained pressure after the UBS move, closing 7
cheaper at 404p on turnover of 1.3m.
Mr Youssef Ziai, life sector specialist at UBS, said he cut his profits
estimate by 8.5 per cent to Pounds 357m. He gave three main reasons for the
reduction. First, the group was suffering from the same high level of
defaults and bad debts at its Bowmaker finance subsidiary that the division
had encountered in the last quarter of 1990; and the level of new lending at
Bowmaker was down. Second, Abbey Life's new business figures for the current
year were running some 10 per cent below those of last year.
Third, Mr Ziai said, the recovery in the housing market will be pushed back
into 1992 by the rising level of unemployment throughout the UK, and this
would adversely effect the group estate agency business.
The oil sector was enlivened by suggestions that the long-awaited sale of
Elf's 25 per cent stake in Enterprise Oil was about to be undertaken as part
of a deal with the UK group involving a joint purchase of Occidental's North
Sea oil and gas interests.
One of a number of market hints was that Enterprise was about to launch a
hefty rights issue to purchase the Elf stake. This would be part of a much
bigger swap deal that could also involve Enterprise exchanging a portion of
its Nelson oil field for other assets in what is seen by specialists as a
tax-efficient move by Enterprise.
There was considerable speculation that the Enterprise shares would be
bought back at 450p a share, plus a tax credit to allow for advance
corporation tax, which would add up to a total price of 600p a share.
Analysts said such a deal would remove the overhang of Elf's stake but that
a rights issue would inevitably prove unpopular in the short term.
Enterprise shares receded 6 to 557p.
BP eased marginally to 354p, unmoved by the possibility that it might report
its first-ever quarterly deficit tomorrow. 'A first-quarter loss has been in
the market since February,' said one analyst. Shell climbed 6 to 532p as
First Boston, the US investment bank, upgraded the stock.
Allied-Lyons put in one of the better performances of the day among Footsie
stocks in response to the confirmation of top management changes. The shares
rose 18 to 570p.
Printing ink maker Usher Walker jumped 42 to 283p as Mr David Williams,
deputy chairman of acquisitive mini-conglomerate Mosaic until last month,
took a 10.19 per cent stake in the company.
Tate &amp; Lyle rose 6 to 365p as Hoare Govett raised its current year forecast
by Pounds 5m to Pounds 232m. With Tate making 60 per cent of its profits in
US dollars, the US currency's recent strength will translate into higher
sterling profits. Strong interim figures are likely to be reported today and
the market is anticipating even larger upgrades than Hoare's. Analysts
expect Tate to announce half-time profits of Pounds 92.5m.
Booker added 5 at 482p as Nomura issued a buy recommendation which focused
on the company's move into food distribution and away from agribusiness
since its acquisition of Fitch Lovell and Linfood. United Biscuits dipped 4
to 381p as a broker was reported to have lowered its current year forecast
by Pounds 4.5m to Pounds 212m and next year's by Pounds 10.5m to Pounds
242m.
BAA put on 8 to 438p following reports it was planning to expand into the US
and also that it was attempting to bring Marks and Spencer into Heathrow
Airport. Analysts, however, said BAA's US involvement was likely to be
small, while it would be at least two years before Marks opened any stores
at Heathrow.
Brierley Investments advanced 7 to 44p on views that the company's financial
position had been secured. It has reduced debt by selling a 30 per cent
stake in Mount Charlotte Investments, the UK hotels group, to the Singapore
government.
Reports that the Office of Fair Trading had confirmed an investigation into
the affairs of Eurocopy, and that the company's consumer credit licence
could be threatened, lowered shares of the independent photocopier
distributor 8 to 88p.
A higher dividend distribution combined with a substantially increased net
asset valuation compensated for lower annual profits from Ropner. Both
classes of shares rose 5, the ordinary closing at 140p and the 'A' at 134p.
Smith &amp; Nephew improved 3 1/2 to 127p ahead of tomorrow's first-quarter
results. Profits are expected to be lower at around Pounds 27.5m, compared
with Pounds 30.7m, and analysts currently hold contrasting views on the
stock.
Aegis, Europe's biggest media buying group, climbed 20 to 213p after
announcing details of a refinancing package including a Pounds 30m placing,
at 260p a share, with a US investment house, and the Pounds 23.4m
acquisition of the remaining shares in TMD, a UK media buying business. TMD
jumped 93 to 340p.
The former also owed instalments of Aegis shares to the vendors of Carat, a
French media buying business bought last year. Two of these have been paid
off early, eliminating a perceived stock overhang. There is one instalment
left, due in December 1993 and which may be made in cash.
