<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / World Stock Markets (America): Weak treasury market causes
Dow to fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US EQUITIES followed bonds lower yesterday afternoon in the wake of the
first leg of the Treasury's quarterly refunding, writes Karen Zagor in New
York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average, which spent most of the day in a narrow
range in lethargic trading, fell 24.15 to 2,917.49. After fairly thin New
York SE volume of 153.3m shares, declining issues outscored advances by 840
to 720. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 lost 2.76 at 377.32.
Stock prices started losing ground in the late afternoon on the back of a
weak treasury market. Bond prices were depressed by the results of the
Treasury's Dollars 13.5bn sale of three-year notes in the first round of its
Dollars 37bn quarterly refunding. Demand for the three-year notes was not as
strong as expected and the treasury's benchmark long-bond, higher for most
of the day, showed a net fall of 5/16 at 95 7/8 , yielding 8.24 per cent, in
late trading.
NCR, which finally surrendered to AT&amp;T's hostile Dollars 110 a share offer,
eased Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 103 1/2 while AT&amp;T lost Dollars 1 to Dollars
36.
IBM retreated Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 102 after the computer manufacturer
said it would reduce the prices of its workstations by as much as 60 per
cent.
First Capital, an insurer 28 per cent owned by American Express, plunged
Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 1 1/8 amid concern about the lack of progress in its
rescue plans. American Express was off Dollars  1/4 at Dollars 25 1/8 .
American Waste dropped Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 7 3/4 in active trading
after PaineWebber lowered its earnings estimates for 1991 and 1992. Waste
Management and Browning Ferris, the two biggest waste companies, were down
Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 39 5/8 and unchanged at Dollars 28 5/8 .
Air Wisconsin Services, a commuter airline linked to United Airlines, forged
ahead Dollars 1 to Dollars 9 7/8 after an analyst at PaineWebber increased
his rating on the stock. UAL, parent of United Airlines, slipped Dollars
5/8 to Dollars 156 1/8 .
Walt Disney, which was added to the Dow Industrials this week and made a
strong contribution to Monday's 2.78 rise in the Dow index, receded Dollars
2 1/4 to Dollars 119 7/8 .
JC Penney, the department store group, put on Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 52 5/8
after an analyst at Kidder Peabody predicted improved same-store sales for
April.
The secondary market held up yesterday, with the Nasdaq composite 0.03
firmer at 491.51.
Thornapple Valley, an animal slaughterer, climbed Dollars 2 to Dollars 38 as
traders covered short positions. Although there was no news to fuel
yesterday's gain, about two weeks ago a brokerage firm issued a trading buy
on the stock on the basis of its low valuation and the company's earnings
growth potential.
Canada
A FIRM start for the Toronto market was reversed, leaving a slightly easier
close for the third consecutive trading day.
The composite index lost 8.8 on balance at 3,478.8, after touching 3,498.4.
Declines led rises by 299 to 249 after a moderate volume of 23.7m shares, up
from Monday's 15m.
George Weston, which fell CDollars 1 to CDollars 44, said it expects 1991
net to be about 20 per cent below 1990's results, after reporting
first-quarter net of 20 cents a share against 55 cents a year earlier.
Trimel jumped CDollars 1 1/8 to CDollars 6 3/4 . The company said it has
acquired 50.1 per cent of Swiss pharmaceutical firm Biovail for an
undisclosed price, with an option to buy the rest of the equity in two
years.
Stelco announced a reorganisation under which its two operating divisions
will be absorbed into the main company's organisation, and named Mr Robert
Milbourne president and chief operating officer. The 'A' shares gained
CDollars  5/8 to CDollars 7 3/8 and the preferred 'C' stock rose CDollars 1
to CDollars 8 3/4 .
