<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Commodities and Agriculture: Soviets and Jamaicans to meet
over bauxite shipping deadlock
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CANUTE JAMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KINGSTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAMAICAN and Soviet government representatives will begin negotiations later
this month to resolve problems which have bedevilled an agreement for the
island to ship bauxite for use in refineries in the USSR.
The agreement replaced a pact which expired last December, and committed
Jamaica to supplying 1m tonnes of ore annually over five years starting this
year.
Jamaican officials said that instead of taking the 250,000 tonnes of ore
which was scheduled in the first quarter of this year, the Soviets took only
30,000 tonnes. They said a deteriorating economic situation in the Soviet
Union was the cause of the breakdown of the agreement.
The USSR is paying Jamaica with hard currency for the bauxite, but the
island is committed to spending 25 per cent of its earnings from the deal to
purchase Soviet-made goods.
Soviet officials, however, have been unhappy with aspects of the earlier
agreement, and industry sources here say similar concerns are affecting the
new contract.
One representative of the trade ministry in Moscow recently described the
agreement as 'limited' in what it offered in trade between the two
countries. The Soviets have also expressed concern that the trade balance
has always been in Jamaica's favour.
The Jamaica Bauxite Institute, a state agency, reported that Jamaica's raw
ore exports of 1.1m tonnes in the first quarter of this year were 108,000
tonnes more than the corresponding period of last year.
'Shipments would have been better had we supplied the additional 220,000
tonnes to the Soviet Union as was expected under the contract,' the
institute said.
While seeking to repair the agreement with the Soviets, Jamaica, which is
the world's third largest bauxite producer after Australia and Guinea, has
secured another contract to supply ore.
Pechiney of France is purchasing 450,000 tonnes of ore from Jamaica, through
the Bauxite and Alumina Trading Company, a Jamaican state agency. The
Jamaican industry says the deal is worth more than Dollars 11m.
The government's effort to further expand bauxite production with the
reopening of some mines which were closed seven years ago has not been
successful.
The General Electric Company of the US had proposed reopening the mines
which were previously worked by a subsidiary of Reynolds Metals. The US
company had told the Jamaican government that it would produce and market
the ore, and use the profits to cover investments it planned to make in
electricity generating plants in the island.
Mr Carlton Davis, executive chairman of the Bauxite Institute, said this
week that the proposals for marketing the ore were 'too tenuous'.
The reopening and rehabilitation of the mines, and the power plant General
Electric had proposed, would have represented an investment of Dollars 275m
in the island.
Mr Davis said that the problems with the Soviet agreement should not affect
Jamaica's chances of achieving this year's production target of 11m tonnes.
The island's bauxite production last year was 10.92m tonnes, 1.27m tonnes
more than in 1989. Earnings of the industry last year were Dollars 714m,
Dollars 156m above 1989.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
