<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Commodities and Agriculture: Decrees to change Peruvian
agriculture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SALLY BOWEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LIMA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Alberto Fujimori has given Peruvian agriculture its biggest
shake-up in more than 20 years. Two supreme decrees are to change land
tenure legislation for the first time since the Velasco military
government's land reform law in 1969.
The new provisions allow for agricultural land to be transferred and sold
without restrictions and permits those who are not themselves farmers to own
land.
Workers in the cooperatives formed after the expropriation of vast sugar,
rice and cotton haciendas in the 1970s will now be able to elect to form a
limited liability company and to become shareholders, with the consequent
right to dispose of those shares. Limited liability companies had been
prohibited from land ownership.
In another departure from current law, land may now be used as collateral
against agricultural loans. The maximum area permitted has been raised to
1,000 hectares from the previous 150 top limit if the owner has installed
irrigation.
Federico Uranga, former Minster of Agriculture in the 1980-85 Belaunde
administration, praised the 'courage' of President Fujimori. 'He is doing
what the democratic governments which followed the military regime could not
or would not do,' he said.
The changes incorporate many of the demands of Peru's embryonic, but
potentially vast, agro-industrial sector. Principal peasant and small
farmers'organisations are opposing at least some of the measures. They argue
that land-owning by limited liability companies runs counter to the 1979
Constitution.
Some agricultural experts also fear that changes in the law may force
impoverished small farmers to sell out to agro-industrial businesses. Few,
however, disagree about the need to reform Peruvian agriculture. Production
of cotton, rice and sugar, once important exports, has slumped by about half
during the past two decades. Peru now imports hundreds of millions of
dollars a year in foodstuffs.
This year, the sector is in more acute crisis than ever. The 1990 harvest
was disastrously affected by the most severe drought on record. Farmers were
left with virtually no resources; seed potatoes were eaten up by the
half-starved, while livestock was slaughtered wholesale for lack of grazing.
The already decapitalised sector was harmed further by the arrival of the
Fujimori administration last July. Fiscal austerity measures meant that
indiscriminate monetary emission to finance cheap loans to farmers via the
state Agrarian Bank disappeared overnight. The vast majority of small
farmers, especially in the Andes and in the jungle, did not have the
collateral to obtain commercial credit.
This shows up in this season's figures. The Ministry of Agriculture says
that throughout Peru 91,000 hectares (225,000 acres) fewer had been planted
by March than at the same time last year. Almost all of this is accounted
for by diminished sowings of yellow corn, cotton and rice. There were also
more than 16,000 hectares (40,000 acres) fewer for wheat and barley than
last year. The only crop to register an increase in area planted was sorghum
 -almost 10,000 hectares more than 1990.
Ministry figures show that the coast has been worst affected, because of
water shortages. Crops in the jungle have been less affected.
It is not known, however, how much of the 'missing' 91,000 hectares has been
planted with short-term crops which ministry statistics do not measure.
Increased competition from imports is another threat. In March, the
government slashed import tariffs as part of general trade liberalisation
policy. Surcharges have since been placed on five key products - corn,
wheat, powdered milk, rice and sugar - to give local producers some
protection from dumping and 'unfair' competition from cheap imports.
The main problem, however, lies in the exchange rate. Peru's currency, the
inti, is overvalued, economists calculate, by between two and three times.
Local costs are disproportionately high. Producers calculate the farm-gate
price of yellow corn in Peru's jungle department of San Martin at Dollars
392 (with a 30 per cent profit margin). The imported equivalent costs
Dollars 186.
Of Peru's 7.6mn hectares of potential agricultural land, only about 2.7mn
are cultivated at present, according to estimates from Onern, the Peruvian
natural resources organisation.
The main hope for agricultural expansion is the coast and the jungle - the
Andes are already over-farmed. Peru's 52 coastal valleys, where the
agro-industrial take-off will come, provide the country's best agricultural
land. The desert soil needs irrigation to make it flower and that may cost
between Dollars 800 and Dollars 6,000 per hectare.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 32
