<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / International Company News: New charge card issued by
Deutsche Bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KATHARINE CAMPBELL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DEUTSCHE Bank, Germany's leading financial institution, is launching a new
plastic card in association with the German Tennis Association, in further
signs of new life being injected into the domestic bank card market.
While cash and cheques continue to be the Germans' preferred form of
payment, there have been some important developments recently, indicating
competition in the realm of bank cards is sharpening up.
Since the beginning of the year, the big German banks have begun issuing
their own Eurocard (Mastercard) products - hitherto the preserve of a
central issuing cartel - and some have started for the first time selling to
customers of other banks.
The cards, however, remain charge cards, with no revolving credit facility
other than any arrangement clients may have with the bank.
Deutsche Bank's first 'co-branding' agreement with the Tennis Association is
designed to give the bank, which services some 5m customers, access to a
wider field of perhaps 6m tennis players.
The card, a gold Eurocard costing DM140 (Dollars 79) a year, will be
marketed by the Tennis Association, and will carry the names of both
institutions.
Meanwhile, the German banks' recent surge of activity is putting established
card issuers on their toes. American Express, for instance, recently
announced that it would lower its annual fees for the green card to DM100
from DM140.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 28
</PAGE>
