<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / International Company News: ITT chief bullish on profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR RAND Araskog, whose compensation as chairman of ITT has been sharply
criticised because of the group's flat earnings, yesterday forecast that the
company would have stronger operating profits this year.
Mr Araskog, speaking in Leominster, Massachusetts, where the
hotels-to-insurance conglomerate held its annual meeting, did not elaborate.
In 1990, the group had operating profits of Dollars 1.11bn, excluding its
investment in the telecommunications equipment company Alcatel.
The largest public pension fund in the US, the California Public Employees
Retirement System, voted against re-election of the company's directors at
the meeting in protest against Mr Araskog's 1990 compensation. However, the
directors were overwhelmingly re-elected.
In a year when ITT's earnings rose 3.9 per cent, to Dollars 958m, and its
share price sank 18 per cent, Mr Araskog's cash compensation rose by about
50 per cent to Dollars 5.5m.
Mr Araskog's compensation has become a lightning rod for mounting US
shareholder concern over apparent disparities between generous executive pay
and poor corporate performance.
According to a recent survey by Business Week magazine, the average chief
executive's salary and bonus rose by 3.5 per cent last year, to Dollars
1.21m despite a 7 per cent drop in profits.
The Californian pension fund, which is taking a lead among institutional
investors on pay issues, said Mr Araskog did not deserve his pay rise
because the company's performance had been 'mediocre'. It calculated that
his pay over the past four years had been more than double the going rate
for chief executives of companies of a comparable size and performance.
But ITT replied that the board's compensation committee, which used outside
compensation consultants, felt the chairman's pay was entirely appropriate
in the light of his performance and accomplishments. Mr Araskog said
yesterday that the sum fairly reflected long-term performance.
</TEXT>
