<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / International Company News: Ericsson down 14% to SKr1bn for
quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ERICSSON, the Swedish telecommunications group, yesterday unveiled a 14 per
cent drop in pre-tax profits to SKr1.01bn (Dollars 163m) for the first
quarter of the year.
This is the first time since 1986 the company has suffered a decline, and it
comes after a period of strong growth. The latest quarterly figure compares
with SKr1.18bn for the same period last year.
The order book also fell, by 12 per cent, to SKr10.73bn from SKr12.19bn.
Consolidated net sales rose by only 2 per cent to Skr10.65bn, from
SKr10.41bn last time.
The company said profits for this year would be lower than those in 1990,
which were a record high of SKr4.85bn. It blamed continuing investment in
technological development and the effects of weak business conditions in
many of its key markets.
Ericsson said its decision to increase development costs in the public
telecommunications and mobile telephone sectors by SKr500m to around
SKr3.7bn in the first quarter contributed largely to the drop in profits.
The expenditure was in response to the move from analog to digital systems
in the US, Europe and Japan.
The small rise in net sales was due to 'the worldwide downturn in business
conditions', while the decline in order bookings resulted partly from 'the
unusually high volume of orders booked during the corresponding period of
1990, as well as delayed purchasing in 1991'.
However, Mr Lars Ramqvist, chief executive officer, said the level of
Ericsson's profits continued 'at a satisfactorily high level'.
He said the company was well placed for the 1990s, thanks to its high level
of expenditure in research and development and aggressive marketing.
There was a 2 per cent drop in first-quarter sales in the company's public
telecommunication business, to SKr5.26bn from SKr5.35bn. The radio
communications division pushed up sales to SKr2.87bn from SKr2.71bn, helped
by strong growth for mobile phones in the US.
