<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / International Company News: Holzstoff withdraws motion to
limit shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DULLFORCE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN ALLIANCE of foreign and Swiss pension funds yesterday scored the first
success against Swiss companies' restrictions on ownership of their shares.
At its annual meeting in Basle, the board of Holzstoff Holding withdrew a
motion that would have limited the number of registered shares which one
person or group could hold to 2 per cent of the total and voting rights to 5
per cent of the total.
This is the first occasion on which opposition from shareholders has
prevented a Swiss company from imposing shareholding limits since Nestle,
the foods group, opened its stock register to foreigners in 1988 but at the
same time restricted the number of shares an investor could hold.
Mr Alexander de Beer, a Zurich lawyer representing a UK pension fund, said
he hoped Holzstoff's decision would serve as a signal to other companies.
Earlier attempts by Swiss pension fund managers to block the imposition of
limits by such companies as Ciba-Geigy and Sandoz, the big chemical groups,
faded.
Both foreign and Swiss pension funds have built up stakes of more than 5 per
cent in Holzstoff, a rapidly diversifying paper manufacturing group with
substantial net assets.
They would have been partially disenfranchised had the board's proposal been
accepted yesterday.
Informal contacts between the pension funds led to agreement to vote against
the motion. The board, noting an unusually high 71 per cent of the voting
stock was represented at the shareholders' meeting and having apparently got
wind of the alliance, said it was withdrawing the restrictive proposal.
Under the existing statutes the board has the discretion to decide which
shares it will register.
The board said it wanted to wait for expected amendments to Swiss corporate
law and for developments in EC corporate rules before proposing new rules.
</TEXT>
