<PROFILE>_AN-BEHBSAE3FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910508
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Facing the realities of recession - The
fading fortunes of the hotel industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID CHURCHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IAN AND Diana Sykes are beginning to rue the day five years ago when they
bought the 12-bedroom Swan House country house hotel two-and-a-half miles
outside Stratford-on-Avon.
'It seemed a good idea at the time,' recalls 30-year-old Mr Sykes. 'Everyone
wanted to stay in a hotel in the country and the banks were only too willing
to lend us money to renovate the house from top to bottom.'
But the dream has turned sour. High interest rates, fewer Americans visitors
because of the weak dollar and Gulf crisis, and a dearth of weekenders
willing to enjoy short-breaks in the countryside has left the Sykes
desperately trying to sell up.
Two years ago their hotel was valued at Pounds 1m, but after several months
on the market at Pounds 700,000 Mr Sykes is contemplating a further price
cut to tempt buyers.
'It looks as if we shall have to sell our boat and our house if things don't
pick up soon,' he says.
The Sykes are not alone in their dilemma. Over 100 country house hotels are
estimated to have been put into receivership so far this year as a result of
the recession and slump in tourism. Many of these forced sales represent the
end of their owners' dreams.
'It was relatively easy for people in the 1980s to sell their town house and
buy a country hotel property and think they could become hoteliers as simply
as that,' says Mr Bruce Williamson, chief executive of Druce Hotels and
Leisure, the property agency which specialises in country houses.
'But the reality of the recession has brought home to many that it is not as
easy as it looks to survive the bad times as well as good,' he adds.
The slump in the country house hotel market is but a microcosm of the state
of the UK hotel industry in general. After years when the most pressing
concern for many British hoteliers was simply finding the best sites for
hotels to meet the burgeoning leisure and business demand, the downturn this
year has hit hard.
During the early part of this year, UK hotels - especially those in London -
saw their occupancy drop to their lowest ever level: down to 20 per cent in
many cases. Newly-opened hotels such as the refurbished Dorchester in Park
Lane were said to be hit even harder. Since then, both business and leisure
travel has picked up substantially, to about 60 per cent on average
occupancy in UK hotels.
But the outlook is far from buoyant: City analysts expect at least a 20 per
cent shortfall in overseas tourist numbers to Britain this summer. While
individual business travel is returning after the clampdown during the Gulf
war, some companies have decided to maintain a tight control on travel
expenses. Conference and incentive group travel, moreover, will take several
months, if not longer, to recover judging by the experience of the last
downturn in trade during the post-Libyan bombing scares in 1986.
'Of course occupancy levels in hotels are higher than they were in January
and February,' points out Mr Jonathan Bodlender, chairman of hotel
consultants Horwath Consulting. 'But they would be expected to pick up in
March and April. The question is, how far have they still to go to reach
last year's levels: I would think quite a way.'
Britain's top two hoteliers - Trusthouse Forte and Mount Charlotte Hotels -
recently made clear the impact of the war and recession on hoteliers. THF's
pre-tax profits fell 27 per cent to Pounds 190m for the year to end-January,
while those of Mount Charlotte stayed virtually static at Pounds 47.5m in
spite of a 55 per cent increase in turnover after acquiring Thistle Hotels
last year.
Only Queens Moat Houses, the third largest UK hotels operator, appears to
have shrugged off the gloom that has afflicted its rivals - its recent
pre-tax profits figures were some 51 per cent higher at Pounds 94.09m. But
this reflected the fact some 40 per cent of its hotel stock is based on the
continent where the impact of recession has been felt less.
THF's response will be unveiled today when it announces the long-awaited
restructuring of its 350 UK hotels, creating some five 'core' brands and
possibly changing its corporate identity to simply Forte.
'We want to emphasise our strengths and make people clearly aware of what
they can expect from our hotels under each brand name,' says Mr Rocco Forte,
THF's chief executive, who refuses to confirm or deny until today the
dropping the Trusthouse part of the THF name.
Under the THF restructuring, its hotels will be brought together under three
main brands: Travelodges, Post Houses, and Crest. Other hotels which do not
fit these three categories will be rebranded under such names as Heritage
Hotels, for country house properties, or Exclusive hotels. Those that fall
into none of these five categories will be sold. THF has already earmarked
some 32 hotels for sale - expected to raise over Pounds 100m - which do not
fit its new strategy.
It is a strategy honed to perfection over the past decade by US hotel chains
such as Marriott and Hyatt as well as Holiday Inn, now owned by the Bass
brewing group.
These hotel groups have increasingly realised that hotel guests are not one
homogeneous market: not only does the business executive during the week
become the leisure traveller at weekends but both business and leisure
travellers at all time want different types of accommodation.
French group Accor has identified such niche marketing more than any other
European hotel group and now has its growth strategy firmly targetted on the
UK.
In France it operates a multi-tier strategy: Sofitel hotels aimed at the
city centre luxury market; Novotel, three-star properties sited close to
airports and motorways; Ibis, two-star hotels for families; and Formula One
 -basic accommodation with shared facilities.
'We believe that the UK market is right for a similar segmented strategy,'
says Mr William Miller, Accor's UK chairman. Already Novotel and Ibis hotels
have been opened in the UK, with basic Formula One properties to be built
shortly.
But THF's decision to segment its hotel chain may not necessarily help it
out of the industry's present doldrums. 'Branding is no panacea,' says Mr
Paul Slattery, senior hotels analyst with stockbrokers Kleinwort Benson.
'Hotels in a branded portfolio may bear a family resemblance to each other,
but they are not and cannot be clones as is the case with consumer product
brands.'
THF's new brand strategy may seem far removed from the plight of Mr and Mrs
Sykes in Stratford-on-Avon. But not all country house hoteliers are feeling
the pinch.
The Lygon Arms, part of the Savoy Group and based in the Cotswold village of
Broadway, has been virtually full up with weekenders over the past month.
A combination of aggressive marketing and improved facilities - it recently
opened a Pounds 1.5m health complex and swimming pool - has kept the guests
coming, reports Mr Kirk Ritchie, the Lygon's managing director.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 23 Photograph (Omitted). Photograph Rocco Forte (left), chief
executive of THF, and Robert Peel, his counterpart at Mount Charlotte
(Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1063</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEHBSAE2FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910508
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Investors make waves over a sea of money: Kenneth Gooding
looks at growing impatience with Minorco, which is sitting on a Dollars
1.9bn cash hoard
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INVESTMENT community is beginning to lose patience with Minorco.
Eighteen months ago, the Luxembourg-quoted investment arm of the South
African mining house, Anglo American, promised to transform itself into a
world-class natural resources group using its Dollars 2.5bn (Pounds 1.47bn)
war chest.
Today the cash pile still amounts to Dollars 1.9bn.
Criticisms are being aimed at the group's apparent hesitancy to put its cash
to work, particularly its failure to pick up cheap companies last year when
share prices were depressed.
The let-down is more acute because of the excitement generated by Minorco's
unsuccessful hostile bid for Consolidated Gold Fields of the UK. Much of
Minorco's cash came from the sale of its stake in the target company to the
Hanson conglomerate in September, 1989.
Mr Rob Davies, analyst at Shearson Lehman Brothers, reflects a widespread
view when he says: 'We continue to have doubts about the ability of the
management to make acquisitions and to run operations successfully.'
Minorco's institutional investors are mainly in South Africa. Most UK
institutions are not interested. They have been put off by Minorco's South
African parentage and Luxembourg quote, in addition to the management's
performance.
One UK fund manager typified the prevailing lethargy when he said: 'I think
we still hold a few Minorco shares for tax reasons. But it wouldn't trouble
me if we didn't have them.'
Mr Tony Lea, one of the three 'young Turks' who, with Sir Michael Edwardes,
led the disastrous attack on Gold Fields, agrees that 'the jury must be out
until we are fully invested and people can see what this company has
become'.
But Mr Lea, now joint managing director, suggests that Minorco is 'motoring
along' towards its objective.
Its most spectacular move so far was to buy Freeport McMoRan Gold in March
last year for Dollars 705m.
The cost, representing 50 times historic earnings, always looked high and a
falling gold price since has not improved the perception. Low prices and
some technical problems saw the gold company, renamed Independence Mining,
do little better than break even in the half-year to December 30.
Some analysts suggest that Minorco paid a substantial premium partly because
it wanted to prove that the US was not 'off-limits'. The Gold Fields bid
foundered because of decisions by a New York judge. Consequently, it was
widely assumed that Minorco would face a court battle about its South
African parentage any time it attempted to buy in the US.
If Minorco had taken over Gold Fields, it intended to keep the North
American gold interests and the UK group's ARC aggregates operations.
In March Minorco broke into the aggregates market by agreeing to buy for
DM178m (Pounds 59.9m) Elbekies Muhlberg in what used to be east Germany,
together with the rights to 230m tonnes of sand and gravel on the River
Elbe.
Again, the price looks high. But Mr Roger Phillimore, Minorco's other joint
managing director, points out that research convinced the group that 'you
can make a lot of money from aggregates if you get the costs right'.
Minorco aims to be a big player in Europe 'so that we can play in a bigger
game - in joint ventures with other major companies, for example . . . East
Germany gave us the opportunity to get big very quickly - but with some
risk. It is a super asset, but we might have a rough time for a while
waiting for demand to come right.'
Another recent deal did not exactly fit the main strategic thrust. Minorco
paid Dollars 30m for 81 per cent of the loss-making Beralt Tin &amp; Wolfram in
Portugal, which operates Europe's only wolfram mine. This move was widely
seen as Anglo American reshuffling assets because the seller was Charter
Consolidated, a 36 per cent-owned associate of Minorco. But Mr Phillimore
insists the deal had strategic implications. It gives Minorco a foothold on
the Iberian Peninsula, which promises to become a highly active mining
region.
Minorco also intends to acquire a world-class base metals business. The
group already has a stake in base metals through its 56 per cent-owned
subsidiary, Inspiration Resources, which owns Hudson Bay Mining and Smelting
in Canada. Inspiration Resources is being reorganised by selling or closing
down all non-core assets, leaving just the Terra agricultural business in
the US and the Hudson Bay (Hudbay) group.
Analysts suggest this leaves the way clear for Terra to be sold and for
Minorco to take control of Hudbay. This company must invest CDollars 185m
(USDollars 160.8m) , including CDollars 50m on its smelter, to meet
stringent Canadian anti-pollution measures due to be introduced in 1994.
Inspiration would be hard pressed to finance the Hudbay project but Minorco
could afford it. 'We are paying a great deal of attention to Hudbay. There
is a big challenge there,' says Mr Lea. 'But Hudbay is not world class, by
any stretch of the imagination. And we want a world-class base metals
business.'
Changes at Inspiration Resources illustrate Minorco's approach to its
investments. Mr Phillimore says Minorco still intends either to take control
of assets or sell them off - 'but in our own time'.
'While we are waiting, we have been encouraging those assets to perform
better and become more valuable. We have encouraged them to focus on the
businesses they do best.'
Apart from Inspiration and Charter Consolidated, the quoted investments also
include Adobe Resources, a US oil and gas producer (49 per cent owned) and
Engelhard Corporation, a US speciality chemicals and precious metals group
(30 per cent).
Full control of Charter, however, would probably be politically impossible
unless Minorco sheds its Engelhard stake. Charter owns 38 per cent of
Johnson Matthey, the world's biggest platinum marketing group and
Engelhard's main competitor.
US anti-trust legislators would not countenance both these important
platinum marketeers being under the direct influence of Minorco and, thus,
Anglo American, which is a big platinum producer.
Meanwhile, interest on Minorco's cash hoard is providing about 80 per cent
of its net earnings which totalled Dollars 58m in the first half of the
current financial year and Dollars 784.4m in the previous 12 months.
The share price has languished at a discount to net asset value of between
20 and 30 per cent.
Why not simply give the money back to the shareholders? Mr Phillimore laughs
and says: 'That would require a degree of humility we don't have.'
</TEXT>
