FT  08 MAY 91 / G7 members consult about asking Gorbachev to summit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER, Diplomatic Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOVIET President Mikhail Gorbachev may attend the forthcoming economic
summit of the world's seven leading industrial nations in London if
consultations among them lead to a decision to invite him.
The possibility of inviting Mr Gorbachev as an observer to the G7 summit,
due to be held from July 15-17, was first mooted by Mrs Margaret Thatcher,
the former prime minister, at the previous summit of G7 leaders in Houston,
Texas, last year. It was decided then to leave the question open until
nearer the date.
Mr Gorbachev's presence would give him the opportunity to try to persuade
the participants - the US, Japan, Germany, France, Britain, Italy and Canada
 -that he is going ahead with his economic reform programme, in spite of all
the indications that it has foundered.
The final communique after the Houston summit stated that the Soviet Union
would stand a better chance of receiving western economic assistance if it
introduced a genuine market economic system.
Though it would be for Mr John Major, as prime minister of the host nation,
to issue an invitation for July, he could do so only if all his partners
agreed to such a step. No decision to this effect has yet been taken,
British officials said yesterday.
In Moscow Mr Vitaly Ignatenko, the president's spokesman, said Mr Gorbachev
would consider going if he was invited. Moscow has made it clear that it is
extremely anxious to persuade western businesses to invest in the Soviet
Union and has been disappointed with the response, particularly from British
companies. One of the main Soviet complaints has been that some western
governments will not provide the financial guarantees which would give
companies worried by Soviet the present climate of instability, in the
Soviet Union, the confidence to do business there.
The US in particular has been cool to increasing economic co-operation with
the Soviet Union because the demands of the Baltic states for independence
or greater autonomy have not been granted.
