<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Polly Peck aims to avoid break-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ADMINISTRATORS of Polly Peck International are to submit proposals to
continue operating the bulk of the fresh-fruit-to-electronics group as a
single entity at the long-awaited creditors' meeting later this month.
But they will propose selling certain 'non-essential affiliates' and, 'if
possible', existing investments in northern Cyprus and Turkey.
This seems to suggest that the administrators, who were appointed last
November, will try to soldier on without disposing of either Del Monte or
Sansui, Polly Peck's two flagship subsidiaries.
The summary proposals emerged from the text of a full-page advertisement,
aimed at the group's bondholders, which is being carried in today's Swiss
press.
A full list of proposals, together with a 20-page administrators' report,
should reach the group's approximately 100 banking and 28,000 commercial
creditors later today.
The proposals will be submitted to creditors in the form of a single
resolution on May 24.
Polly Peck has extensive fruit, electronics, leisure and packaging interests
in the Near and Middle East, which in 1989 contributed more than two-thirds
of the group's Pounds 161.4m in reported pre-tax profits.
However, administrators have been frustrated in their efforts to build up a
full financial picture of the group's activities in the region, and in
particular to track down interests worth Pounds 200m which the company said
were located in northern Cyprus.
It is not specified in the summary proposals which of the assets they
propose to sell. In March they said they hoped to float the Turkish and
Cypriot leisure subsidiaries on the Istanbul stock exchange.
The May 24 meeting will also see the appointment of a five-member creditors'
committee and a 10-member secondary committee. However, the latter will have
no formal powers.
The new proposals have been made public in the wake of a concerted and
puzzling buying spree of Polly Peck shares.
The buying spate has extended to Zurich, where Polly Peck is still quoted;
in London, the shares were suspended last September at 108p.
Mr Asil Nadir, the group's Turkish Cypriot chairman, has said that he knows
nothing about the buying spree.
