FT  08 MAY 91 / Observer: Golden goodbyes
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It must be a buy signal. Rob Weinberg, James Capel's gold mining guru and
number one in the Extel survey, is out of the door with no job to go to.
Along with the departure of Tom Butler, author of Samuel Montagu's respected
bullion review, Rhona O'Connell (ex-Shearson) and Mike Coulson (ex-County
NatWest), it means that London's role as a centre of research into the
yellow metal has just about disappeared.
Andy Smith of UBS-Phillips &amp; Drew is the last rated Extel analyst still
studying gold, and since Swiss banks are more interested in the stuff than
most, his job is probably safe for the moment. Research activity seems to be
gravitating towards the gold-producing countries of North America and
Australia.
With the prospect of South Africa being welcomed back into the international
business community, it all seems rather short sighted. London is still the
most active gold market, the main international clearing centre, and has a
central bank which understands gold. It badly needs someone to plug the
research gap.
If RTZ, the world's biggest mining finance house, will not take up the
golden research ball dropped by Hanson's Consolidated Gold Fields, perhaps
the London Bullion Market Association should.
