<DATE>910508
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Leading Article: Questions for the car makers
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE motor industry has pre-dictably huffed and puffed over a recent study
for the Monopolies and Mergers Commission which finds that some cars sell in
Britain for 50 per cent more than elsewhere in the European Community.
However, the MMC should not allow the car makers to side-track its
investigation by seeking simply to discredit the study or by arguing that
the car market is so complex as to frustrate attempts at exact price
comparisons.
Almost every recent independent survey has found wide discrepancies between
car prices in the UK and on the Continent. Such an accumulation of evidence
cannot just be dismissed as flawed or irrelevant. The onus is now on the
industry to demonstrate conclusively that substantial price differences do
not exist, or that they are due entirely to normal business costs. That
obligation is all the greater because UK and EC policies have long afforded
the industry special privileges. The MMC - and British consumers - need to
be satisfied that these are not being abused to distort competition.
The most obvious privilege is the block exemption of car distribution from
EC competition rules, which authorises manufacturers to sell exclusively
through designated dealers. Though the UK would need to seek European
Commission approval for any changes, the MMC findings are likely to carry
weight in Brussels, which is conducting its own review of the scheme.
Doubly dubious
The exemption was granted in response to industry arguments that cars
require expert maintenance which can only be assured if dealers enjoy
adequate profit margins and are answerable to manufacturers. But such
assertions are doubly dubious, given the reliability of modern cars and the
poor quality of much car servicing in the UK. Surveys by the Consumers'
Association have found standards to be no higher at franchised dealers than
at independent garages.
Nor have car makers themselves hesitated to bypass dealers when it suited
them. A recent study by the Retail Motor Industry Federation found that
about a fifth of all UK car sales were made directly to fleet buyers.
Discounts ranged up to 40 per cent - far higher than those offered to
individuals. The federation concludes that business users are being
subsidised by private buyers, who are denied the advantages of bulk
purchasing by the block exemption.
The distortion has been aggravated by tax concessions on company cars, which
have concentrated buying power in the hands of fleet operators. There is
also evidence that the scheme has restricted consumer choice. Mr Paul Tosch,
chairman of Vauxhall, acknowledged as much when he said last week that if
company car users had to pay for their vehicles themselves, they would buy
far more models from abroad. In effect, the scheme is a non-tariff barrier.
In the interests of a competitive market, the sooner the government removes
any residual subsidy to company cars, the better.
Third privilege
The third privilege enjoyed by the car industry is the 'gentleman's
agreement' limiting Japanese imports into the UK. The MMC has already
identified the restriction as a 'complex monopoly' but has yet to decide
whether it is harming consumers. However, a study for the National Consumer
Council has estimated that it adds as much as Pounds 2,000 to the price of
imported Japanese cars.
In any event, the 16-year-old restriction has long since outlived its
original purpose of sheltering the UK-owned car industry. It is curious, to
say the least, that a government which has so vigorously attacked trade
barriers in other fields should have continued to smile on this
protectionist relic. It is odder still that Whitehall is ready to have the
arrangement enshrined in the EC's planned restraints on Japanese cars.
The government showed courage in exposing the car industry to MMC scrutiny.
It needs to be prepared for the possibility that a really searching
investigation will uncover restrictive practices and market distortions
which will require as much firmness of purpose to eradicate.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
