<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Management: Why Chapter 11 does not tell quite the whole
story - Nikki Tait assesses the pros and cons of sending in the cavalry to
corporate casualties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
On a cold winter morning, the rust-belt town of Erie goes quietly about its
business. Only the local court seems abnormally active as flurries of
besuited lawyers hurtle up its steps.
Inside, a marathon session is getting under way. During the next 12 hours,
Judge Warren Bentz will hear how Wheeling-Pittsburgh, the nation's ninth
largest steelmaker, plans to haul itself out of Chapter 11 bankruptcy
proceedings. He will snap at lawyers who raise long-winded objections to a
package agreed between the company, its workers and major creditors. He will
return for an unscheduled weekend sitting. And finally, several weeks later,
he will sign an order which returns the company to the land of the living
after five and a half years in corporate purgatory.
This unwieldy, yet ultimately effective, proceeding could only occur in the
US. Had Wheeling-Pittsburgh been a British company, it would almost
certainly have gone into receivership in 1985, when slumping demand for
steel coupled with heavy debts taken on to fund modernisation crippled its
finances. Assets would have been sold off and the proceeds given to
creditors.
In the US, by contrast, the notion that corporate casualties should be
rehabilitated is deeply ingrained. As one bankruptcy lawyer puts it: 'Our
founding fathers wanted to start a new life, and that attitude is still at
the heart of the legislation.' Even the American Constitution makes
reference to bankruptcy laws.
Accordingly, the 'Chapter 11' process has developed. In essence, this allows
an ailing company to ask the courts for protection from its creditors while
it reorganises its affairs. If granted, such protection prevents a company's
assets being seized; allows a debtor to suspend certain interest and debt
repayments; permits the debtor to cancel certain contracts; and means that
suits against the debtor can only be pursued as a claim through the courts.
Creditors, meanwhile, organise their own 'committees', which in turn gain
access to information about the company's finances. The aim is to negotiate
an agreement which either repays creditors (in part or in full), or gives
them some stake in a revitalised company.
To UK eyes, this arrangement is usually viewed with envy; earlier this year,
for example, critics of the ILG collapse have claimed that the travel
company's demise was needlessly swift. Indeed, in the last overhaul of UK
bankruptcy legislation, the 1985 Insolvency Act introduced an
'administration' procedure modelled on Chapter 11, although its successful
use has been limited.
But from a US perspective, matters are not so simple. Thanks to the
corporate leveraging rife in the 1980s and to the recessionary climate of
the 1990s, bankruptcy has been a growth industry. Coupled with the demise of
the takeover business, top law firms - like Skadden, Arps - have been
beefing up their presence in this area.
So what are the pluses and minuses of the process? On the first score,
Chapter 11 can obviously work - preserving jobs, manufacturing capacity and
so on. Wheeling-Pittsburgh is a good example. Today, the company still
employs over 6,000 people, has annual sales of around Dollars 1bn, and
forecast profits of Dollars 32.5m after-tax for 1991 - although, given the
present climate in the steel industry, analysts' expectations are
significantly lower. Unsecured creditors, meanwhile, have been repaid 71
cents in the dollar.
True, the company sold off major facilities in Monessen, a small steel
community outside Pittsburgh, while in Chapter 11. Although these operations
were largely acquired by other steel manufacturers, the town wears a
depressed air.
But Wheeling-Pittsburgh itself boasts a newly-modernised facility at
Steubenville on the Ohio-West Virginia border, and has generally adjusted
production to higher value-added items. That, suggests Leonard Wise, who
chaired the company through the final throes of the Chapter 11 process,
could only be done under its protection. 'The cost of terminating Monessen
would have lead to defaults on existing debt anyway,' he says.
More generally, figures for the success rate of the process are hard to come
by. According to Dun &amp; Bradstreet, the financial information group, around
60,000 companies failed last year and about one-fifth entered Chapter 11,
but it does not track subsequent performance.
Academic studies are limited in their scope. One, conducted at Tulane
University, New Orleans, looked at American or New York Stock Exchange
companies which went bankrupt between 1979 and 1986, and had their cases
handled in seven major jurisdictions. There were 51 filings altogether, and
by mid-1989, 30 companies had been rehabilitated.
Chapter 11 is time-consuming and costly. Periods spent under this protection
vary enormously from company to company, but Wheeling's 69-month sojourn is
by no means a record. The Tulane study, for example, suggested that the
average time taken by the 30 firms to reorganise was two and a half years
and the longest over eight years.
This means that the direct costs attached to the process can mount and eat
into the debtor's estate.
It only takes a brief visit to a bankruptcy court to see why. At the first
Pan Am bankruptcy hearing, for example, at least five airlines were
represented. So were suppliers and lessors, like GE Capital. So were
government agencies, such as the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation. So
were unions, ranging from the airline pilots to the Teamsters.
Most of these organisations employed outside counsel and, as lawyers
announced their credentials, the packed courtroom listened to a roll-call of
New York's most prestigious law firms.
Generalising about costs - even if the indirect impact on the business of a
bankruptcy filing is ignored - is difficult. However, at least one study has
suggested that the direct expense of an 'average' Chapter 11 proceeding may
be ten times that of a debt restructuring conducted outside the courtroom.
Judges, aware of this criticism, have made some moves to cut back fees. Last
month, for example, a judge in the complex Southmark bankruptcy case chipped
Dollars 3m off the Dollars 54.2m demanded for work in the year-long
proceedings.
There is also much debate over whether, and how, the process can be
shortened. One major bone of contention is a provision which gives a debtor
the exclusive right to propose a plan of reorganisation for the first 120
days after a Chapter 11 filing. 'Exclusivity' can also be extended - and, in
the case of the Manville bankruptcy, the debtor succeeded in doing so ten
times. Only when this period ends can other parties make suggestions. Many
lawyers argue that a more restricted period of exclusivity would accelerate,
and enhance, the process.
But in reality, it is often down to a judge - like the one who dealt with
Wheeling - to keep matters on track. This can lead to some brutal bullying.
As claims in the Drexel bankruptcy rose to a ludicrous Dollars 20bn-plus,
for example, Judge Milton Pollack threatened to liquidate the investment
bank unless the lawyers pared their claims.
But here a second concern comes into play - namely, the extent of the
judge's discretion. Although the aim is a negotiated settlement, it is often
up to the judge to maintain the balance between debtor's and creditors'
interests.
This is no easy task, and a suspicion that courts bend towards the debtor is
widespread. The point was made forcibly in the case of Eastern Airlines.
Back in November, creditors were sufficiently alarmed at the rate of losses
made by the bankrupt carrier, to suggest that it should should be forced
into liquidation before all their money was lost. The judge decided
otherwise (supporting Eastern's management), but three months later, the
carrier grounded its fleet anyway. That decision may have cost the creditors
Dollars 135m.
Another difficult area concerns the extent to which claims can/should be
traded. At present, the situation is relatively permissive, and in practice
trade claims, as well as publicly quoted stocks, change hands. On the one
hand, this introduces practised 'bankruptcy investors' into the process. On
the other, it raises the question of how closely bankruptcies should be
monitored for possible 'insider trading'.
In Wheeling's case, for example, a group headed by New York-based
businessman, Ron LaBow, acquired most of the bank claims, making it the
principal secured creditor and, under the reorganisation scheme, the largest
single shareholder. This investor group then played a pivotal role in
pushing through a critical agreement between the company and its steel
unions.
While this may bring short-term advantages - such investors tend to be good
negotiators - it is questionable whether they always act in the long-term
interests of the company. Wheeling's 'rebirth' has been untimely in terms of
sector conditions, and Wise, a well-respected steel industry veteran, has
departed.
This leads on to the broader management question. When a company files for
Chapter 11, the incumbent directors are left in place - a clear contrast
with the UK's administration procedure, which introduces an independent
trustee.
Yet, in many cases, these are the very managers who have played a part in
the company's demise. It has been reckoned that only half the directors of a
financially distressed company are likely to stay with the business
throughout reorganisation. But the process of dislodging recalcitrant
executives often depends on the energy of the creditors' committee and the
leanings of the judge.
But perhaps the most fundamental worry about the process is that it keeps
ailing firms in business - and even offers them some additional operating
advantages. All too easily, the bankrupt company's need to chase cash flow
can produce business strategies which are detrimental to healthier
competitors.
This has been particularly noticeable in the airline industry. Eastern
Airlines, for example, drove down prices on some East Coast routes last
year. This, in turn, forced relatively successful rivals, like Delta, to
match such fares. Similar arguments could be made about the retail sector,
where distressed companies have exacerbated price-cutting.
At the end of the day, then, it is endlessly debatable whether the pluses of
Chapter 11 outweigh its minuses. But before European eyes glance jealously
at the American bankruptcy system, it might be wise to remember that
corporate rehabilitation does have its price.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 16 Illustration (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1079</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEHBSAEMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910508
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Jobs: The problem without any clear remedy - Britain's
middle classes have been taken aback by what they saw as favourable events
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOW'S about this for a snapshot of the times in Britain? A reader dwelling
in west London writes: 'My regular bridge evening this week brought together
four people all in their early 40s who have held down senior positions in
areas as diverse as market research, quantity surveying, investment banking
and financial control. We have presently one further thing in common: we are
all near to or in unemployment with families to support, mortgages and in
some cases school fees to meet.'
Yes, there can no longer be any doubt about it. In redoubled, the British
middle classes are feeling the squeeze.
Unemployment, which they hitherto regarded as largely a working-class
preserve, has proved upwardly mobile. And lest the Jobs column be accused of
finding amusement in others' misfortunes, it had better be known that I'm
fairly closely affected. Of my four sons and a foster son, aged between 25
and 35, two at the older end have seen their career paths disappear, and a
third has had to take a 20 per cent cut in salary.
As too often happens, I didn't twig the reality of the development until it
struck close to home, although I had long seen it coming. For instance, it
is well over a year since I heard the first of several chiefs of large
companies confiding that he was regretfully going to take an axe to the
group's middle ranks, where it was heavily overstaffed by the standards of
competitors abroad.
In which case, since overseas readers in executive and higher specialist
work have presumably gone through the fire before, they may think I'm making
undue fuss on behalf of the newly burned Brits. But, although it may seem
like special pleading, people raised in the central layers of society on the
Continent and in America are not quite the same as their counterparts over
here.
Since at least the 12th century, when master craftsmen such as architects
began to break free of the feudal yoke and sell their services for money, we
have been differentiating ourselves from the workers. With the exception of
agricultural small-holders, individual shopowners and such, we've
traditionally shunned physical hands-on activities, being employed as
traders, august professionals and more lately managers. Indeed - probably to
a worse extent than our equivalents elsewhere - whatever we have been
educated for, it is not to make things for sale.
Now, ironically, just as the collapse of east European regimes has confirmed
our assurance that Marxism was no threat to us, we stand menaced by
influences such as market forces and computers we'd thought were on our
side. But there is clearly no point in apportioning blame, let alone in
nostalgia. The fact seems to be that more and more of us will need to find
uncustomary ways of earning our keep, which is a problem even knottier than
it may at first appear.
I say that on the evidence of a survey of an activity being taken up by many
of the managers and staff specialists ejected from companies' ranks. It is
to continue doing broadly what they did beforehand as independent
consultants.
The study has just been published by the GMS consultancy, one of 10 concerns
in Britain that act as go-betweens on such independent operators' behalf.
One stark finding is that, during 1990, the number on the books of GMS alone
rose from a bit under 2,100 to over 3,100. The minimum, maximum and average
gross earnings of the 337 thereof who took part in the survey, are shown in
the table below.
Surprisingly, says GMS - with its eyes on the overall 1.1 per cent rise in
earnings over 1989 - the market for independent consultancy has held up
well. Even so, as the table's lower lines show, conditions for different
broad specialisms have been distinctly patchy, and that is not all.
The differences between individual consultants within the same specialism
are often huge, the survey report says. Even in the averagely depressed
fields of personnel, computers and general management, the most successful
people are doing extremely well.
Indeed, in the highest growth field of engineering as well as the others, a
few such exceptional operators hoist the averages to well above the earnings
of most folk involved. A lot are hard put to make enough to live. Moreover
for them, the remedy seems unlikely to lie in the optimism shown by their
1991 forecasts even if demand for their services picks up.
For GMS says it has often met upper rankers propelled or persuaded out of
company hierarches who 'thought that a move into independent consultancy was
going to be no different than life before. So many failed to make the
grade.' Worse still, to judge by other research evidence on such matters,
not only is doing something successfully on a self-employed basis different
from doing same on someone else's payroll, but a lot of us lack what it
takes to make the change.
While the Jobs column wishes it knew of a cure for such cases, even if only
for family reasons, it simply does not. And although numerous middle-class
Brits who have been caught unprepared - including the reader quoted at the
outset - seem to be looking to government for a remedy, I cannot share their
hopes.
All I can say, which doesn't help much, is that the ruling party would be
foolish to think it can survive the upwardly mobile upheaval unscathed.
Anyone who doubts it need only read Roy Lewis's and Angus (later Lord)
Maude's The English Middle Classes, published by Penguin in 1953.
It shows that its subjects have been through upheavals before. The last came
after 1945 when they found the Labour government they'd been instrumental in
electing, was citing the national interest in imposing sacrifices on them
that the working classes were not made to share.
The eventual result, even if not morally justified, was that the Labour
party remained out of power for 13 years. What's the betting that the
Tories, who've been in it for the past dozen, will soon be doing the same?
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 15 Table (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1080</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEHBSAELFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910508
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / FT Law Report: French judgment can be enforced in the UK
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RACHEL DAVIES, Barrister
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTERDESCO SA v NULLIFIRE LTD
Queen's Bench Division (Commercial Court): Mr Justice Phillips:
May 1 1991
A FOREIGN judgment given in a country which is party to the 1968
Jurisdiction and Judgments Convention can be registered in the UK despite
defence allegations that it was obtained by fraud, because the English court
will not re-investigate facts decided by the foreign court and, although it
can hear fresh evidence as to fraud, it will not do so if the foreign
jurisdiction has an appropriate remedy.
Mr Justice Phillips so held when dismissing an appeal by the defendants,
Nullifire Ltd, from Master Miller's order that a judgment obtained against
it by the plaintiffs, Interdesco SA, in the Cour d'Appel, Paris, on
September 27 1990, be registered in the High Court.
HIS LORDSHIP said that Interdesco were manufacturers of paint with special
fire protection properties. Their best-selling product was marketed as S60,
indicating that it gave protection for at least 60 minutes.
On January 13 1982, by a five-year agreement, Interdesco gave Nullifire
exclusive distribution rights in the UK and Ireland.
In mid-1985 Nullifire terminated the agreement. It claimed that S60 failed
to satisfy the UK standard for 60 minute paint and was therefore
unmarketable.
Interdesco denied this. They contended that Nullifire was acting pursuant to
a carefully-prepared plot to replace them and steal their market.
Before the Tribunal de Commerce de Paris Interdesco claimed damages for
wrongful termination. A crucial question was whether S60 satisfied the
contractual standard.
Interdesco relied on tests by the Centre Scientifique et Technique du
Batiment (CSTE), the testing institution agreed under the distribution
agreement.
Those tests supported Interdesco's case that the paint was up to standard.
Nullifire relied on earlier tests by the Warrington Research Centre and the
Fire Insurers' Research and Testing Organisation (Firto), to prove the paint
was sub-standard.
The Tribunal attached little weight to the English tests. It gave judgment
for Interdesco on January 21 1987. On June 15 1988 the Cour d'Appel de Paris
rejected an appeal by Nullifire and appointed an expert to assess damages.
The expert assessed damages at Ff7.4m, (Pounds .04) on the premise that but
for Nullifire's breach of contract, Interdesco would have been able to
continue to sell in the UK.
Under the relevant French appellate procedure, each party filed with the
Cour d'Appel a document described as 'conclusions', which was not evidence
but was a statement of the party's case similar to a pleading in English
law.
Nullifire's conclusions averred that, after the breach of contract,
Interdesco had attempted in vain to obtain certified approval of S60 in the
UK. Interdesco filed conclusions confirming that it had not attempted to
obtain certified approval in the UK.
On September 27 1990 the Cour d'Appel substantially upheld the Ff7.4m
assessment of damages.
On December 4 1990 Master Miller ordered that the September 27 judgment be
registered in the High Court pursuant to the Civil Jurisdiction and
Judgments Act 1982.
On March 26 1991 Nullifire instituted before the Cour d'Appel a form of
appellate procedure known as 'recours en revision', to set aside the
September 27 judgment on the ground that it was procured by fraud. The
procedure could be constituted any time after judgment, provided it was
initiated within two months of the appellant becoming aware of the facts
giving rise to his ground of appeal. If the recours en revision succeeded
the Cour would rehear the case on its merits.
Nullifire now appealed against Master Miller's registration order of
December 4.
Section 2 of the Act provided that the 1986 Convention on Jurisdiction and
Enforcement of Judgments in Civil and Commercial Matters was to have force
of law in the UK.
Article 27 of the Convention provided that a foreign judgment should not be
recognised 'if such recognition is contrary to public policy in the state in
which recognition is sought'.
Nullifire contended that recognition of the judgment was contrary to English
public policy because it was procured by fraud.
On recently obtained evidence it made out a prima facie case that
Interdesco's averments in their conclusions were calculated to mislead, even
if not literally untrue.
In Owens Bank v Bracco, FT April 12 1991 Lord Justice Parker said that where
an English judgment was attacked on grounds of fraud the court would not
permit the new action to proceed unless the plaintiff could put forward
fresh evidence discovered since the first trial, which could not have been
produced then with reasonable diligence, and which, had it been put forward,
would probably have resulted in a different conclusion.
In the case of a foreign judgment, he said, the judgment debtor could defend
himself by showing fraud even though the plea would involve retrial in the
UK of matters adjudicated by the foreign court. He held that was clearly
established in Abouloff (1882)10 QBD 259 and Vadala (1890) 25 QBD 310.
In Owens Bank the court was concerned with proceedings under section 9 of
the Administration of Justice Act 1920, where the same principles applied as
in an action on a foreign judgment at Common Law. The issue here was whether
Abouloff applied in a Convention case.
Article 29 of the Convention, under the heading 'Recognition', and article
34, under the heading 'enforcement', each provided 'Under no circumstances
may a foreign judgment be reviewed as to its substance'.
Where the foreign court had ruled on precisely the matters that a defendant
sought to raise when challenging its judgment on grounds of fraud, the
Convention precluded the court from reviewing the conclusion of the foreign
court.
Thus the rule in Abouloff could not, at least in its most extreme
formulation, be applied in a Convention case.
The question was what course should the court adopt where the defendant
sought to raise a fresh case or to rely on fresh evidence.
In the official reports on the Convention, Jenard commented that the public
policy ground for refusal of recognition in article 27(1) 'ought to operate
only in exceptional circumstances'.
Schlosser commented that to obtain a judgment by fraud could constitute an
offence against public policy. But, he said, the legal systems of all member
states provided redress for a judgment obtained by fraud, and the court in
the state addressed must therefore always ask itself whether breach of its
public policy still existed in view of the fact that proceedings for redress
could be lodged in the foreign court.
The English court should first consider whether a remedy lay in the foreign
jurisdiction. If so it would normally be appropriate to leave the defendant
to pursue his remedy in that jurisdiction.
It was not an area where rigid rules should be formulated. Estoppel
principles should be applied with care and a degree of flexibility to ensure
they accorded with rather than defeated the ends of justice - see Arnold v
National Westminster Bank, FT, April 30 1991.
Subject to that, the English court should not normally entertain a challenge
to a Convention judgment in circumstances where it would not permit a
challenge to an English judgment.
It was hard to see how the English court could reliably determine that
Interdesco's averment was instrumental in procuring the French judgment,
without re-trying the entire issue of measure of damages.
The proper course was to leave Nullifire to seek its remedy in the recours
en revision. The French court was plainly the best place to decide whether
there had been fraud.
Mr Hirst submitted the court had power under article 30 of the Convention,
to stay the proceedings until the result of the recours en revision was
known. Article 30 provided that a court might stay recognition proceedings
'if an ordinary appeal against the judgment has been lodged'.
In Industrial Diamond Supplies (1977) ECR 2175 the European Court ruled that
'ordinary appeal' within article 30 was an appeal 'the lodging of which is
bound . . . to a period which . . . starts to run by virtue of' the
judgment. The recours en revision could be instituted any time after
judgment. It was not 'an ordinary appeal'. The court had no power to stay
the proceedings.
The appeal was dismissed.
For Interdesco: Mark Cran QC (DJ Freeman &amp; Co).
For Nullifire: Jonathan Hirst QC, Michael Brooke and Susan Carr (Titmuss
Sainer &amp; Webb).
</TEXT>
