<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / UK News (Employment): MSF poll winner faces threat of
instant removal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WINNER of an election to head MSF, Britain's fifth-largest union, may be
removed from office two days after the declaration of the result next week,
Michael Smith writes.
The poll outcome is scheduled to be announced on Thursday of next week, but
a motion to be considered by the conference of the general technical union
on May 18 calls for the election to be declared null and void.
It has been proposed by the union's branch in St Pancras, London. Mr Roger
Lyons, assistant general secretary and one of the two candidates, is one of
its members. Supporters of Mr Lyons argued strongly for the election this
year of a general secretary-designate to succeed Mr Ken Gill, who retires in
August 1992.
Mr Gill, a standardbearer of the left in the trade union movement, opposed
the move, saying it was intended to undermine his position.
The union executive's decision to call the election in between annual
conferences last year and this year angered some members who believe the
timing should have been a conference decision.
In addition, the Commissioner for Trade Union Rights has indicated that the
election could be challenged legally on the ground that a general secretary
and his or her successor should not hold office together for more than six
months.
Mr Lyons' opponent in the election is Miss Barbara Switzer, another
assistant general secretary.
The St Pancras motion seeks to censure the executive for proceeding with the
election. It says: 'The conference is the proper place to take decisions of
this magnitude.'
Another motion, from Queen's University, Belfast, urges the conference to
ask Mr Gill to stand down immediately to allow a successor to take up the
reins. 'This would also avoid the possibility of any further legal action in
this area.'
The MSF said yesterday it had settled a pay dispute with more than 100
officers that led to a ban on overtime.
The settlement provides for 9.3 per cent rises, backdated to January 1. MSF
had originally offered 4.5 per cent. Negotiations are to take place on a
formula for determining future pay awards.
</TEXT>
