FT  08 MAY 91 / Parliament and Politics: Beckett pledges no increase in two
taxes - Finance Bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN INCOMING Labour Government would not increase corporation tax or capital
gains tax, the Commons was told last night.
Mrs Margaret Beckett, shadow chief secretary to the Treasury, denied any
intention to increase corporation tax,and Mr Nicholas Brown, another Labour
front bench spokesman, said there were no plans to increase the capital
gains tax.
Mr David Mellor, chief secretary to the Treasury, clashed repeatedly with
Mrs Beckett and her colleagues when he argued that Labour's public
expenditure commitments would inevitably involve higher taxation.
The exchanges dominated the start of the committee stage of the Finance
Bill, which gives legal effect to the March Budget.
Mr Mellor emphasised that in the run-up to the general election, ministers
would make known the results of a detailed analysis of the likely cost of
Labour's programme.
He argued that the closing off of areas like corporation tax provided
pointers to where increases would be imposed.
With support from the government benches, Mr Mellor contended that the
number of taxes which Labour was undertaking not to increase suggested that
'the poor old chap on the standard rate of income tax' would bear the main
brunt of the extra burden arising from its proposals for increasing public
expenditure.
Mr Brown held to his statement that there were no plans to increase the
capital gains tax when it was pointed out from the government side that
keeping the existing 40 per cent rate meant that it would not be aligned
with the 50 per cent rate of income tax Labour intended to impose on the
'top slice' of earnings.
Mr Mellor forecast that the coming to power of a Labour government and the
introduction of measures such as the abolition of the present Pounds 20,280
ceiling on national insurance contributions would result in the return of
the 'brain drain' as professional and skilled workers decided to leave
Britain.
Mr Chris Smith, another Labour front bench spokesman, highlighted the fact
that that when Labour left office in 1979, only 34 per cent of the gross
national product was taken in taxation by the Treasury compared with the
current 37 1/2 per cent.
A Labour amendment designed to 'target' proposed reductions in corporation
tax on the manufacturing sector instead of applying them to all sections of
business and commerce was defeated by a government majority of 95 (264-169).
The committee stage will be resumed later today.
</TEXT>
