<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Parliament and Politics: Borrie points to 'disarray' -
Takeover &amp; Merger Policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT IS TOO EARLY to judge the success or failure of the government's policy
on UK acquisitions by foreign state-controlled companies, Sir Gordon Borrie,
the Director-General of Fair Trading said yesterday.
Sir Gordon told the Commons Trade and Industry Committee investigation on
takeovers and mergers, however, that following the clearance by the
Monopolies and Mergers' Commission of the Pounds 300m acquisition by Elf
Aquitaine, the French state-controlled oil group, of the UK downstream
assets of Amoco last week, the so-called 'Lilley doctrine' was 'in some
disarray.'
Sir Gordon said since last July there had been a number of mergers which
qualified for referral to the MMC under the new policy. In six cases, Mr
Lilley had accepted the director-general's advice not to refer. In three
cases, Credit Lyonnais-Woodchester, Signet-Sligos and Elf Aquitaine-Amoco,
he had not taken the director-general's advice.
In two other cases, Kemira Oy-ICI and British Aerospace-Thomson CSF, there
were issues of competition involved which required investigation.
In the light of the MMC's clearance of four of these five mergers, Mr Lilley
would no doubt want to review his policy, Sir Gordon suggested.
It would be wrong for the director-general to stretch his independence to
include any matter which he personally thought should be referred, Sir
Gordon said.
</TEXT>
