<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Parliament and Politics: High ratings herald renewed
optimism - Scottish Tories gather for their 1991 conference
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PERTH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH Conservative party activist, looking ahead to her party's annual
conference which begins this afternoon, said: 'I expect we'll be a pretty
happy bunch.'
Scots Tories are always fairly happy when they get together, if only because
they can temporarily drop that wariness about expressing their views too
forthrightly which comes from being in a country where only 24 per cent of
the electorate voted Conservative at the last election.
Their happiness is increased by the knowledge that the party's standing in
the opinion polls in Scotland is now, according to System Three in the
Glasgow Herald, 27 per cent - one of its highest ratings since the early
1980s.
The fact that before Mrs Margaret Thatcher was replaced by Mr John Major the
party stood at 16 per cent tells its own story.
In recent months the Scottish party has done better in local government
by-elections than at any time since the 1970s. Mrs Thatcher herself helped
to heal divisions last autumn by removing Mr Michael Forsyth, the right-wing
Scottish Office minister, from his disastrous 14-month tenure of the
Scottish party chairmanship.
He was replaced by Lord Sanderson, a long-serving party dignitary.
Yet in Perth the party is having to swallow the planned replacement of the
community charge - introduced in response to the Scottish Tories' outrage at
the 1985 rating revaluation - by the property-based council tax.
It is also being asked by Mr Ian Lang, the Scottish secretary, to accept
that the creation of a Scottish legislative assembly is a 'fantasy' to which
few Scots attach much importance.
Cannily the party managers have shoved most of the controversy into the
first debate of this afternoon (many delegates do not usually arrive until
Thursday), discussing an anodyne motion on the funding, functions and
structure of local government.
Of the 33 motions submitted on finance, nearly half supported the principle
of the poll tax and none a property tax.
Mr Lang gave every sign of fighting in cabinet to preserve the community
charge in some form before accepting the council tax.
His protestations that this interpretation of his role is, as he put it in
an interview with the Financial Times 'a fantasy,' are politely disbelieved.
'The diehards are absolutely furious about the abandonment of the principle
of the poll tax,' says a prospective Tory candidate, 'and in places there've
been some resignations. But most see the greater cause (that of the party)
as more important.'
The idea of creating one tier of local government in Scotland instead of two
is popular with most Tories, provided it can be done in a way that preserves
existing pockets of Tory support.
But the debate will allow an opportunity to raise the issue of creating a
Scottish assembly, even if only to supervise those aspects of local
government that could, under reform, revert to the Scottish Office.
Mr Lang insists that local government and an assembly are unconnected, and
asserts his strong opposition to an assembly, especially one with
tax-raising powers. At the weekend, he dismissed opinion polls that showed
60 per cent of Tories and about 80 per cent of Scots favoured some kind of
assembly.
But in recent weeks there have been signs that the Conservative Party is
thinking again about devolution. Mr Struan Stevenson, Tory candidate for
Edinburgh South, argued for a strong assembly with power to levy all taxes
paid in Scotland.
Mr Lang said at the weekend Mr Stevenson's claim that demand for devolution
was an immovable force was 'absolute nonsense.'
Even if devolution is only raised in passing on the floor of the conference
hall it will come up in fringe meetings, with the Scottish Young
Conservatives strongly against and the Scottish Tory Reform Group gently in
favour.
</TEXT>
