<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Banks are left impaled on the town hall railings: David
Lascelles and Richard Evans on the government's decision not to act over
local-authority swaps
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES and RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government faced a tricky decision over the local-authority swaps
affair. Its intention, announced yesterday, to do nothing about it angered
many more people than it pleased.
Swaps enable two borrowers to improve their financial management by
exchanging debt service payments.
Mr Michael Heseltine, the environment secretary, could have introduced
retroactive legislation to legalise billions of pounds' worth of swaps
contracts entered into by local authorities but ruled by the House of Lords
to be illegal.
The advantage of doing so would have been to regularise numerous complex
financial deals and save the banks involved from heavy losses. Mr Heseltine
would have placated a powerful banking lobby and heeded the advice of the
Bank of England, which is worried about the damage the affair is doing to
the City of London's reputation.
The arguments against that were also powerful. Governments do not like
retrospective legislation, particularly to validate something the courts
have declared illegal. Although new laws would legitimise many deals entered
into in good faith by banks and authorities, it would do the same for
councils such as Hammersmith and Fulham, which has been described in court
as a gambler.
It was also far from certain, as the government saw it, that the banks were
quite the innocent victims of the affair that they claimed to be. There are
doubts as to whether they heeded warnings from legal experts or checked that
local authorities had empowered officials to sign swaps contracts. By acting
to straighten out the matter, the government might also reinforce the
impression that it stood behind local authorities - which it does not.
The immediate losers from the decision are the 80 banks that arranged the
swaps and must cancel them and bear losses estimated at Pounds 550m.
One factor that weighed in Mr Heseltine's decision was the calculation that
banks' actual losses will be as little as half of that. They will still be
able to obtain via restitution proceedings up to Pounds 125m that they have
paid over to the local authorities under the swaps contracts. Of the
remaining Pounds 425m loss, more than a third will be set against their
corporation tax bill.
Most of the 130 local authorities involved may also lose by the decision
because they now have the prospect of lengthy litigation with the banks -
and the worry that relations in general with the financial community will
continue to be soured.
One exception is Hammersmith and Fulham, which welcomed the decision as 'a
clear and definitive statement from the government that it will now be left
to the parties to resolve the matter between themselves.'
Mr Ian Ward, a finance expert at the Association of District Councils, said
the decision was unhappy for local authorities as well as bankers because
most deals would now have to go to court to be resolved. As every deal was
slightly different, it was bound to be a lengthy process.
Mr Ward said local authorities were also uncertain about whether they had
the power to enter into a compromise agreement with the banks, and that had
not been resolved in any way by the government. The asociation had been
seeking not only validation of the deals that had been done, but permission
for swaps to be entered into in a properly controlled treasury operation.
Similarly, the attitude of the Association of Metropolitan Authorities was
that there should be full validation of past deals. Mr Keith Beaumont of the
AMA said it was now very likely that there would be extensive litigation and
that might compromise the financial standing of local authorities.
Only in the longer term will it become clear whether the affair has done
lasting damage to the City, as has been claimed by Sir Jeremy Morse and Sir
Martin Jacomb, the chairmen of the City's two biggest lobby groups,
representing the clearing banks and the merchant banks.
Their main worry was that many foreign banks faced losses and that the
affair exposed possible weaknesses in the City's legal underpinnings.
The government's view was that whatever damage had been done was very
localised, and there is little evidence of business leaving London.
Still unresolved is whether the government should legislate to enable local
authorities to engage in swaps in future. Mr John Maples, the Economic
Secretary at the Treasury, said there were no plans to do so, and it was not
clear that that would be desirable. But the Treasury would listen to
proposals.
</TEXT>
