<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Ulster talks fail to find venue for Dublin input
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELFAST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PROGRESS on Northern Ireland's future ran aground yesterday when the
province's political leaders again failed to agree on where talks involving
the Irish government should take place.
Unionist and nationalist leaders met Mr Peter Brooke, Northern Ireland
secretary, for more than six hours of bilateral meetings at the Stormont
parliament buildings in Belfast.
The planned 'round table' discussions have been delayed until later today at
the earliest.
Mr Brooke wanted 11 weeks of talks, but one week has already passed with no
agreement on the venue for the second strand of talks, when the Dublin
government joins in the discussions.
The location is regarded as symbolic by all sides and the political leaders
are anxious not to be seen by their respective grassroots supporters as
giving way.
The fact that there has been no agreement on compromise locations shows how
deep divisions run.
Mr Addie Morrow of the Alliance party delegation said: 'It has been a
frustrating day.' The Irish government wants the talks to be held in
Ireland, either in the Republic or Northern Ireland.
Unionists insist that the talks should be held elsewhere, preferably London,
because of the republic's constitutional claim on the north and perhaps
because they fear protests from their supporters about the fact that
negotiations with Dublin are taking place. Unionist leaders prefer London.
Compromise locations in Europe - such as Strasbourg - would present travel
difficulties. Mr John Taylor, Ulster Unionist MP for Strangford, said: 'Once
you get to Strasbourg it is like house imprisonment. It is impossible to get
out. There are no flights from Belfast and no flights from Dublin.'
Mr Brooke and Mr Gerry Collins, Irish foreign minister, thought the
difficulty was small-scale when they met in London two weeks ago.
The location of the third and final strand of the talks - to consider a
replacement for the 1985 Anglo-Irish agreement - has not been decided yet.
</TEXT>
