<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / The Blue Arrow Trial: County sought to avoid disclosure,
court told - Court Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COUNTY NATWEST wanted to avoid disclosing in its year-end accounts the Blue
Arrow holdings taken by advisers to the 1987 rights issue because of the
stock market's ignorance of these holdings, the Blue Arrow trial was told
yesterday.
Mr James Riddell, a former County financial control director, agreed with Mr
Nicholas Purnell, QC, prosecuting, that disclosure of the holdings taken in
the September issue was the one thing everyone had tried to avoid.
He agreed there was no alternative to the eventual disclosure of a 9.8 per
cent holding made on December 17. The losses suffered in the stock market
crash had to appear in some form in County's results.
Mr Riddell was cross-examined by Mr Roy Amlot, QC, for Mr Alan Keat, a
solicitor with Travers Smith Braithwaite who advised County, over
discussions between the two men on the presentation of the losses in
County's accounts.
Mr Riddell agreed Mr Keat had expressed concern over a number of options
being considered. Mr Keat had warned him disclosure would be necessary if
some options were followed. If NatWest acquired the holdings of both County
and County NatWest Securities, the aggregation rules of the Companies Act
would apply.
He said Mr Keat had advised him that, if NatWest gave CNWS a guarantee
against losses on its holding, that would put into doubt the market makers'
exemption from disclosure. He had said the written indemnity given to UBS
Phillips &amp; Drew for its holding could not be extended because that would
undermine its market makers' exemption.
Mr Riddell said that Mr Keat had also expressed concern over the favoured
option of transferring the stake held by County's corporate advisory
division to the parent bank as a long-term trade investment. Mr Keat had
advised that that depended on the intentions of NWB's directors and had
agreed with Ernst and Whinney, the auditors, that such an option was not
possible.
He had considered Mr Keat's advice to have been honest throughout, Mr
Riddell agreed
County NatWest, NatWest Investment Bank, UBS Phillips &amp; Drew Securities and
seven individuals deny conspiring to mislead the markets over the outcome of
the Pounds 837m rights issue. The trial continues today.
</TEXT>
